{"title_page": "Princess Fiona", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|Fictional character in the Shrek franchise}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #00663A\n| name               = Princess Fiona\n| series             = [[Shrek (film series)|Shrek]]\n| image              = {{nowrap|[[File:Princess Fiona.png|130px]][[File:PrincessFionaHuman.jpg|160px]]}}\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = Fiona as an Ogre (left) and as a Human (right)\n| first              = ''[[Shrek]]'' (2001)\n| creator            = [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]]<br>[[Terry Rossio]]<br> [[Joe Stillman]] <br> [[Roger S. H. Schulman]]\n| voice              = [[Cameron Diaz]] (2001\u20132010)<br />[[Holly Fields]] (singing voice and merchandise)\n| species            = [[Ogre]] <br> [[Human]] (formerly)\n| status             = [[Deceased]]\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = [[Princess]]\n| family             = [[King Harold (Shrek)|King Harold]] (deceased father)<br>[[Queen Lillian]] (mother)<br>[[Arthur Pendragon (Shrek)|Arthur Pendragon]] (cousin)\n| spouse             = [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]]\n| children           = [[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|Felicia]] (daughter)<br>[[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|Fergus]] (son)<br>[[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|Farkle]] (son)\n}}\n'''Princess Fiona'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/shrek/cast/134500/|title=Shrek \u2013 Cast & Crew|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TV Guide]]|id=The character is officially credited as \"Princess Fiona\", as opposed to simply \"Fiona\".|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918230927/https://www.tvguide.com/movies/shrek/cast/134500/|archive-date=September 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8a5b3173|title=Shrek 2 (2004)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[British Film Institute]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Has a fat throbbing cat she a baddie period ' ''[[Shrek (franchise)|Shrek]]'' franchise, first appearing in the [[Animated film|animated]] film ''[[Shrek]]'' (2001). One of the film series' main characters, Fiona is introduced as a beautiful princess placed under a curse that transforms her into an ogre at night. She is initially determined to break the enchantment by kissing a prince, only to meet and fall in love with [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]], an ogre, instead. The character's origins and relationships with other characters are further explored in subsequent films; she introduces her new husband Shrek to her parents in ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004), becomes a mother by ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), and is an empowered warrior in ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010), much of which takes place in an [[Multiverse|alternate reality]] in which Fiona and Shrek never meet.\n\nCreated by screenwriters [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] and [[Terry Rossio]], Fiona is loosely based on the unsightly princess in [[William Steig]]'s children's book ''[[Shrek!]]'' (1990), from which her role and appearance were significantly modified. The screenwriters adapted the character into a princess under a [[shapeshifting]] enchantment, an idea that was initially greatly contested by other filmmakers. Fiona is voiced by actress [[Cameron Diaz]]. Comedian and actress [[Janeane Garofalo]] was originally cast as the character until she was fired from the first film with little explanation. Fiona was one of the first human characters to have a lead role in a [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] film, thus the animators aspired to make her both beautiful and realistic in appearance. However, an early [[test screening]] resulted in children reacting negatively towards the character's [[Uncanny valley|uncanny realism]], prompting the animators to re-design Fiona into a more stylized, cartoonish heroine. Several revolutionary achievements in computer animation were applied to the character to render convincing skin, hair, clothing and lighting.\n\nThe character is considered a [[parody]] of traditional princesses in both fairy tales and [[Disney Princess|animated Disney films]]. Reception towards Fiona has been mostly positive, with critics commending her characterization, [[martial arts]] prowess and Diaz's performance. However, reviewers were divided over the character's human design, some of whom were impressed by her technological innovations, while others found her realism unsettling and too similar to Diaz. Several media publications consider Fiona a feminist icon, crediting her with subverting princess and gender stereotypes by embracing her flaws. Diaz also became one of Hollywood's highest-paid actresses due to her role in the ''Shrek'' franchise, earning $3 million for her performance in the first film and upwards of $10 million for each sequel.\n\n== Development ==\n\n=== Creation and writing ===\n\n''Shrek'' is loosely based on [[William Steig]]'s [[Children\u2019s book|children's book]] ''[[Shrek!]]'' (1990),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.decentfilms.com/reviews/shrek|title=Shrek (2001)|date=2001|website=Decent Films|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116131854/http://www.decentfilms.com/reviews/shrek|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> but significantly deviates from its [[source material]], particularly pertaining to its main characters.<ref name=\":17\" /> In Steig's story, a witch [[Prediction|foretells]] that Shrek will marry an unnamed princess, who she describes as uglier in appearance than Shrek himself, enticing the ogre to seek her.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tor.com/2010/02/02/introducing-the-original-shrek/|title=Introducing the Original Shrek!|last=Potter|first=Beth|date=February 2, 2010|website=[[Tor.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919171954/https://www.tor.com/2010/02/02/introducing-the-original-shrek/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Described as \"the most stunningly ugly princess on the surface of the planet\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/556154/how-shrek-went-from-worlds-biggest-animated-franchise-internets-creepiest-meme|title=How Shrek went from the world's biggest animated franchise to the internet's creepiest meme|last=Meslow|first=Scott|date=May 21, 2015|website=[[The Week]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414101453/https://theweek.com/articles/556154/how-shrek-went-from-worlds-biggest-animated-franchise-internets-creepiest-meme|archive-date=April 14, 2019|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Steig's princess bears little resemblance to Fiona, but the two characters are immediately attracted to each other and wed with little [[Conflict (narrative)|conflict]].<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" /> Animation historian [[Maureen Furniss]], writing for [[Animation World Network]], identified the fact that Shrek's [[love interest]] is altered from \"a really ugly woman\" into a beautiful princess as the film's most significant modification.<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/shrek-something-old-something-new|title=Shrek: Something Old, Something New|last=Furniss|first=Maureen|authorlink=Maureen Furniss|date=May 31, 2001|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726031123/https://www.awn.com/animationworld/shrek-something-old-something-new|archive-date=July 26, 2019|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> In an effort to expand the plot while making its characters more visually appealing and [[marketable]] \"from a Hollywood\" perspective, the writers decided to adapt ''Shrek!''<nowiki/>'s princess into a beautiful maiden who has been cursed to become ugly only during evenings, which she is forced to conceal from the film's other characters, thus providing \"narrative motivation for not showing her ogre manifestation.\"<ref name=\":17\" /> Furthermore, Furniss observed that [[Lord Farquaad]]'s romantic interest in Fiona is more practical since he is vain and only attracted to her beauty, while his main motivation remains to marry a princess so that he can rule Duloc.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nFeeling that her curse remaining undiscovered until the end was unsuitable for a feature-length film, screenwriters [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] and [[Terry Rossio]] introduced the concept of a [[shapeshifting]] princess, which was rejected by the other filmmakers for six months because they found it \"too complex\" for a fairy tale.<ref name=\":60\">{{cite web|url=https://creativescreenwriting.com/shrek/|title=Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio on Shrek|last=Shewman|first=Den|last2=Ryfle|first2=Steve|date=June 9, 2016|website=Creative Screenwriting|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905220452/https://creativescreenwriting.com/shrek/|archive-date=September 5, 2017|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> Elliot and Rossio contested that similar ideas had been used successfully in Disney's ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989) and ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (1991), ultimately convincing the studio by referring to Fiona as an enchanted princess instead.<ref name=\":60\" /> Some writers expressed concerns over whether turning Fiona into an ogre full-time once she professes her love for Shrek suggested \"that ugly people belong with ugly people.\"<ref name=\":60\" /> Rossio explained that since Fiona shape-shifts, the best moral is \"'Even princesses who change their shapes can find love too.' And Shrek would love her in all of her varied forms.\"<ref name=\":60\" /> Elliot elaborated that this prompts audiences to debate if Fiona's \"true form\" is beautiful or unattractive: \"Her true form is beautiful by day, ugly by night.' ... and she was trying to rid herself of part of who she truly was, because society maintained that was wrong.\"<ref name=\":60\" /> The studio ultimately conceded that Fiona remain an ogre, which Elliot considers to be \"a more conventional idea\".<ref name=\":60\" /> \n\nIn early drafts of the script, Fiona is born an ogre to human parents, who lock her in a tower to conceal the true nature of their daughter's appearance,<ref name=\":28\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/19/31.aspx|title=Recycling, \"Shrek\" style|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=May 18, 2004|website=Jim Hill Media|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010164842/http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/19/31.aspx|archive-date=October 10, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> lying to the kingdom that she is a beautiful princess.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/shrek-dreamworks-behind-scenes-hidden-trivia/|title=26 Crazy Revelations Behind The Making Of Shrek|last=Kurland|first=Daniel|date=July 15, 2018|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018040320/https://screenrant.com/shrek-dreamworks-behind-scenes-hidden-trivia/|archive-date=October 18, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> One day, Fiona escapes and seeks assistance from a witch named Dama Fortuna, who offers her a choice between two potions: one will turn the princess beautiful, while the other guarantees Fiona's happily ever after.<ref name=\":28\" /> Fiona ignorantly drinks the \"Beauty\" potion for which she does not realize there is a [[Fine print|catch]],<ref name=\":28\" /> as the potion renders her human during the day only to revert her to an ogre every night.<ref name=\":12\" /> The writers originally intended for Fiona's [[backstory]] to be fully animated and used as the film's [[prologue]], but discarded the idea after [[Test audience|test audiences]] deemed it too depressing.<ref name=\":28\" /> Entitled \"Fiona's Prologue\", the sequence was [[Storyboard|storyboarded]] but never animated.<ref name=\":29\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/345217/Shrek/notes.html|title=Shrek (2001) \u2013 Notes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TCM.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010190649/http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/345217/Shrek/notes.html|archive-date=October 10, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> A second abandoned scene entitled \"Fiona Gets Them Lost\" follows Fiona, Shrek and [[Donkey (Shrek)|Donkey]] after she is and they become trapped in a cave; an action sequence inspired by the film ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' (1984) ensues.<ref name=\":29\" /> In the writers' original draft, Fiona's monstrous form was to have a physical altercation reminiscent of [[Hong Kong action films]] with Shrek once he discovers her, assuming that the monster has harmed Fiona.<ref name=\":60\" /> The idea was abandoned because, according to Elliot, few were familiar [[Hong Kong Cinema|Hong Kong cinema]]'s \"emphasis on action and physicality\" in comparison to more violent American films, explaining, \"no matter how much we described it, [the studio] ... imagined this violent, knock-down, [[Steven Seagal|Steven Segal]]-type, bone-cracking fight\", while some female crew members protested that the concept was [[misogynistic]] towards Fiona.<ref name=\":60\" />\n\nElliott and Rossio had suggested revisiting the discussion about Fiona's true nature is beautiful or an ogre in a potential sequel, but the idea was rejected.<ref name=\":60\" /> The directors spent four months brainstorming several new ideas for the sequel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=3572710|title=Director Andrew Adamson on Shrek 2 and The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe|last=Baillie|first=Russell|date=June 28, 2004|website=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921001608/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=3572710|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref> before ultimately determining that the only logical \"jump off point\" was one of the few areas not explored in the first film: Fiona's parents' reaction to their daughter both marrying and remaining an ogre.<ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-shrek-2-directors|title=INT: Shrek 2 directors|last=JoBlo|date=May 21, 2004|website=[[JoBlo.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920085450/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-shrek-2-directors|archive-date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> ''Shrek 2'' director [[Kelly Asbury]] explained that introducing Fiona's parents presented an entirely \"new story to go on, and a whole new place to go.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/extras/features/4664-the-shrek-2-cast-and-crew-talk|title=The Shrek 2 Cast and Crew Talk|last=|first=|date=May 11, 2004|website=[[ComingSoon.net]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108144426/http://www.comingsoon.net/extras/features/4664-the-shrek-2-cast-and-crew-talk|archive-date=November 8, 2018|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, ''Shrek 2'' reveals why Fiona was locked in a tower in the first place,<ref name=\":5\" /> with the filmmakers realizing they could use some of the first film's abandoned concepts to gradually uncover more details about Fiona's story throughout the remainder of the series.<ref name=\":85\">{{cite web|url=https://bluray.highdefdigest.com/4164/shrek_whole_story.html|title=Shrek: The Whole Story|last=Peck|first=Aaron|date=December 8, 2010|website=High Def Digest|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923005900/https://bluray.highdefdigest.com/4164/shrek_whole_story.html|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> For ''Shrek 2'', the filmmakers decided to resurrect the idea of Dama Fortuna, re-imagining her as Fiona's conniving [[fairy godmother]] and the sequel's main villain, who uses magic against Fiona and Shrek's marriage.<ref name=\":28\" />\n\n=== Voice ===\n\nFiona is voiced by American actress [[Cameron Diaz]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parade.com/76403/iraphael/famous-animated-voices/|title=Famous Animated Voices|last=Raphael|first=Isabelle|date=July 26, 2011|website=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005030807/https://parade.com/76403/iraphael/famous-animated-voices/|archive-date=October 5, 2018|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> one of the franchise's three main cast members.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/1462103/Money-talks-for-cast-of-Shrek-2.html|title=Money talks for cast of Shrek 2|last=Davies|first=Hugh|date=May 17, 2004|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620164507/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/1462103/Money-talks-for-cast-of-Shrek-2.html|archive-date=June 20, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Diaz voiced Fiona in all four installments of the film series over the course of ten years.<ref name=\":79\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/cam-regrets-fionas-californian-tones-458354.html|title=Cam regrets Fiona's Californian tones|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[The Irish Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011013801/https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/cam-regrets-fionas-californian-tones-458354.html|archive-date=October 11, 2018|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":80\">{{cite web|url=https://filmreviewonline.com/2010/05/19/shrek-forever-after-cameron-diaz-on-love-and-happiness/|title=Shrek Forever After \u2013 Cameron Diaz on love and happiness and the ending|last=Sloane|first=Judy|date=May 19, 2010|website=Film Review Online|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011013919/https://filmreviewonline.com/2010/05/19/shrek-forever-after-cameron-diaz-on-love-and-happiness/|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> The role was originally intended for comedian and actress [[Janeane Garofalo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2011/08/the-lost-roles-of-janeane-garofalo.html|title=The Lost Roles of Janeane Garofalo|last=Evans|first=Bradford|date=August 11, 2011|website=[[Vulture.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918231049/http://www.vulture.com/2011/08/the-lost-roles-of-janeane-garofalo.html|archive-date=September 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> who was fired from the first film and ultimately replaced with Diaz.<ref name=\":88\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/160924-5-actors-almost-cast-in-shrek-because-mike-myers-wasnt-supposed-to-voice-the-ogre|title=5 Actors Almost Cast In 'Shrek,' Because Mike Myers Wasn't Supposed To Voice The Ogre|last=Denninger|first=Lindsay|date=May 18, 2016|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718030554/https://www.bustle.com/articles/160924-5-actors-almost-cast-in-shrek-because-mike-myers-wasnt-supposed-to-voice-the-ogre|archive-date=July 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Garofalo maintains that she was fired without an explanation, joking, \"I assume [it is] because I sound like a man sometimes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2756227/janeane-garofalo-talks-ratatouille/#fbid=XY8O2chJ8lO|title=Janeane Garofalo Talks Ratatouille|last=Villalobos|first=Brian|date=June 29, 2007|website=[[MTV]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806190951/http://www.mtv.com/news/2756227/janeane-garofalo-talks-ratatouille/|archive-date=August 6, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> However, it is believed that re-casting Fiona resulted from the death of comedian [[Chris Farley]], who was originally cast as Shrek and had already recorded most of the character's dialogue until he died during production, at which point he was replaced with actor [[Mike Myers]].<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/64343/15-giant-facts-about-shrek|title=15 Giant Facts About Shrek|last=Cormier|first=Roger|date=March 22, 2016|website=[[Mental Floss]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624202213/http://mentalfloss.com/article/64343/15-giant-facts-about-shrek|archive-date=June 24, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> According to film historian Jim Hill, the filmmakers originally cast Garofalo as Fiona because they had felt that the actress' \"abrasive, sarcastic [[comic persona]]\" would serve as an ideal [[Foil (literature)|foil]] to Farley's positive approach to the titular character,<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.verbicidemagazine.com/2015/08/06/chris-farley-shrek-video-watch/|title=Chris Farley's Version of Shrek Has Leaked Online|last=|first=|date=August 6, 2015|website=Verbicide Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919024813/https://www.verbicidemagazine.com/2015/08/06/chris-farley-shrek-video-watch/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> but eventually relented that Garofalo was \"too downbeat\" for the film's lighter tone, offering the role to Diaz.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/17/how-quot-shrek-quot-went-from-being-a-train-wreck-to-one-for-the-record-books.aspx|title=How \"Shrek\" went from being a train wreck to one for the record books|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=May 16, 2004|website=Jim Hill Media|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423190123/http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/17/how-quot-shrek-quot-went-from-being-a-train-wreck-to-one-for-the-record-books.aspx|archive-date=April 23, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> With a \"sweeter\" version of Fiona introduced, Shrek was developed into a more pessimistic character.<ref name=\":6\" /> [[File:Cameron diaz 2010.jpg|left|thumb|Actress [[Cameron Diaz]] (2010) has voiced Fiona for the entire series.|249x249px|alt=]]\n\nFiona was Diaz's first animated role.<ref name=\":25\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-05-31-0105310026-story.html|title=A timely morality play|last=Munoz|first=Lorenza|date=May 31, 2001|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920011102/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-05-31-0105310026-story.html|archive-date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]] invited Diaz to star in an animated film about an ogre and a princess who learn to accept both themselves and each other.<ref name=\":25\" /> In addition to the film's positive message, Diaz was drawn to the idea of co-starring alongside Myers, [[Eddie Murphy]] and [[John Lithgow]].<ref name=\":25\" /> Approaching her role as though it were a [[Drama Film|dramatic]] performance, Diaz recorded most of her dialogue before a full script had been written, working closely with director [[Andrew Adamson]] to stage scenes before the film had been storyboarded.<ref name=\":25\" /> Prior to ''Shrek'', Diaz starred in the [[action-comedy]] film ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]'' (2000), a role for which she had undergone [[martial arts]] training.<ref name=\":26\" /> While recording the scene in which her character fights Monsieur Hood and his Merry Men, Diaz became quite animated, gesturing and occasionally uttering [[Cantonese]] phrases; her martial arts background is credited with benefiting the sequence.<ref name=\":26\" /> Diaz once burped during a recording session, which was written into a scene for Fiona.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/leisure/movies/hollywood-s-a-list-of-most-popular-voice-actors-1.825243|title=Hollywood's A-list of most popular voice actors|last=Crane|first=Kelly|date=June 23, 2011|website=[[Gulf News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919132214/https://gulfnews.com/leisure/movies/hollywood-s-a-list-of-most-popular-voice-actors-1.825243|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Without a proper screenplay to aid her, Diaz found the improvisation required for some scenes one of the most challenging aspects of the recording process.<ref name=\":67\" /> The actress did not see the film's completed story until after she had finished working on the project on-and-off for two years, by which point she finally truly understood her \"character and ... what she was going through\".<ref name=\":25\" /> Myers was both impressed with and inspired by Diaz's commitment to her role, to the point that he felt he was acting opposite Fiona herself.<ref name=\":25\" /> Asbury recalled that Diaz immediately \"nailed\" her character, elaborating, \"She had this certain thing about her voice where she could be headstrong and know exactly what she wants and be confident, but also have this touch of sweet naivete and all make it completely believable.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> Despite admiring the performances of her predominately male co-stars, Diaz seldom worked directly with them throughout the ''Shrek'' series.<ref name=\":48\" />\n\nDiaz enjoyed \"the good feeling\" she experienced playing Fiona,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.accessonline.com/articles/justin-cameron-reunite-at-shrek-the-third-premiere-59282/|title=Justin & Cameron Reunite At 'Shrek The Third' Premiere|last=|first=|date=May 7, 2007|website=[[Access Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918231237/https://www.accessonline.com/articles/justin-cameron-reunite-at-shrek-the-third-premiere-59282/|archive-date=September 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> and preferred voicing her character as an ogre over a princess, the former of which she finds truly beautiful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/dec/05/news|title=Cameron Diaz on board for Shrek sequel|last=|first=|date=December 5, 2001|website=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Apart from the ''Charlie's Angels'' sequel ''[[Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle]]'' (2003), ''Shrek'' is the only franchise in which Diaz reprised a role.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-total-film-interview-cameron-diaz/|title=The Total Film Interview - Cameron Diaz|last=|first=|date=July 1, 2007|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> The origins of Fiona's parents had not yet been disclosed in the first film, therefore Diaz voiced Fiona using an [[American Accent|American accent]].<ref name=\":79\" /> After discovering that English actors [[Julie Andrews]] and [[John Cleese]] would voice her parents [[Queen Lillian]] and [[King Harold (Shrek)|King Harold]], respectively, in ''Shrek 2'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hollywood//articleshow/37015964.cms|title=English Fiona|last=|first=|date=May 21, 2010|website=[[Ahmedabad Mirror]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> Diaz regretted voicing her character with her default [[California accent|Californian accent]] as opposed to a [[British accent]].<ref name=\":80\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a221338/diaz-i-wish-fiona-had-a-british-accent/|title=Diaz: 'I wish Fiona had a British accent'|last=Minaya|first=Marcell|date=May 23, 2010|website=[[Digital Spy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011053616/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a221338/diaz-i-wish-fiona-had-a-british-accent/|archive-date=October 11, 2018|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> She identified her accent as one of the few things she would have changed about her performance in retrospect.<ref name=\":80\" /> Bob Thompson of the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' observed that few, if any, critics took issue with Diaz's inconsistency.<ref name=\":81\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20100528/285022620666276|title=Cameron Diaz finds it easy to be green|last=Thompson|first=Bob|date=May 28, 2010|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|access-date=October 11, 2018|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> Although admitting that working on the films for only a few hours at a time sporadically sometimes resulted in her feeling as though she is not \"100 per cent involved ... at the same time, that character is so my character. I feel very possessive of Fiona. It's interesting to see something that's not actually tangible so fully embody your essence. It feels like I've lent something to this film that I could never give to any other film, in a weird way.\"<ref name=\":66\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/its-not-easy-being-green-20040529-gdxx8h.html|title=It's not easy being green|last=Horn|first=John|date=May 29, 2004|website=[[The Age]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Diaz would often defend Fiona's appearance from the press asking how she feels about playing an \"ugly\" character, explaining, \"It's shocking to me that that's the perception, just because she's big and round ... Her body is everything that she is inside. I love that she is the princess who isn\u2019t like all the other princesses. She doesn\u2019t look like them, and she's just as beloved and accepted.\"<ref name=\":62\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/getting-it-straight-from-the-women-of-shrek/|title=Getting it straight from the women of \"Shrek\"|last=Germain|first=David|date=May 23, 2007|website=[[Seattle Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> In ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), Diaz co-starred alongside her ex-boyfriend, singer [[Justin Timberlake]], with whom she had broken up the previous year.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.recordonline.com/article/20070507/entertain/70507017|title=Justin Timberlake and Cameron Diaz reunite at 'Shrek the Third' premiere|last=Cidoni|first=Michael|date=May 7, 2007|website=[[Recordonline.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Timberlake plays her character's cousin [[Arthur Pendragon (Shrek)|Arthur Pendragon]], heir to her late father's throne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/justin-timberlake-cameron-diaz-kiss-on-shrek-red-carpet/|title=Justin Timberlake & Cameron Diaz Kiss on Shrek Red Carpet|last=Hammel|first=Sara|date=May 7, 2007|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919024826/https://people.com/celebrity/justin-timberlake-cameron-diaz-kiss-on-shrek-red-carpet/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1501062/justin-timberlake-will-learn-his-lesson-in-shrek-3/|title=Justin Timberlake Will Learn His Lesson In 'Shrek 3'|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=May 2, 2005|website=[[MTV]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> ''Shrek 2'' features a brief reference to Timberlake; a picture of a young knight named \"Sir Justin\" appears in Fiona's childhood bedroom, which is believed to be a reference to their relationship.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/2004/05/17/Shrek-2-features-Timberlake-joke/6281084766400/|title='Shrek 2' features Timberlake joke|last=|first=|date=May 17, 2004|website=[[United Press International]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2007/shrek-the-third-fun-facts/|title=Shrek the Third fun facts|last=Armstrong|first=Josh|date=April 20, 2007|website=Animated Views|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Diaz was unaware of Timberlake's [[Cameo appearance|cameo]] until watching the film, believing it had been finalized before they were a couple.<ref name=\":66\" /> Although Timberlake was initially cast as Arthur while he was still dating Diaz, producer [[Aron Warner]] maintains that Timberlake's involvement was not influenced by their relationship, insisting that he earned the role based on his own merit and comedic timing.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":49\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/king-shrek-hollywood-s-favourite-ogre-making-regal-return-1.236823|title=King Shrek, Hollywood's favourite ogre, making regal return|last=Germain|first=David|date=April 10, 2007|website=[[CTV News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The film's May 2007 premiere in Los Angeles was the first media event at which the former couple had been photographed since the end of their relationship.<ref name=\":3\" /> Director [[Mike Mitchell (director)|Mike Mitchell]] denied media speculation that Timberlake and his character's omission from ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010) correlated to Diaz and Timberlake's breakup, explaining that Arthur was written out solely to allow more screen time for more relevant characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Justin-Timberlakes-Omission-from-Shrek-Not-Diaz-Related-94507314.html|title=Justin Timberlake's Omission from \"Shrek\" Not Diaz Related|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[NBC Chicago]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA filmmaker described Diaz as \"the rock\" of the franchise because \"She brings such a great spirit to these movies.\u201d<ref name=\":53\">{{cite web|url=http://mantras.tv/animation/movies/Shrek%20the%20Third.pdf|title=Shrek the Third|last=|first=|date=2007|website=Mantras.TV|page=9|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Following the release of ''Shrek Forever After'', the series' final installment,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/181220/cam-diaz-prefers-ogre-green-to-angels-leather|title=Cam Diaz Prefers Ogre Green to Angels Leather|last=Huntington|first=Heather|date=May 15, 2010|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Diaz reflected that the ''Shrek'' films had remained her \"safety net\" for several years, describing the period as \"a decade of knowing that you finish one and for the next two years we'll be making another one\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/16/movies/16shrek.html|title=He's Big, He's Green, and He's Gone|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|date=May 14, 2010|work=|access-date=September 18, 2018|author-link=Dave Itzkoff|website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> She remains hopeful for future sequels,<ref name=\":0\" /> joking, \"I'm ready for 'Shrek 18,' if they haven't killed Fiona off by then.\"<ref name=\":49\" /> Diaz was saddened to bid farewell to her character,<ref name=\":42\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/cameron-diaz-on-her-shrek-role/93734154/|title=Cameron Diaz on her \"Shrek\" role|last=Covert|first=Colin|date=May 15, 2010|website=[[Star Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103183535/http://www.startribune.com/cameron-diaz-on-her-shrek-role/93734154/|archive-date=January 3, 2018|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/celebrity-news/swamp-monster-cameron-diaz-983747|title='Swamp monster' Cameron Diaz|last=|first=|date=June 28, 2010|website=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> admitting that she took the films and Fiona for granted until the end because she always assumed she would be invited back within a few months for another installment.<ref name=\":48\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/saturday-star/20100717/282226597000502|title=Cameron Diaz on becoming Princess Fiona|date=July 17, 2010|work=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Saturday Star]]|access-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922135733/https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/saturday-star/20100717/282226597000502|archive-date=September 22, 2018|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> Considering the role \"a privilege and honor\",<ref name=\":48\" /> Diaz maintains that Fiona is the role for which she is most recognized by children,<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/the-interview-cameron-diaz-185337.html|title=The Interview: Cameron Diaz|last=Lyons|first=Saffron|date=July 21, 2002|work=|access-date=September 18, 2018|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> but she prefers when parents allow them to pretend that her character truly exists without revealing her voice actress,<ref name=\":0\" /> often attempting to prevent parents from exposing the truth.<ref name=\":81\" /> Diaz elaborated that Fiona has become \"part of my screen persona. Rather than me putting myself through her I think she comes through me in a weird way. When people think of me they think of Fiona, it's not the other way around.\"<ref name=\":67\" /> Diaz believes that her popularity has greatly increased since voicing the character.<ref name=\":9\" /> Despite being currently in development, Diaz has yet to confirm whether or not she will reprise her role in a fifth film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/3/31/15141312/shrek-5-reinvent-franchise-dreamworks|title=Shrek 5 will completely reinvent the series|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=March 31, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> although she had previously said that she would return for a fifth installment if asked.<ref name=\":81\" />\n\nDiaz's role in the ''Shrek'' series is believed to have contributed to her becoming one of Hollywood's wealthiest actresses by 2008.<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/top-10-highest-paid-actresses/8/|title=Top 10 Highest-Paid Actresses \u2013 3. Cameron Diaz ($15+ Million/Movie)|last=|first=|date=2007|website=[[CBS News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.urbandaddy.com/articles/41889/a-farewell-to-cameron-diazs-acting-career|title=A Farewell to Cameron Diaz's Acting Career|last=Ashcraft|first=Kady Ruth|date=March 12, 2018|website=[[UrbanDaddy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921231746/https://www.urbandaddy.com/articles/41889/a-farewell-to-cameron-diazs-acting-career|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018|quote=She went on to voice the ogress Fiona in the Shrek franchise, a career move that in 2008 ranked her as Forbes\u2019 richest female celebrity.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/a3069/cameron-diaz-interview-environment/|title=Cameron Diaz's Excellent Adventure|last=Kaylin|first=Lucy|date=June 2, 2009|website=[[Marie Claire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2018|quote=the highest-earning actress in Hollywood, thanks largely to some nimble voice work as the ogress Fiona in the Shrek franchise.}}</ref> After being paid $3 million for the first film,<ref name=\":77\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2008-12-04/news/0812030245_1_shrek-jean-vander-pyl-princess-fiona|title=Is a voice worth that much?|last=Lewis|first=Herschell Gordon|authorlink=Herschell Gordon Lewis|date=December 4, 2008|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006000742/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2008-12-04/news/0812030245_1_shrek-jean-vander-pyl-princess-fiona|archive-date=October 6, 2018|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Diaz originally re-negotiated to receive $5 million for ''Shrek 2'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/film/news/inside-move-shrek-2-s-expensive-voices-1117802559/|title=Inside Move: 'Shrek 2's' expensive voices|last=Brodesser|first=Claude|date=July 10, 2001|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> estimated to be an hourly salary of $35,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=103716|title=Shrek Stars' Salaries Jump for Sequel|last=|first=|date=July 11, 2002|website=[[ABC News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919024830/https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=103716|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.ign.com/articles/2001/07/12/shrek-2-cast-sees-green|title=Shrek 2 Cast Sees Green|last=Linder|first=Brian|date=June 21, 2012|website=[[IGN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> She ultimately earned between $10 to $15 million for reprising her role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/12/28/voiceover-industry-attracts-big-celebs-gets-more-competitive.html|title=Big-name stars flooding market for voice-over work, experts say|last=McKay|first=Hollie|date=December 28, 2012|website=[[Fox News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404091951/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/12/28/voiceover-industry-attracts-big-celebs-gets-more-competitive.html|archive-date=April 4, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/45762/diaz-sandler-really-rich|title=Diaz, Sandler Really Rich|last=Byrne|first=Bridget|date=August 29, 2003|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/shrek-2-189216/|title=Shrek 2|last=Travers|first=Peter|date=2004|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/aug/29/entertainment/et-quick29.2|title=Diaz's pay is said to be a record|last=Dutka|first=Elaine|date=August 29, 2003|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> For ''Shrek the Third'', Diaz was paid $30 million, her highest salary at that point,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/top-actress-salaries-are-quote-156261|title=Top actress salaries are quote-worthy|last=Grabicki|first=Michelle|date=December 4, 2007|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> due to securing a significant portion of the installment's profits.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/reese-angelina-lead-list-of-highest-paid-actresses/|title=Reese, Angelina Lead List of Highest-Paid Actresses|last=Silverman|first=Steven M.|date=November 30, 2007|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920011221/https://people.com/movies/reese-angelina-lead-list-of-highest-paid-actresses/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/30/AR2007113000445.html?noredirect=on|title=Reese Witherspoon Highest-Paid Actress|last=|first=|date=December 1, 2007|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> She earned $10 million for ''Shrek Forever After''.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/03/24/hollywood-movies-animation-business-entertainment-animation-stars_slide.html|title=Slide Show: Hollywood's Animation A-List|last=Pomerantz|first=Dorothy|date=Mar 24, 2010|website=[[Forbes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/03/24/hollywood-movies-animation-business-entertainment-animation-stars.html#59ecf76a2ffc|title=Hollywood's Animation A-List|last=Pomerantz|first=Dorothy|date=March 24, 2010|website=[[Forbes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 19, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, ''Forbes'' ranked Diaz Hollywood's second highest-earning voice actor, behind only Myers.<ref name=\":21\" /> On the actress' lucrative earnings, filmmaker [[Herschell Gordon Lewis]] wrote in an article for the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' \"Sure, she captured the character well. Yes, the 'Shrek' movies invariably are box office successes. But can anyone say that if the voice of Princess Fiona were that of a competent actress other than Cameron Diaz, the movie would have flopped?\"<ref name=\":77\" /> Actress [[Holly Fields]] has provided the character's singing voice in the film, in addition to voicing the character in several video games, toys, commercials and amusement park rides. Fields is often hired to imitate Diaz, describing the experience as one of her \"coolest jobs\".<ref name=\":91\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.diabolikdvd.com/holly-fields-interview/|title=Holly Fields Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=DiabolikDVD|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Design and animation ===\n\nFiona is the franchise's [[Leading lady|female lead]] and Shrek's [[romantic interest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=pt&u=https://super.abril.com.br/mundo-estranho/que-personagens-famosos-sao-vitimas-das-parodias-de-shrek/&prev=search|title=What famous characters are \"victims\" of Shrek's parodies?|last=da Silva|first=C\u00edntia Cristina|date=April 18, 2011|website=[[Superinteressante]]|language=Portuguese|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\":48\" /> ''Shrek'' was the first computer-animated film to feature human characters in lead roles,<ref name=\":32\">{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2001/05/24/anti_shrek/|title=\"Shrek\" is not Shrek!|last=Mifflin|first=Margot|date=May 24, 2001|website=[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/co-directing-shrek-victoria-jenson|title=On Co-Directing Shrek: Victoria Jenson|last=Koseluk|first=Chris|date=May 10, 2001|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018|quote=This is the first time you really see humans appear in principal roles in a CG film}}</ref> thus director [[Vicky Jenson|Vicki Jenson]] believed its heroine should be beautiful yet convincing.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/06/18/shrek_2001_directors_interview.shtml|title=Andrew Adamson and Vicky Jenson|last=Falk|first=Ben|date=2001|website=[[BBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030023829/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/06/18/shrek_2001_directors_interview.shtml|archive-date=October 30, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Elliott and Rossio had originally envisioned Fiona's monstrous form as furry in appearance, wanting her to resemble an entirely unique character as opposed to simply a female version of Shrek, but the filmmakers struggled to agree upon her final design.<ref name=\":60\" /> Aiming to achieve stylized realism,<ref name=\":69\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/844510/Shrek-animators-add-style-to-reality.html|title='Shrek' animators add style to reality|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Breznican|date=May 25, 2001|website=[[Deseret News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> the animators found that they could emphasize Fiona's face most efficiently by focusing \"on the subtleties of the human form\" and compiling [[Transparency and translucency|translucent]] layers of skin to prevent the character from resembling plastic, a task they found particularly daunting due to people's familiarity with human skin.<ref name=\":50\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemareview.com/production.asp?prodid=1357|title=Shrek|last=|first=|date=|website=CinemaReview.com|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> To make Fiona's skin more believable, the animators studied [[dermatology]] books to learn how various light sources interact with human skin,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailylocal.com/arts_and_entertainment/shrek-animators-give-reality-style/article_8e70c702-1c7b-5596-845f-956e5e6d684a.html|title='Shrek' animators give reality style|last=|first=|date=May 17, 2001|website=[[Daily Local News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref> which visual effects supervisor Ken Bielenberg approached as though they were lighting Diaz herself.<ref name=\":69\" /> Bielenberg joked, \"You want the sunset to reflect off her face in a way that's flattering ... Fiona may be a computerized princess, but she has her bad side.\"<ref name=\":69\" /> The animators painted a combination of freckles and warmer tones onto some of her skin's deeper layers, through which they then filtered light.<ref name=\":20\" /> A [[shader]] was used to penetrate, refract and re-emerge layers of light, the [[Saturation (color theory)|concentration]] of which was adjusted to achieve Fiona's desired radiance; they learned that too much [[Exposure (photography)|exposure]] resulted in a [[mannequin]]-like appearance.<ref name=\":50\" /> The lighting department consulted with makeup artist Patty York to learn different approaches to creating realistic effects on Fiona's face,<ref name=\":26\">{{cite web|url=http://culture.com/articles/463/shrek-production-information.phtml|title=Shrek : Production Information|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema.com|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> while the computer graphics software [[Autodesk Maya|Maya]] was used to animate her hair,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalmediafx.com/Shrek/shrekfaq.html|title=Shrek FAQ|last=Tracy|first=Joe|date=|website=Digital Media FX|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> which consists of more than 1 million polygons.<ref name=\":59\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/shrek-summer-152865|title=A Shrek of Summer|last=Ansen|first=David|authorlink=Ansen, David|date=May 6, 2001|website=[[Newsweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The animators felt that Fiona's design was \"too real\" at times.<ref name=\":7\" /> When the film was previewed to test audiences, some children cried because they found Fiona's [[Hyperreality|hyperrealism]] disturbing;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sessions.edu/notes-on-design/by-hand-or-on-the-computer-the-threat-of-the-uncanny-valley/|title=By hand or on the computer? The threat of the Uncanny Valley|last=|first=|date=February 13, 2012|website=[[Sessions College for Professional Design]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919132232/https://www.sessions.edu/notes-on-design/by-hand-or-on-the-computer-the-threat-of-the-uncanny-valley/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":89\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/science/sdut-ucsd-exploring-why-some-robots-creep-people-out-2011aug04-story.html|title=UCSD exploring why robots creep people out|last=Robbins|first=Gary|date=August 4, 2011|website=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/idealog/20170724/282385514564811|title=The Creep Factor|last=|first=|date=July 24, 2017|work=Idealog|access-date=September 19, 2018|via=PressReader}}</ref> the character was suffering from a phenomenon known as the [[uncanny valley]].<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=124371580|title=Hollywood Eyes Uncanny Valley In Animation|last=York|first=Jamie|date=March 5, 2010|website=[[National Public Radio]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Consequently, DreamWorks ordered that the character be re-animated to appear more like a cartoon and less like a human simulation.<ref name=\":15\" /> Animator Lucia Modesto recalled that her team was instructed to \"pull back\" on the character's design because her realism was growing unpleasant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irssh.com/yahoo_site_admin/assets/docs/17_IRSSH-436-V4N2.44204045.pdf|title=Hyper-Realistic Characters and the Existence of the Uncanny Valley in Animation Films|last=Kaba|first=Fethi|date=2012|website=International Review of Social Sciences and Humanities|page=190|issn=2248-9010|access-date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829040130/http://irssh.com/yahoo_site_admin/assets/docs/17_IRSSH-436-V4N2.44204045.pdf|archive-date=August 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2002/06/face/|title=Why Is This Man Smiling?|last=Weschler|first=Lawrence|date=June 1, 2002|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=Animation Studies \u2013 Animated Dialogues, 2007|last=Butler|first=Matthew|last2=Joschko|first2=Lucie|date=2007|page=61|citeseerx = 10.1.1.664.7656}}</ref> Subsequently, Fiona was modified to fit in among the film's more fantastical characters, which supervising animator [[Raman Hui]] credits with improving the believability of Fiona and Shrek's relationship.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalmediafx.com/Interviews/ramanhui.html|title=dFX Interview: Raman Hui|last=|first=|date=|website=Digital Media FX|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> To make Fiona a more \"cartoony-looking love interest,\"<ref name=\":14\" /> the animators enlarged her eyes and smoothed her skin.<ref name=\":7\" /> Hui acknowledged that Fiona was much more difficult to animate as a human because any errors were quite apparent.<ref name=\":59\" /> In total, Fiona's face required a year of constant experimentation before the animators were satisfied with her final design: a realistic yet softer interpretation of the princess.<ref name=\":54\">{{cite web|url=https://www.asc.ohio-state.edu/palazzi.1/AC753W05/Computer%20Graphics%20World%20-%20Medieval%20Magic.pdf|title=Medieval Magic|last=Robertson|first=Barbara|date=October 2004|website=[[The Ohio State University]]|page=3|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDirector Andrew Adamson admitted that making Fiona beautiful yet viscerally familiar posed several unique challenges for the filmmakers.<ref name=\":54\" /> For example, her eyebrows sometimes cast shadows over her eyes, while her upturned lip and large eyes resulted in a \"spooky\" appearance.<ref name=\":54\" /> They wanted Fiona's appearance to be relatable without \"stick[ing] out among Shrek and the other fantastic characters and distract from the fairy-tale mood.\"<ref name=\":71\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2001/05/13/accent-on-the-details-shrek-takes-quantum-leap-in-animation/|title=Accent on the details: 'shrek' takes quantum leap in animation|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|authorlink=Lou Lumenick|date=May 13, 2001|website=[[New York Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Adamson identified Fiona as the film's most difficult character to animate due to people's familiarity with human mannerisms and expressions, whereas audiences are not nearly as accustomed to talking animals, such as Donkey.<ref name=\":71\" /> Hui maintains that Fiona's appearance was not based on that of any specific individual.<ref name=\":7\" /> Although the animators wanted to avoid making the character resemble Diaz too closely, elements of the actress's movements and mannerisms, which were videotaped during recording sessions,<ref name=\":71\" /> were incorporated into Fiona nonetheless, which they drew onto a different face to create a unique new character.<ref name=\":7\" /> Studying Diaz's mannerisms inspired the animators to exaggerate Fiona's expressions and reactions, instead of striving for realism.<ref name=\":71\" /> For example, Adamson believes Fiona squinting her eyes and compressing her lips while listening to someone else offers \"a richness you\u2019ve never seen before\u201d, despite their difficulty to animate.<ref name=\":71\" /> Diaz was shocked and ran out of the studio screaming joyfully when she saw her character animated to her voice for the first time.<ref name=\":11\" /> Although Diaz did not think the character resembles her, she recognized that Fiona had many of her mannerisms in addition to her own voice, appearing \"more real than she had imagined\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2004-05-19/lifestyle/0405170385_1_shrek-green-ogre-animation|title=Shrek 2 Has Ingredients Of Another Monster Hit|last=Koltnow|first=Barry|date=May 19, 2004|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> The actress explained that \"the experience was so weird she felt like she was watching some kind of strange sister.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Now-animation-is-king-Shrek-and-Atlantis-2921792.php|title=Now animation is king / 'Shrek' and 'Atlantis' will duke it out this summer|last=Stack|first=Peter|date=May 13, 2001|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Fiona's body consists of 90 muscles,<ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":54\" /> but her entire model is made up of more than 900 movable muscles.<ref name=\":59\" /> Even in her ogre form, Fiona is significantly smaller than Shrek, with layout supervisor Nick Walker confirming that Shrek is capable of swallowing Fiona's head whole.<ref name=\":52\">{{cite web|url=https://www.linuxjournal.com/article/9653|title=DreamWorks Animation \"Shrek the Third\": Linux Feeds an Ogre|last=Rowe|first=Robin|date=June 5, 2007|website=[[Linux Journal]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nActor [[Antonio Banderas|Antonia Banderas]], who voices [[Puss in Boots (Shrek)|Puss in Boots]], originally found it challenging to accept Fiona's unconventional appearance.<ref name=\":31\" /> Banderas explained that he experienced \"a certain resistance as a spectator for her to be an ogre\", initially wishing for her and Shrek to end the film as humans before finally accepting the character's appearance and sequel's ending.<ref name=\":31\" /> The actor believes several audience members \"went through this process when they were observing this movie\" because \"We are used to rejecting ugliness without reason.\u201d<ref name=\":31\" /> Costume designer [[Isis Mussenden]] designed the character's costumes for the first two ''Shrek'' films, for which she helped develop new technology to animate clothing in the then-new computer animation medium.<ref name=\":40\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BOMcDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT606&lpg=PT606&dq=Andrew+Adamson+fiona+interview#v=onepage&q=Andrew%20Adamson%20fiona%20interview&f=false|title=The Art and Practice of Costume Design|last=Mertz|first=Melissa|publisher=CRC Press|year=2016|isbn=9781317573678|location=United States|pages=|via=Google Books}}</ref> The filmmakers wanted a more realistic approach to costumes than previous computer animated films, in which clothing was typically depicted as a tight layer over the figure, adorned with a few wrinkles.<ref name=\":40\" /> The filmmakers had envisioned Fiona's velvet gown as one that moves independently from her body, therefore one of the film's producers recruited Mussenden, with whom they had worked prior, to assist them with the process.<ref name=\":40\" /> Mussenden began by creating a one-quarter scale replica of the skirt. To determine the gown's volume, fullness and where certain areas would rest on the character's form, the costume designer worked with both a pattern maker and designer.<ref name=\":40\" /> The patterns and seams were labeled and forwarded to the animators, who would replicate the images on the computer.<ref name=\":40\" /> Mussenden decided to give Fiona's dresses tight sleeves as opposed to the long, flowing sleeves associated with traditional [[Medieval fashion|medieval clothing]] due to the difficulty the latter would have been for the animators.<ref name=\":41\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2004/05/18/clothes-make-the-ogre/a04bd3bd-2597-4e9d-9ee4-7a6c5c244319/|title=Clothes Make the Ogre|last=|first=|date=2004|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Unlike ''Shrek'', Fiona has several costume changes in ''Shrek 2''. In the sequel, both Fiona's ogre and human forms are shown wearing the same green dress. To ensure that both forms looked equally flattering in the same outfit, Mussenden lowered the dress' waistline to make it more medieval in appearance than the costume she wears in the first film.<ref name=\":41\" /> Fiona's first costume is a lilac dress, which Mussenden designed to appear \"organic and textured, because she's been living in the swamp\". Towards the end of the film, she changes into a white ballgown with rhinestones inspired by an image of a 1958 dress the costume designer had found.<ref name=\":41\" /> \n\nThe scene in which Fiona single-handedly defeats Monsieur Hood and his Merry Men references the [[slow motion]] special effects popularized by ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999),<ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\":59\" /><ref name=\":43\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pluggedin.ca/movie-reviews/shrek/|title=Shrek|last=Waliszewski|first=Bob|last2=Smithouser|first2=Bob|date=|website=[[Plugged In]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921230232/https://www.pluggedin.ca/movie-reviews/shrek/|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> as well as Diaz's own ''Charlie's Angels'' films.<ref name=\":58\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/shrek-review/|title=Shrek Review|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2001|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.film4.com/reviews/2001/shrek|title=Shrek (2001)|last=|first=|date=2001|website=[[Film4]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406054408/http://www.film4.com/reviews/2001/shrek|archive-date=April 6, 2010|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":61\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-05-18-0105180372-story.html#|title=An ogre in love|last=Caro|first=Mark|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> In a DVD bonus feature, Fiona explains that she performed her own stunts in the film, claiming that she based her kung fu on ''Charlie's Angels''.<ref name=\":83\">{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2002/02/23/shrek-laat-scheten-in-een-sprookje-7578827-a143954&prev=search|title=Shrek lets fart in a fairy tale|last=Linssen|first=Dana|date=February 23, 2002|website=[[NRC Handelsblad]]|language=Dutch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Despite concerns that references to ''The Matrix'' would eventually date the film, Rossio believes the gag will remain funny because it is a parody instead of merely an imitation.<ref name=\":60\" /> A similar reference is made when Fiona defeats a mob at the beginning of ''Shrek 2'', a complex sequence for which animators used powerful data processors to store and manipulate millions of computer generated images.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=http://www.elmundo.es/magazine/2004/246/1086789278.html&prev=search|title=Know what Shrek laughs about|last=Calleja|first=Pedro|date=June 13, 2004|website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Modesto created new character models for Fiona and Shrek in ''Shrek the Third'',<ref name=\":51\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/guest_writers1/b/leo_n_holzer/archive/2007/05/01/toon-tuesday-dreamworks-artists-technicians-tried-hard-not-to-ogre-compensate-while-working-on-shrek-the-third.aspx?PageIndex=2|title=Toon Tuesday : \"Shrek the Third\" artists & technicians tried hard not to ogre-compensate|last=Holzer|first=Leo N.|date=April 30, 2007|website=Jim Hill Media|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> while new software and servers were implemented to animate individual strands of the princess's hair much faster than had been possible during production of the first film.<ref name=\":53\" /> In ''Shrek Forever After''<nowiki/>'s alternate reality, the character wears her hair unbraided for the first time,<ref name=\":37\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allure.com/story/princess-fionas-expensive-new-do|title=Princess Fiona's Expensive New 'Do|last=Wexler|first=Sarah|date=May 19, 2010|website=[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> which was inspired by singer [[Janis Joplin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/movies/10-things-didnt-know-shrek-forever|title=10 Things You Didn't Know about Shrek Forever After|last=|first=|date=December 9, 2017|website=[[TVOvermind]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Due to its costliness, Fiona's new hairstyle first needed to be approved by DreamWorks, with Mitchell likening the process to \"prepar[ing] like a lawyer\".<ref name=\":38\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Why-Fiona-Taking-Her-Hair-Down-Is-a-Really-Big-Deal-94165809.html|title=Cameron Diaz's Ogre Hair Style Took a Team of 20 for \"Shrek\"|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=May 18, 2010|website=[[NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> The re-design was a difficult, expensive process that required 20 animators to animate each strand individually,<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":38\" /> as Mitchell was particularly determined to render it correctly due to audiences' familiarity with long hair.<ref name=\":38\" /> One group was specifically tasked with setting up Fiona's hair, which head of production technology Darin Grant believes \"allowed the process to be optimized and work across many, many shots\" as it \"flows and cascades throughout\" the entire film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/vfxworld/decade-shrek-tech|title=A Decade of 'Shrek' Tech|last=Desowitz|first=Bill|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> reinforcing Fiona's liberated personality.<ref name=\":37\" />\n\n=== Personality ===\n\nAccording to Rossio, the first film's four main characters are written \"around the concept of self-esteem, and appropriate and/or inappropriate reactions to appropriate or inappropriate self-assessment\", explaining that Fiona seeks validation from others because she believes \"there's something not correct about herself\".<ref name=\":60\" /> Adamson elaborated that the character's main issue revolves around living up to stereotypes and ideas \"represented in fairy tales that if ... you look a certain way and act a certain way and put the right dress and slippers on a handsome man is going to come\", dismissing this as an unrealistic and unhealthy approach to finding romance.<ref name=\":19\" /> Diaz confirmed that Fiona only becomes her true self once she is freed from the tower and realizes her Prince Charming differs from who she had been taught to expect.<ref name=\":66\" />\n\nA scene during which Fiona duets with a bird who explodes once the princess sings a high note,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Animated-fairy-tale-perfectly-fractured-Shrek-2862091.php|title=Animated fairy tale perfectly fractured / 'Shrek' delights viewers of all ages|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|date=November 2, 2001|website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> subsequently frying its eggs for breakfast,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/shrek1/|title=Shrek (2001)|last=Parker|first=Sabadino|date=2001|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160728073931/http://www.popmatters.com/review/shrek1/|archive-date=July 28, 2016|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> is considered to be a parody of Disney fairy tales such as ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'' (1950), about which Adamson explained \"pok[es] fun at people's expectations\" of princesses.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/05/29/shrek-anti-disney-fairy-tale/|title=Is ''Shrek'' the anti- Disney fairy tale?|last=Reese|first=Lori|date=May 29, 2001|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Diaz believes her character's personality \"shattered\" children's perception of princess characters from the moment she was freed from the tower, explaining that Fiona had always been capable of freeing herself but chose to remain in the tower solely because she was \"following the rules of a fairy tale book\".<ref name=\":48\" /> In the sequel, Diaz explained that Fiona \"has a lot of pressure from all the people who told her about Prince Charming to take everything materialistically and monetarily. And she literally is just kind of baffled by it and says, 'Sorry, but I don't need any of those things.' All she needs is this man who she loves and loves her and accepts her.\"<ref name=\":66\" /> Diaz considers her character to be an empowered, positive role model for young girls,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/people/celebrity-news/it-s-ogre-diaz-says-bye-to-fiona/article_75fc04c8-0201-5028-929e-ccd7cd7aff40.html|title=It's ogre: Diaz says bye to Fiona|last=Covert|first=Colin|date=May 21, 2010|website=Daily Herald|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> explaining, \"She's never depended on anyone to rescue her, which is a different message from Snow White and Rapunzel ... She was capable of getting out of the tower herself\" and \"took on Shrek as her partner rather than as her rescuer.\"<ref name=\":42\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhregister.com/news/article/Hollywood-s-highest-paid-actress-says-good-bye-to-11592108.php|title=Hollywood's highest-paid actress says good-bye to her 'Shrek' character|last=Covert|first=Colin|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[New Haven Register]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref> She believes that the moment she accepts herself as an ogre is her most empowered moment, as well as \"the biggest stride in her evolution as a person\".<ref name=\":67\" />\n\nDiaz considers Fiona to be \"the anchor that holds all these kooky characters\", identifying her as the comedy's [[straight man]].<ref name=\":67\">{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/fashion-news/happy-days-for-cameron-diaz-997160|title=Happy days for Cameron Diaz|last=|first=|date=April 20, 2010|website=[[Manchester Evening News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925104231/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/fashion-news/happy-days-for-cameron-diaz-997160|archive-date=September 25, 2018|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Revealing that she \"hate[s] naggy women\", Diaz sometimes found herself wishing that Fiona would be \"less naggy\" and more compassionate and understanding towards the difficult changes Shrek is undergoing since marrying her.<ref name=\":1\" /> During production of ''Shrek the Third'', Diaz observed that the filmmakers had made Fiona into more of a nag and asked that they tone this down, explaining, \"just because she got married it doesn't mean she has to become a nag'.\"<ref name=\":67\" /> This was one of only a few things Diaz asked that they adjust about Fiona.<ref name=\":67\" /> In ''Shrek Forever After''<nowiki/>'s [[Multiverse|alternate reality]], Fiona frees herself from the tower on her own and subsequently becomes a warrior and leader of an army of ogres,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canmag.com/nw/15767-shrek-forever-after-cameron-diaz|title=Cameron Diaz on Shrek Forever After|last=Topel|first=Fred|date=May 19, 2010|website=CanMag|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> which some commentators found to be a more empowering approach to the princess; Diaz contested that her character has \"always been a warrior ... of love through all these films. What she\u2019s worked for, what she\u2019s fought for is the love that she has for herself and the love that she has for Shrek and her family and her friends.\"<ref name=\":36\">{{cite web|url=https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/features/21634-qaa-the-stars-of-shrek|title=Q&A: The Stars of Shrek|last=|first=|date=May 21, 2010|website=[[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921074453/https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/features/21634-qaa-the-stars-of-shrek|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Diaz concluded that, due to the fourth film's tone, Fiona's responsibilities are simply more apparent,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/sun/intermission/index.ssf/2010/05/shrek.html|title=Voices speak fondly to 'Shrek,' forever after|last=Urbancich|first=John M.|date=May 21, 2010|website=Cleveland.com|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> believing that in this film she is \"fighting for what she believes in.\"<ref name=\":48\" />\n\n== Characterization and themes ==\n\nTodd Anthony of the ''Sun-Sentinel'' cited Fiona among several elements that make ''Shrek'' resemble an archetypal fairy tale initially.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-05-18/entertainment/0105160756_1_lord-farquaad-shrek-princess-fiona|title=Ogre's Odyssey Fractures A Few Fairy Tales Shrek|last=Anthony|first=Todd|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Furniss identified Fiona's [[character arc]] as struggling with insecurities about her identity and appearance before finally \"accept[ing] herself in a so-called 'ugly' physical manifestation\", which she described as merely \"cute\" as opposed to \"push[ing] the boundaries of true ugliness.\"<ref name=\":17\" /> Demonstrated by her \"very definite ideas about how she wants to be rescued,\"<ref name=\":74\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2001/05/16/shrek-it-out-an-unlikely-lovable-ogre-cavorts-in-an-instant-fairy-tale-classic/|title='Shrek' it out: an unlikely lovable ogre cavorts in an instant fairy-tale classic|last=Lumenic|first=Lou|authorlink=Lou Lumenick|date=May 16, 2001|website=[[New York Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Bob Waliszewski of ''[[Plugged In]]'' believes Fiona \"has bought into the conventions of fairy tale [[romanticism]] hook, line and sinker\", writing, \"Her skewed perspective on love and marriage undermines [[agape love]] and spiritual discernment in relationships.\"<ref name=\":43\" /> Similarly, ''[[TV Guide]]'' film critic [[Frank Lovece]] described Fiona as a \"beautiful and headstrong princess\" who has spent too much time thinking about true love.<ref name=\":76\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/shrek/review/134500/|title=Shrek \u2013 Review|last=Lovece|first=Frank|authorlink=Frank Lovece|date=2001|website=[[TV Guide]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> [[Michael Sragow]], film critic for ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', agreed that the character is \"fixated on being treated like a fairy-tale princess\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2001-05-18/features/0105180081_1_donkey-eddie-murphy-fairy|title=A beauty of a beast|last=Sragow|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Sragow|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> resulting in a precarious outlook on reality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/shrek|title=Shrek|last=B|first=N|date=2001|website=[[Total Film]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Although Fiona is originally disappointed upon discovering her rescuer is not a Prince Charming, her expectations are more-so grounded in \"rituals of self-loathing\".<ref name=\":33\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/shrek|title=Shrek|last=Gonzalez|first=Ed|date=May 13, 2001|website=[[Slant Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Furniss believes Fiona's story is targeted towards Disney films in which princesses are constantly rescued from \"horrible fates by knights\".<ref name=\":17\" /> However, despite her efforts to look, speak and behave like a traditional princess,<ref name=\":46\">{{cite web|url=https://geekgirlcon.com/princessfiction/|title=This is what a Princess Looks Like: Fictional Edition|last=Krismer|first=Shiboo|date=February 27, 2012|website=GeekGirlCon|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Fiona is soon proven to be an nontraditional princess, exemplified by her traits as a skilled fighter, unusual diet occasionally consisting of wild animals and tendency to belch spontaneously.<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":46\" />\n\nJames Clarke, author of ''Animated Films - Virgin Film'', described Fiona as \"both an old-school and new-school heroine, in love with the notion of a charming prince who will rescue her but also tough talking and tough acting\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B090Ndx1o6cC&pg=PT124&lpg=PT124&dq=best+animated+heroines+princess+fiona#v=onepage&q=best%20animated%20heroines%20princess%20fiona&f=false|title=Animated Films - Virgin Film|last=Clarke|first=James|publisher=Random House|year=2012|isbn=9781448132812|location=United States|pages=|via=Google Books}}</ref> Although she originally possesses traits associated with a traditional princess, being tall and slender, both Shrek and audiences soon agree that Fiona is different,<ref name=\":17\" /> and the princess is merely \"following a script from a storybook\" herself.<ref name=\":46\" /> Paul Byrnes of ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' wrote that Fiona's depiction in the first film offers \"a sense of how gender roles had shifted\" by resembling \"a bottom-kicking heroine\".<ref name=\":90\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/shrek-forever-after-20100609-xwjw.html|title=Shrek Forever After|last=Byrnes|first=Paul|date=June 10, 2010|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref> Among her unusual characteristics, John Anderson of ''[[Newsday]]'' observed that Fiona is \"perfectly capable of taking care of herself. She's just been waiting for some classic romance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/content/movies/nd4756.htm|title=The Neatest Story Ever Told 'Shrek' stands tall among fairy tales|last=Anderson|first=John|date=2001|website=Newsday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010526174307/http://www.newsday.com/content/movies/nd4756.htm|archive-date=May 26, 2001|url-status=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Although in the context of the film Shrek initially observes Fiona's differences once she belches, \"it rapidly also becomes apparent that she is indeed not a prototypical fairy-tale princess\", according to author Johnny Unger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/2553641|title=Gendered discourses in a contemporary animated film: subversion and confirmation of gender stereotypes in Shrek|last=Unger|first=Johnny|last2=Sunderland|first2=Jane|date=|website=Academia.edu|page=6|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> The ''New York Press'' observed that ''Shrek'' emphasizes \"that the ogre falls in love with the heroine not because of her conventional good looks, but in spite of them ... looking past Fiona's skinny, blond human surface and seeing the belching, bug-eating ogre beneath.\"<ref name=\":34\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?avis=NP&date=20040525&category=NEWS&lopenr=305259985&Ref=AR&template=printart|title=Green Meanies|last=|first=|date=|website=New York Press|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Journalist [[Steve Sailer]], writing for [[United Press International|UPI]], similarly wrote that \"Fiona wins Shrek's heart by belching, beating up Robin Hood's Merry Men (who act like Broadway chorus boys) with cool \"Matrix\"-style kung fu, and cooking the Blue Bird of Happiness' eggs for breakfast.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/2001/05/17/Film-of-the-week-Shrek-is-kids-revenge/9297990072000/|title=Film of the week: 'Shrek' is kids' revenge|last=Sailer|first=Steve|date=May 17, 2001|website=UPI|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Elliot believes that Fiona's storyline explores \"the actual prevalence of attitudes about appearance in society\", identifying a theme of lacking self-esteem as particularly prevalent with Fiona.<ref name=\":60\" /> Film critic [[Emanuel Levy]] shared that \"Fiona suffers/benefits from duality\", transitioning from a \"sexy, opinionated, and feisty\" character into an outcast once \"her secret is revealed\", after which she becomes closer to Shrek.<ref name=\":72\">{{cite web|url=http://emanuellevy.com/article.php?articleID=3053|title=Shrek|last=Levy|first=Emanuel|authorlink=Emmanuel Levy|date=2001|website=[[Emanuel Levy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061118223241/http://emanuellevy.com/article.php?articleID=3053|archive-date=November 18, 2006|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]], film critic for the ''[[New York Press]]'', wrote that Fiona takes the film's [[metaphor]] pertaining the people \"passing for something they're not\" to \"a whole different level\", explaining, \"At first you think she's a standard-issue princess who's willing to let her hair down and hang with the riffraff\", describing her as \"a modern-day Disney heroine.\"<ref name=\":75\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/shrek-the-best-american-movie-of-the-year/|title=Shrek: The Best American Movie of the Year|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|date=May 22, 2001|website=New York Press|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Seitz also observed \"interracial overtones\" in Fiona and Shrek's relationship.<ref name=\":75\" />\n\n''PopMatters'' contributor Evan Sawdey wrote that the ''Shrek'' films use Fiona to promote acceptance, particularity the moment she \"discovers that her true form is that of an ogre\", by which she is not saddened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/134878-shrek-the-whole-story-2496098809.html?rebelltitem=1#rebelltitem1|title='Shrek: The Whole Story': Imagine What We Would Have Missed If We Just Left Him Alone|last=Sawdey|first=Evan|date=December 15, 2010|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Believing that Fiona would happily battle and defend whatever she loves or believes in, Diaz identified the character as \"the anchor everyone has attached themselves to\", to whom Shrek looks to for guidance, which she would not have been able to provide unless she possessed the strength herself.<ref name=\":48\" /> In terms of character development and evolvement, Diaz recalled that, despite having been raised in a \"storybook life\", Fiona eventually comes to terms with the fact that \"her Prince Charming didn\u2019t come in the package she thought he would. She\u2019s learned to have patience with Shrek, accept him for who he his\", particularly going against being taught that her Prince Charming must look and act a certain way.<ref name=\":1\" /> Thus, Adamson considers Fiona to be \"an [[Women's empowerment|empowering]] character\" for young girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/Profiles/Articles/AndrewAdamson/AndrewAdamson.html|title=Creating Imaginary Worlds from Shrek to Narnia|last=Fischer|first=Paul|date=November 21, 2005|website=FilmMonthly|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Unlike Farquaad, Shrek respects Fiona for speaking up for and defending herself.<ref name=\":30\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyedge.ie/shrek-appreciate-4041874-May2018/|title=9 reasons we need to appreciate Shrek more than we already do|last=O'Neill|first=Rachel|date=May 29, 2018|website=[[The Daily Edge]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Fiona's final transformation sequence in which she transforms into an ogre permanently is considered to be a parody and critique of the Beast's transformation into a human in Disney's ''Beauty and the Beast'' (1991),<ref name=\":75\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cVHhj-GIk0wC&pg=PA860&lpg=PA860&dq=princess+fiona+transformation+beauty+and+the+beast#v=onepage&q=princess%20fiona%20transformation%20beauty%20and%20the%20beast&f=false|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Folktales and Fairy Tales: Q-Z|last=Haase|first=Donald|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2008|isbn=9780313334443|location=United States|page=860|via=Google Books}}</ref> with Fiona coming to realize that her \"true love's true form\" is in fact an ogre.<ref name=\":34\" /> Novelist and film critic [[Jeffrey Overstreet]] considered it to be \"part of society\u2019s downfall that we embrace the Princess Fionas when they\u2019re glamorous rather than real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lookingcloser.org/2008/05/shrek-2001/|title=Shrek (2001)|last=Overstreet|first=Jeffrey|date=2001|website=Looking Closer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229005001/http://lookingcloser.org/2008/05/shrek-2001/|archive-date=December 29, 2008|url-status=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] observed that Fiona is the only princess competing to be Farquaad's bride (opposite Cinderella and Snow White) who \"who has not had the title role in a Disney animated feature\", which he considered to be \"inspired by feelings DreamWorks partner Jeffrey Katzenberg has nourished since his painful departure from Disney\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shrek-2001#disqus_thread|title=Shrek|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=May 18, 2001|website=Roger Ebert|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a review for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', film critic [[Stephanie Zacharek]] observed that Fiona \"has two little [[freckle]]like beauty spots, one on her cheek and one on her upper chest\", which she interpreted as \"symbols of her human authenticity, but they also serve as a sort of factory trademark left by her creators: 'You see, we've thought of every last detail.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2001/05/18/shrek/|title=Shrek|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|date=May 18, 2001|website=Salon|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Rick Groen of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' observed that Fiona \"appears to replicate the body of Cameron Diaz\", describing her as \"a cute brunette with a retrouss\u00e9 nose, ample curves, and cleavage that broadens whenever she bends low in her scoop-neck frock.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/movie/MOVIEREVIEWS/20010518/RVSHRE|title=If only it were kid's stuff|last=Groen|first=Rick|date=May 18, 2001|website=The Globe and Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040221114849/http://www.globeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/movie/MOVIEREVIEWS/20010518/RVSHRE|archive-date=February 21, 2004|url-status=|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Fiona is skilled in [[hand-to-hand combat]] and martial arts.<ref name=\":46\" /> ''[[The New York Times]]'' journalist A. J. Jacobs wrote that Fiona's [[Chinese martial arts|kung fu]] skills rival those of actor [[Bruce Lee]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/19/books/review/frogkisser-garth-nix-the-land-of-stories-chris-colfer.html|title=Fairy Tales, Gently Fractured|last=Jacobs|first=A. J.|date=May 19, 2017|website=The New York Times|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> abilities she is explained to have inherited from her mother Queen Lillian.<ref name=\":85\" /> Describing Fiona as tough and clever, museum curator Sarah Tutton observed that, despite being a love interest, the character \"doesn\u2019t play the typical supporting role ... Just because Princess Fiona subverts the idea of beauty, it doesn\u2019t mean that beauty is not important. It means that the film isn\u2019t taking it as a cliche.\"<ref name=\":44\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/forget-waiting-for-prince-charming-modern-princesses-are-breaking-gender-stereotypes/news-story/f6ce5199600ab44953f384197b64fda7|title=Forget waiting for Prince Charming, modern Princesses are breaking gender stereotypes|last=Weekend|first=Anna Brain|date=April 4, 2014|website=[[Herald Sun]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> In the third film, Fiona teaches the classic princesses, who are naturally inclined to \"to assume passive positions\", not to wait for their princes to rescue them,<ref name=\":31\">{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/shrek-creators-embrace-fractured-fairy-tales-wbna18661568|title='Shrek' creators embrace fractured fairy tales|last=|first=|date=August 4, 2010|website=[[Today.com|Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> making them over into [[action hero]]ines themselves when Prince Charming takes over the kingdom while teaching them to stand up for themselves.<ref name=\":62\" /><ref name=\":52\" /> Several critics considered this moment to be about [[girl power]] and female empowerment,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sociotimes.com/archives/2007/05/girl_power_hits.aspx|title=Girl Power Hits Shrek III|last=Kendall|first=Pete|date=May 21, 2007|website=Socio Times|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":64\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2007/05/16/shrek-third-2/|title=Shrek the Third|last=Schwarzbaum|first=Lisa|authorlink=Lisa Schwarzbaum|date=May 16, 2007|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://login.live.com/login.srf?wa=wsignin1.0&rpsnv=13&ct=1537245256&rver=6.7.6640.0&wp=MBI_SSL&wreply=https://outlook.live.com/owa/?RpsCsrfState=9ede1515-3e01-3d5d-a4c4-49dde02ac750&id=292841&whr=hotmail.com&CBCXT=out&lw=1&fl=dob,flname,wld&cobrandid=90015|title=Shrek The Third: review|last=Mclaughlin|first=Robert|date=July 2, 2007|website=Den of Geek|access-date=September 24, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/17/review.shrek/index.html|title=Review: 'Shrek' continues genial hit-or-miss ways|last=Charity|first=Tom|date=May 17, 2007|website=CNN|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/a-nervous-shrek-loses-the-old-spark-20070523-gdq7ef.html|title=A nervous Shrek loses the old spark|last=Maddox|first=Garry|date=May 23, 2007|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> as well as a ''Charlie's Angels'' reference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mustangnews.net/shrekiiiafairytalegoneboring/|title=Shrek III a fairytale gone boring|last=Narciso|first=Isaiah|date=May 22, 2007|website=Mustang News|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Diaz believes that the films and her character \"retain the best qualities of\" classic fairy tale characters, \"infusing them with contemporary wit, style and relevance\" for a more contemporary generation.<ref name=\":31\" /> Diaz elaborated, \"We do love those girls ... But now they have a whole new life. They can exist in our current culture, our pop culture again ... Where before, they were forgotten. It\u2019s a celebration of them. It\u2019s a rebirth.\u201d<ref name=\":31\" /> Furthermore, Diaz believes that the princesses' independence is a positive message for both women and men, interpreting it as \"a message for everyone \u2026 You have to be proactive in your own life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/diaz-shrek-pals-share-fairy-tale-talk-1C9423012|title=Diaz and 'Shrek' pals share fairy-tale talk|last=|first=|date=May 9, 2007|website=Today|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Miller believes that Fiona's skills as a martial artist prove naturally beneficial to her adjustment to motherhood because \"she can use her whole body. She\u2019s very adaptable.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/exclusive-shreks-babies-revealed/#mom-knows-best|title=Exclusive: Shrek's Babies Revealed!|last=Lynch|first=Jason|date=May 1, 2007|website=People|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Appearances ==\n\n===Film series===\nFiona first appears in ''[[Shrek]]'' (2001) as a bride chosen by Lord Farquaad, who intends to marry the princess solely so that he can become King of Duloc.<ref name=\":55\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4724343/A-monster-triumph.html|title=A monster triumph|last=O'Hagan|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew O'Hagan|date=June 29, 2001|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> In order to regain ownership of his swamp, Shrek and Donkey agree to retrieve Fiona from her dragon-guarded tower and deliver her to Farquaad.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":56\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/shrek-u-9153444.html|title=Shrek (U)|last=Quinn|first=Anthony|date=June 28, 2001|website=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Fiona is rescued successfully but disappointed upon discovering that Shrek is an ogre instead of a knight, proceeding to act coldly towards him at the beginning of their journey back to Duloc. However, her attitude softens once she overhears Shrek explain that he is constantly misjudged by his appearance, and the two gradually develop a camaraderie as Fiona falls in love with [[Shrek]].<ref name=\":76\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ericdsnider.com/movies/shrek/|title=Shrek|last=Snider|first=Eric D.|date=2001|website=Eric D. Snider|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Late one evening, Donkey discovers that Fiona is under an enchantment that transforms her into an ogre every night, and she wishes to break the spell by kissing Farquaad before the next sunset.<ref name=\":84\">{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/2016/04/108730/disney-princess-fiona-shrek|title=The One Princess No One Talks About & Why She Matters|last=Cohen|first=Anne|date=April 22, 2016|website=[[Refinery 29]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref> When she finally decides to tell Shrek the truth the following morning, she learns that Shrek has already summoned Farquaad to take her back to Duloc himself, having overheard and misinterpreted some of her conversation with Donkey.<ref name=\":76\" /> The princess and ogre part ways, Fiona returning to Duloc with Farquaad and Shrek returning to his swamp alone. Shrek and Donkey soon [[Wedding Crasher|interrupt]] Fiona and Farquaad's wedding ceremony, where Shrek professes his love for her. With the sun setting, Fiona allows herself to transform into an ogre in front of Shrek for the first time, prompting Farquaad to threaten to lock her back in her tower for eternity. However, the [[Dragon (Shrek)|dragon]] that had once imprisoned Fiona eats Farquaad, killing him. Fiona finally confesses her feelings for Shrek and, upon kissing him, turns into an ogre full-time; the two ogres marry.\n\nIn ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004), Fiona and Shrek return home from their [[honeymoon]] to find that Fiona's parents are inviting them to the kingdom of Far, Far Away to celebrate and bless their marriage. Shrek is apprehensive about meeting his parents-in-law, but Fiona insists.<ref name=\":24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/animation/shrek-2/4018693.article|title=Shrek 2|last=Oppenheimer|first=Jean|date=May 16, 2004|website=[[Screen Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Fiona's parents, King Harold and Queen Lillian, are surprised to find that their daughter married an ogre,<ref name=\":47\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shrek-2-2004|title=Shrek 2|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|date=May 18, 2004|website=[[RogerEbert.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> with Harold acting particularly coldly towards his new son-in-law, which in turn strains Fiona and Shrek's relationship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/film/review/shrek2|title=Shrek 2|last=Thomas|first=David|date=2004|website=[[Contactmusic.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> When a tearful Fiona unintentionally summons her [[Fairy Godmother (Shrek)|Fairy Godmother]], who discovers that the princess married someone other than Prince Charming \u2013 her own son \u2013 she conspires with Harold to kill Shrek and trick Fiona into falling in love with Charming, as per their original agreement.<ref name=\":47\" /> Fiona is briefly returned to her human form when Shrek consumes a potion that turns both him and his true love beautiful,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/shrek-2-v286672|title=Shrek 2 (2004) \u2013 Synopsis by Mark Deming|last=Deming|first=Mark|date=May 19, 2004|website=[[AllMovie]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> but Shrek must obtain a kiss from Fiona before midnight, otherwise the spell will revert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/n_10395/|title=Con Anima|last=Rainer|first=Peter|date=2004|website=New York|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> However, Fairy Godmother, from whom Shrek steals the potion, tricks Fiona into believing Charming is Shrek's human form. Despite their efforts, Fiona continues to resent Charming's impression of her husband to the point where Fairy Godmother imprisons Shrek and insists that Harold feed Fiona a potion that will force her to fall in love with whomever she kisses first, intending for this to be Charming. However, the king refuses upon seeing how unhappy Fiona has become, thwarting Fairy Godmother's plan. Fairy Godmother and Charming are defeated by Fiona, Shrek and their friends. Although Shrek offers to kiss Fiona so that they can remain human forever, Fiona refuses, insisting that she would rather spend forever with the ogre she fell in love with and married, and they turn back into ogres.\n\nIn ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), Fiona and Shrek take on the roles of acting Queen and King of Far, Far Away while Harold is ill.<ref name=\":51\" /> When Harold passes away, Shrek is reluctantly named next-in-line to Harold's throne, a position he declines because becoming king would prevent him and Fiona from returning to their swamp.<ref name=\":82\">{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/shrek-third-cast-finalized|title=Shrek the Third Cast Finalized|last=DeMott|first=Rick|date=July 13, 2006|website=Animation World Network|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Determined to locate a suitable heir, Shrek sets out to recruit Fiona's cousin Arthur Pendragon to convince him to assume the throne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2007/05/14/shrek-sustains-creative-dynasty/|title=\"Shrek\" sustains creative dynasty|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2007|website=The Denver Post|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Before Shrek departs, Fiona finally reveals that she is pregnant, forcing Shrek to come to terms with the idea of fatherhood.<ref name=\":4\" /> While Shrek, Donkey and Puss venture to Camelot to recruit Arthur, Fiona remains at Far, Far Away, where her princess friends [[Rapunzel (Shrek)|Rapunzel]], [[Snow White (Shrek)|Snow White]], [[Sleeping Beauty]], [[Cinderella (Shrek)|Cinderella]] and her stepsister Doris host a [[baby shower]] for her.<ref name=\":49\" /> The shower is interrupted by Prince Charming, still bitter over losing both the kingdom and Fiona to Shrek. Charming stages an invasion so that he can proclaim himself king of Far Far Away. Instead of waiting to be rescued, an idea that Fiona finds appalling, she encourages the princesses to free themselves and fight back.<ref name=\":63\" /> After escaping the dungeon, Fiona, Lillian and the princesses (albeit Rapunzel, who has betrayed them to marry Charming) organize a resistance to defend themselves and the kingdom.<ref name=\":82\" /> Artie makes a speech to convince the villains to go straight. In the end, Fiona and Shrek return to the swamp, where Fiona gives birth to [[Ogre Triplets (Shrek)|ogre triplets]] named Felicia, Fergus and Farkle.<ref name=\":90\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lancasteronline.com/features/entertainment/shrek-forever-after-an-ending-fit-for-a-king/article_fb1f6aa3-17fe-5cbd-a835-58a8cb2e8a09.html|title='Shrek Forever After:' An ending fit for a king|last=Glass|first=Erica|date=May 28, 2010|website=[[LNP (newspaper)|LNP]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010) reveals that, during the events of the first film, Fiona's parents had nearly lost the kingdom to Rumpelstiltskin, nearly signing it over in return for their daughter's freedom, but his plans are thwarted when Fiona is rescued by and falls in love with [[Shrek]].<ref name=\":35\">{{cite news|last=Giese|first=Rachel|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/review-shrek-forever-after-1.900866|title=Review: Shrek Forever After|date=May 20, 2010|work=[[CBC.ca]]|access-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live|author-link=Rachel Giese}}</ref> Fiona confronts Shrek, who has grown frustrated with his mundane repetitive life since becoming a father, about losing his temper during their children's birthday; a heated argument between the two prompts Shrek to wish he had never rescued Fiona from the tower, a comment by which Fiona is hurt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_8720000/newsid_8725900/8725939.stm|title=Film Review: Shrek Forever After|last=|first=|date=August 3, 2010|website=BBC|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> When Shrek makes his deal with Rumpelstiltskin, for a single day he is taken to an alternate reality where he was never born. Here, Rumpelstiltskin  has seized power by tricking Fiona's parents out of ruling the kingdom of Far Far Away. Since Shrek never frees Fiona from the tower, she remains under the witch's spell \u2013 human by day and ogre by night \u2013 and has subsequently become the leader of a group of Ogre resistance fighters.<ref name=\":35\" /><ref name=\":68\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/125942-shrek-forever-after-2496190280.html|title='Shrek Forever After': It's Getting Pretty Stale|last=Fuchs|first=Cynthia|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Shrek initially believes his relationship with Fiona still exists there but when she doesn't even recognize him, he finally accepts completely that the reality he is in is not his own and that Rumpelstiltskin  has truly altered reality to be as if he never existed until now. Fiona is shown to still be kindhearted and caring but bitterly cynical and disillusioned about the power of true love, because she was never rescued from her tower, having grown traumatized from her years of solitary imprisonment.<ref name=\":68\" /> She begins to fall in love with him again when he starts training with her, but still does not kiss him (having only started to find him likable). But Fiona's attitude towards Shrek changes as she and the other ogres head off to take down Rumpelstiltskin once and for all. During the day, Shrek realizes that a loophole will negate the deal if he can receive a True Love's kiss from Fiona. After a failed attempt, they realize that he has succeeded when Fiona's curse has been broken. The timeline returns to normal, and Shrek returns to his children's birthday party before he lashed out at everybody and warmly greets Fiona.\n\n=== Television specials and shorts ===\nFiona has appeared in two holiday-themed [[Television special|television specials]]: ''[[Shrek the Halls]]'' (2007) and ''[[Scared Shrekless]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Shrek/Princess-Fiona/|title=Princess Fiona|website=Behind the Voice Actors|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> The animated short ''[[Shrek in the Swamp Karaoke Dance Party|Shrek in the Swamp Karaoke Dance Party!]]'' (2001) is included on [[home video]] releases of ''Shrek'', featuring several of the film's characters performing covers of well-known songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/13-best-movie-karaoke-scenes-lost-in-translation-500-days-of-summer-more|title=13 Best Movie Karaoke Scenes: 'Lost In Translation,' '(500) Days of Summer,' More|last=Stern|first=Marlow|date=July 21, 2013|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=August 25, 2018}}</ref> In the short, Fiona sings an excerpt from [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s song \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\" (1984).<ref name=\":83\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/01/entertainment/ca-64102|title='Shrek' Delivers DVD-ROM Goodies|last=King|first=Susan|date=November 1, 2001|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Fiona appears in the short ''[[Shrek 4-D]]'', a 4-D film originally shown at various amusement and theme parks. The short was renamed ''Shrek 3-D'' and ''The Ghost of Lord Farquaad'' for home video and [[streaming service]] releases. In it, Fiona and Shrek's honeymooning plans are interrupted by Farquaad's ghost,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04n99xk|title=Shrek: The Ghost of Lord Farquaad|last=|first=|date=|website=[[BBC Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> who kidnaps Fiona and intends to kill the princess so that he can marry her ghost in the [[afterlife]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/The-Ghost-of-Lord-Farquaad/552494/|title=The Ghost of Lord Farquaad 2003|last=|first=|date=|website=Blu-ray.com|access-date=October 16, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Shrek and Donkey pursue Farquaad determined to rescue her,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/c7fppf/shrek-the-ghost-of-lord-farquaad/|title=Shrek: The Ghost of Lord Farquaad|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Radio Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> assisted by Dragon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shrek_4d_shrek_3d?|title=Shrek 4-D (Shrek 3-D) (2003)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> Fiona appears in the short film ''[[Far far away idol|Far, Far Away Idol]]'', a parody of the [[reality television]] singing competition ''[[American Idol]]'', which is included as a bonus feature on home video releases of ''Shrek 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/shrek-2-the-record-shattering-439-million-box-office-smash-premieres-on-dvd-and-vhs-friday-november-5-74152902.html|title=Shrek 2, the Record Shattering $439 Million Box Office Smash Premieres on DVD and VHS Friday, November 5|last=|first=|date=2004|website=[[PR Newswire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603170304/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/shrek-2-the-record-shattering-439-million-box-office-smash-premieres-on-dvd-and-vhs-friday-november-5-74152902.html|archive-date=June 3, 2013|access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref> First serving as a judge alongside Shrek and an animated version of ''American Idol'' judge [[Simon Cowell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2004/digital/features/idol-times-for-shrek-2-1117911626/|title='Idol' times for 'Shrek 2'|last=Hettrick|first=Scott|date=October 7, 2004|website=Variety|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> offering feedback about the other characters performances,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2004/shrek-2/|title=Shrek 2|last=Simon|first=Ben|date=November 3, 2004|website=Animated Views|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Fiona eventually duets [[The Romantics]]' \"[[What I Like About You (song)|What I Like About You]]\" with Shrek.\n\n===Stage===\n\nFiona appeared in the [[Shrek The Musical|stage musical adaptation of the film]], which ran on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] from 2008 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/shrek-the-musical-477427/#opennightcredit|title=Shrek The Musical|website=Internet Broadway Database|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> The role was originated by actress [[Sutton Foster]], who had been involved in the project three years before its premiere, having learned about it from composer [[Jeanine Tesori]] and director [[Jason Moore (director)|Jason Moore]].<ref name=\":87\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/diva-talk-chatting-with-shreks-sutton-foster-plus-news-of-buckley-lupone-and-minnelli-com-155590|title=Diva Talk: Chatting with Shrek's Sutton Foster Plus News of Buckley, LuPone and Minnelli|last=Gans|first=Andrew|date=November 28, 2008|website=[[Playbill]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> She was drawn towards the idea of playing a princess for the first time, the prospect of which she found \"fun\", as well as the opportunity to collaborate with lyricist and librettist [[David Lindsay-Abaire]].<ref name=\":87\" /> Actresses Keaton Whittaker and Marissa O'Donnell portrayed younger versions of the character.<ref name=\":87\" /> Before production, Foster described Fiona as an atypical princess who is \"a little bipolar, but rightfully so\" having \"grown up, like we all have, with ideas of how the world works\" while trying to surround herself with, and emulate, fairy tales.<ref name=\":87\" /> Foster believes Fiona constantly struggles with her \"inner ogre\" despite trying to be perfect. \"Everything she's been told is that she's supposed to look a certain way and act a certain way, but everything on the inside is telling her something different.\"<ref name=\":87\" /> Although Fiona longs to be a \"proper princess\", Foster identifies herself as \"more of a tomboy\", while Fiona's body contradicts with her desires: \"as soon as she starts farting and burping, she has a really great time! And I just love that, that she finds herself in just having fun with an ogre, with Shrek. And I love that she falls in love with him through something crude.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2008/12/shrek_the_musicals_sutton_foster.html|title=Shrek the Musical's Sutton Foster on the Grave Seriousness of Onstage Farting|last=Fradkin|first=Lori|date=December 12, 2008|website=Vulture.com|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref> Foster found it \"fun to play a truly conflicted character and to be a princess who burps and farts and gets to do silly things.\"<ref name=\":87\" /> Foster earned a Tony Award nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Musical|Best Actress in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/05/theater/theaterspecial/05tonyslist.html|title=2009 Tony Award Winners|date=May 29, 2009|website=The New York Times|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Despite being a fan of the musical adaption, Diaz has stated that she has no intention of reprising her role on stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/cameron-diaz-says-1000881/|title=Cameron Diaz Says \"Shrek No!\" to Broadway|last=Eng|first=Joyce|date=December 15, 2008|website=TV Guide|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nDuring early press screenings, critics were amused by Fiona's bluebird scene to the point where they laughed hysterically.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nitrateonline.com/2001/rshrek.html|title=Shrek|last=Savada|first=Elias|date=May 18, 2001|website=Nitrate Online|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> [[David Ansen]] of ''Newsweek'' reported that the sequence consistently \"sends audiences into fits of delight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/shrek-effect-153723|title=The Shrek Effect|last=Ansen|first=David|authorlink=David Ansen|date=June 17, 2001|website=[[Newsweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' film critic [[Richard Schickel]] called Fiona \"an excellent character,\" highlighting her confrontation with Monsieur Hood.<ref name=\"shrektime\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,999937-1,00.html|title=Cinema: Monstrously Good|last=Schickel|first=Richard|date=May 21, 2001|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=May 15, 2013|author-link=Richard Schickel|url-access=registration}}</ref> Similarly, the ''[[New York Post]]'' film critic [[Lou Lumenick]] identified Fiona's encounters with Monsieur Hood and the bluebird as clever, delightful \"sendups of a long line of Disney classics\".<ref name=\":74\" /> Kelly Vance of the ''[[East Bay Express]]'' wrote, \"Armed with Diaz' vocal portrayal ... Fiona is more charming, more vulnerable, perkier, and even more sensitive than if she were played by a human actress.\"<ref name=\"eastbayexpressshrek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/graphically-ever-after/Content?oid=1065466|title=Graphically Ever After|last=Vance|first=Kelly|date=May 18, 2001|work=[[East Bay Express]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> Film critic Emanuel Levy believes ''Shrek'' benefits from Fiona, writing that \"Diaz applies well skills she had acquired for ''Charlie's Angels''\".<ref name=\":72\" /> [[Hollywood.com]]'s Robert Sims joked that \"Fiona could teach Charlie's Angels a lesson or two in romance and survival skills.\"<ref name=\"shrekhollywood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/review/455380/shrek-review|title=Shrek Review|last=Sims|first=Robert|date=June 3, 2001|website=[[Hollywood.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> [[Malcolm Johnson (journalist)|Malcolm Johnson]] of the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' lauded Fiona as \"a marvel, as beautiful and shapely as a real star but capable of moves that go beyond the wirework in ''The Matrix''.\"<ref name=\":45\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2001-05-18/features/0105181351_1_princess-fiona-snow-white-animation|title=The Green Party 'Shrek' Rules|last=Johnson|first=Malcolm|authorlink=Malcolm Johnson (journalist)|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Hartford Courant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Johnson continued, \"Every turn of Fiona's head, every glance, every shift of mouth lift character animation to new heights.\"<ref name=\":45\" /> Similarly, the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' wrote that \"every bright ringlet on Princess Fiona ... the liquefaction flow of her velvet robe, even her skin tones have the feel of organic root, thread or cell.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/film/green-ogre-rips-disney-to-shreds-7433246.html|title=Green ogre rips Disney to shreds|last=|first=|date=June 28, 2001|website=[[London Evening Standard]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]''<nowiki/>'s Ed Gonzalez identified Fiona's struggles with [[Self-hatred|self-loathing]] as the film's strongest asset.<ref name=\":33\" /> Reviewing ''Shrek the Third'', ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' film critic [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] described Fiona as \"fabulously resourceful\", identifying the moment she reinvents her princess friends into independent women as the film's sole \"Cool Thing.\"<ref name=\":64\" /> \n\nDiaz has also received positive attention for her voice acting.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":92\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/film-and-television-biographies/cameron-diaz|title=Cameron Diaz: 1972\u2014: Model, actress|last=|first=|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[Encyclopedia.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|quote=Besides garnering many rave reviews from critics, Diaz was honored ... for her portrayal of Princess Fiona.}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' film critic [[Desson Howe]] wrote that Diaz's performance offers \"a funny, earthy princess.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/entertainment/movies/reviews/shrekhowe.htm|title='Shrek': A Funny, Fractured Fairy Tale|last=Howe|first=Desson|authorlink=Desson Howe|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> ''GamesRadar+'' wrote Fiona \"nestle[s] comfortably between the movie's storybook style and [[Photorealism|photo-realistic]] convincingness,\" continuing that Diaz's performance \"reinforces her game-for-a-laugh reputation\".<ref name=\":58\" /> Kim Morgan of [[OregonLive.com]] said, \"Diaz's sweet yet tough demeanor shines through all her computer-generated-imagery beauty,\" citing her vulnerability as an asset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/movies/oregonian/index.ssf?/movies/oregonian/al_61fshrk18.frame|title=A romantic leading ogre|last=Morgan|first=Kim|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[OregonLive.com]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010708154405/http://www.oregonlive.com/movies/oregonian/index.ssf?%2Fmovies%2Foregonian%2Fal_61fshrk18.frame|archive-date=July 8, 2001|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<nowiki/>'s film critic [[Andrew O'Hagan]] believes Diaz imbues Fiona with \"easygoing shrillness that modern eight-year-olds may find likeable\",<ref name=\":55\" /> while the ''Deseret News''<nowiki/>' Jeff Vice wrote that Diaz proves more than merely \"a pretty face.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/700002713/Shrek.html|title=Film review: Shrek|last=Vice|first=Jeff|date=August 24, 2004|website=[[Deseret News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Bruce Westbrook of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' reviewed Diaz as an improvement upon \"the spunkiness of today's heroines\" by \"packing surprise punches that would have suited her role in ''Charlie's Angels''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/movies/article/Shrek-1527382.php|title=Shrek|last=Westbook|first=Bruce|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Houston Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 4, 2010}}</ref> [[Turner Classic Movies]] believes Diaz's performance earned the actress \"a legion of younger fans\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/50053%7C173505/Cameron-Diaz/biography.html|title=Cameron Diaz \u2013 Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref> a sentiment with which ''[[TV Guide]]'' agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/cameron-diaz/bio/143212/|title=Cameron Diaz \u2013 Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TV Guide]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020|quote=Younger viewers fell for the California beauty ... when she voiced Princess Fiona in the beloved animated fairy tale Shrek and its sequels.}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]''<nowiki/>' Cynthia Fuchs, reviewing the fourth film, described the princess as \"always at least a little wonderful, patient, and smart (and now awesomely Amazonian),\" and found herself wishing Fiona would discover a [[Parallel universes in fiction|parallel universe]] in which she is truly appreciated.<ref name=\":68\" /> \n\nNot all reviews were positive. Finding Fiona's fight scene unnecessary, Derek Armstrong of [[AllMovie]] wrote that it \"leaves things feeling scattershot\" despite its appealing visuals.<ref name=\":78\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/shrek-v242627/review|title=Shrek (2001) \u2013 Review by Derek Armstrong|last=Armstrong|first=Derek|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[AllMovie]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> In a negative review, [[CNN]]'s Paul Tatara dismissed Fiona as \"bland\" and the film's \"only miscue among the characters\".<ref name=\":8\" /> Criticizing her design, Tatara felt the princess \"gives off the creepy air of a possessed [[Barbie doll|Barbie Doll]]\" while \"Diaz's [[Valley girl|California-girl]] line readings simply don't fit the character.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news|last=Tatara|first=Paul|url=http://www.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/17/review.shrek/index.html|title=Review: 'Shrek' a wild, enchanted, hilarious tale|date=May 18, 2001|work=|access-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live|website=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Similarly, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''<nowiki/>'s Mark Caro found Fiona's design generic and Barbie-like, but admitted these characteristics benefit the film's plot and themes.<ref name=\":61\" /> Anthony Quinn of ''[[The Independent]]'' found Fiona's realism particularly troubling, suggesting that the animators should have simply \"invite[d] Cameron Diaz to play her as well as voice her.\"<ref name=\":56\" /> Similarly, ''[[The New Yorker]]'' film critic [[Anthony Lane]] felt the character was too realistic, writing, \"What I don't want is to gaze at Princess Fiona ... and wonder if she is supposed to resemble Cameron Diaz\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2001/05/21/fantasy-land|title=Fantasy Land|last=Lane|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Lane|date=May 21, 2001|website=[[The New Yorker]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]], film critic for ''[[The Guardian]]'', dismissed Fiona and the film's human characters as \"disappointingly ordinary looking and unexpressive,\" comparing them to [[Clay animation|claymation]],<ref name=\":57\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/jun/29/1|title=Shrek|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Bradshaw|date=June 29, 2001|website=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> while ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''<nowiki/>'s Peter Rainer agreed that human characters such as Fiona \"are less interesting\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/4698/|title=Troll on a Roll|last=Rainer|first=Peter|date=2001|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> Paul Malcolm of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' described Diaz's performance as \"insuperably flat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/film/trouble-in-fairyland-2133359|title=Trouble in Fairyland|last=Malcolm|first=Paul|date=May 16, 2001|website=[[LA Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Philippa Hawker of ''[[The Age]]'' felt the third film could benefited from Fiona being named Harold's heir, opposing the idea of relegating her to \"a cursory girl-power scenario\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/shrek-the-third-20070607-ge52kr.html|title=Shrek the Third|last=Hawker|first=Philippa|date=June 7, 2007|website=[[The Age]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Feminist analysis ===\n\nSome media publications have regarded Fiona as a feminist icon.<ref name=\":63\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2007/05/23/shrek-princess-goes-feminist-402110/|title=Shrek princess goes feminist|last=|first=|date=May 23, 2007|website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alloy.com/entertainment/cartoon-feminist-icons/13/|title=18 Cartoon Characters Who Are Actual Feminist Icons|last=Miles|first=Ellie|date=December 1, 2017|website=[[Clevver news|Alloy]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206170529/http://www.alloy.com/entertainment/cartoon-feminist-icons/13/|archive-date=December 6, 2017|access-date=October 3, 2018|quote=If you need reminding why Princess Fiona is a god damn feminist legend, just cast your mind back to the first Shrek film.}}</ref><ref name=\":39\" /><ref name=\":86\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/7776018.stm|title=The sexual revolution... in cartoon form|last=|first=|date=December 11, 2008|work=|access-date=December 23, 2018|website=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> Upon her debut, Fiona was celebrated by most critics \"as a radical new take on the princess myth\".<ref name=\":70\">{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/the-royal-wedding-and-the-lure-of-the-princess-myth-939|title=The royal wedding and the lure of the princess myth|last=Smith|first=Michelle|date=April 28, 2011|website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018|quote=Shrek\u2019s Princess Fiona ... was celebrated as a radical new take on the princess myth}}</ref> Fiona's subversion of common princess tropes continues to be widely discussed in the media.<ref name=\":65\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/movies/2018/3/13/17116436/cameron-diaz-best-performances-shrek-any-given-sunday|title=What Is Cameron Diaz's Best Performance?|last=Herman|first=Alison|date=March 13, 2018|website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018|quote=Fiona subverts the pretty-princess trope enough to provide fuel for undergrad media studies papers for decades to come}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' contributor Claudia Puig felt the first film boasts \"a wonderfully affirming message for girls courtesy of Fiona\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/dreamworks-animation-movies-ranked-best-worst-shrek-panda-dragon/|title=All 34 DreamWorks Animation Movies Ranked From Worst to Best (Photos)|last=Puig|first=Claudia|date=March 30, 2017|website=[[Wired.com|Wired]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Jack Rear, writing for Pretty 52, described Fiona as \"feminism goals\" due to her martial arts proficiency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pretty52.com/stylish/celebrity-adele-clapped-back-at-people-who-compared-her-to-princess-fiona-20170304|title=Adele Clapped Back At People Who Compared Her To Princess Fiona In The Best Way|last=Rear|first=Jack|date=March 4, 2017|website=Pretty 52|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> ''Affinity Magazine'' contributor Isabel Tovar identified the moment Fiona defeats Monsieur Hood as \"female empowering\", believing \"Fiona has been feminist queen since day one.\"<ref name=\":63\">{{cite web|url=http://culture.affinitymagazine.us/5-moments-that-prove-that-the-shrek-movies-are-the-best/|title=5 Moments That Prove That The Shrek Movies Are The Best|last=Tovar|first=Isabel|date=July 28, 2017|website=Affinity Magazine|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> Teresa Brickey of ''[[The Odyssey Online|The Odyssey]]'' said Fiona contested the [[patriarchy]] by \"accept[ing] her body ... who she loved, and fought for right to do her thing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/dear-kim-kardashian-shrek-is-more-feminist-than-you|title=Shrek Is More Feminist Than Kim Kardashian|last=Brickey|first=Teresa|date=May 30, 2016|website=[[The Odyssey Online|The Odyssey]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Reviewing ''Shrek Forever After'', [[Rachel Giese]] of [[CBC.ca|CBC]] found the character's \"[[Girl power|girl-power]] turn as a warrior princess\" to be one of the installment's most endearing changes.<ref name=\":35\" /> Crowning the character \"the best feminist action hero around\", Emily Shire of ''[[The Week]]'' deemed Fiona \"the kind of feminist action hero movies need more of\", describing her as a strong heroine who \"saves herself and loved ones\" while accepting the \"'ugly' and 'gross' aspects of herself\".<ref name=\":39\">{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/454355/sorry-katniss-princess-fiona-still-best-feminist-action-hero-around#!|title=Sorry Katniss, Princess Fiona is still the best feminist action hero around|last=Shire|first=Emily|date=December 16, 2013|website=[[The Week]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Shire also voiced her preference for Fiona over ''[[The Hunger Games franchise|The Hunger Games]]''<nowiki/>' [[Katniss Everdeen]] and the superheroine [[Wonder Woman]].<ref name=\":39\" /> Allison Maloney of [[The Shriver Report]] shared Shire's sentiments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shriverreport.org/the-best-time-in-history-to-lean-in-princess-fiona-the-role-model-and-the-brand-that-sold-strength-best/|title=The Best Time in History to Lean In, Princess Fiona the Role Model and the Brand That Sold Strength Best|last=Maloney|first=Allison|date=December 20, 2013|website=[[The Shriver Report]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Felicity Sleeman, a writer for ''[[Farrago (magazine)|Farrago]]'', believes \"Fiona completely dispels any misconceptions of the passive princess trope\", citing her as a [[strong female character]] \"able to stand up for herself and fight in ways that would typically be considered masculine.\"<ref name=\":73\">{{cite web|url=http://farragomagazine.com/2016/08/08/in-defense-of-shrek/|title=In Defense Of Shrek|last=Sleeman|first=Felicity|date=August 6, 2016|website=[[Farrago (magazine)|Farrago]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Sleeman continued that one of the most important components of Fiona's personality \"is that the films don\u2019t ignore or degrade any of her qualities that are considered typically feminine\", elaborating that her struggles over her appearance are \"significant in that it presents the ways in which so many girls are pressured by society to uphold a certain standard of beauty.\" Sleeman concluded, \"In an industry where female characters have so often portrayed as [[Secondary character|secondary characters]] defined by their beauty ... Fiona is a well-rounded character who represents an eclectic mix of traits that are representative of real women\", remaining feminine yet strong.<ref name=\":73\" /> Rachel O'Neill, a writer for ''[[TheJournal.ie|The Daily Edge]]'', identified Fiona as \"the first badass princess ... able to speak for herself\", joking, \"nobody can fling a mermaid quite like Fiona.\"<ref name=\":30\" />\n\nIn 2008, [[BBC News Online|BBC News]] named Fiona \"the next feminist icon\", believing the character retains \"a certain sex appeal which continues even after she changes into an ogre - perfectly underlining how attitudes have changed towards women in the 21st Century.\"<ref name=\":86\" /> ''[[HuffPost]]'' contributor Hayley Krischer cited Fiona as a rare example of a princess who \"br[oke] the mold\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/hayley-krischer/im-a-feminist-momand-my-d_b_998130.html|title=I'm a Feminist Mom \u2014 And My Daughter Loves Princesses|last=Krischer|first=Hayley|date=December 20, 2011|website=[[HuffPost]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Iona Tytler of [[Babe.net]] recognized Fiona among childhood feminist characters \"who got you where you are today\".<ref name=\":94\" /> Praising her independence, Tytler said Fiona \"overc[ame] the societal prejudice in her world that came with being an ogre\" while becoming \"more comfortable in her own skin.\"<ref name=\":94\">{{cite web|url=https://babe.net/2016/10/22/every-feminist-character-childhood-got-today-898|title=The feminist characters from your childhood who got you where you are today|last=Tytler|first=Iona|date=October 22, 2016|website=[[Babe.net]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Sarah Tutton, curator of the [[Australian Centre for the Moving Image]]'s DreamWorks exhibit, credits Fiona with \"br[eaking] the mould of the helpless princess,\" citing her as a modern-day feminist.<ref name=\":44\" /> Tutton also said the character \"completely subverts what it means to be a beautiful princess.\"<ref name=\":44\" /> ''Forbes'' contributor Dani Di Placido believes Fiona embodied characteristics associated with the unconventional, rebellious warrior princess several years before such traits became standard in film and television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danidiplacido/2018/08/24/nobody-knows-what-to-do-with-fairytale-princesses/#3870b6507277|title=Fairytale Princesses Are In A Strange Place Right Now|last=Di Placido|first=Dani|date=August 24, 2018|website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Similarly, the [[British Film Institute]]'s So Mayer wrote that heroines such as [[Merida (Disney)|Merida]] and [[Elsa (Frozen)|Elsa]] from Disney's ''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]'' (2012) and ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' (2013), respectively, were both \"late to the party compared to\" Fiona, reflecting, \"over the course of the trilogy she wanders the wilderness, turns down Lord Farquaad, survives imprisonment, decides she prefers being ogre to being human, and organises a resistance composed of fairytale princesses.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/news-bfi/list/feminist-guide-love-screen-list|title=The feminist's guide to love on screen: a list|last=Mayer|first=So|date=January 11, 2018|website=[[British Film Institute]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, ''Female Action Heroes: A Guide to Women in Comics, Video Games, Film, and Television'' author Gladys L. Knight wrote that Fiona challenged the manner in which medieval women are portrayed on screen.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Knight|first=Gladys L.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0PKSFHwhTGYC&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=action+hero+princess+fiona#v=onepage&q=action%20hero%20princess%20fiona&f=false|title=Female Action Heroes: A Guide to Women in Comics, Video Games, Film, and Television|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|year=2010|isbn=9780313376122|location=United States|page=176|pages=|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Mary Zeiss Stange, author of ''Encyclopedia of Women in Today's World, Volume 1'', cited Fiona as an example of an \"outstanding female action hero\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bOkPjFQoBj8C&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=action+hero+princess+fiona#v=onepage&q=action%20hero%20princess%20fiona&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Women in Today's World, Volume 1|last=Stange|first=Mary Zeiss|last2=Sloan|first2=Jane E.|last3=Oyster|first3=Carol K.|publisher=SAGE|year=2011|isbn=9781412976855|volume=1|location=United States|page=19|via=Google Books}}</ref>''[[Refinery29|Refinery 29]]''<nowiki/>'s Anne Cohen felt Fiona remains a strong heroine despite ''Shrek''<nowiki/>'s \"un-feminist plot\" featuring several men making decisions about her future without her involvement.<ref name=\":84\" /> Cohen praised Fiona for defending herself, defying stereotypes, speaking her mind and accepting her own flaws.<ref name=\":84\" /> Crowing Fiona an \"important cultural milestone\", the author concluded that she is \"fierce, honest [and] wonderful\" despite her unconventional appearance.<ref name=\":84\" /> \n\nSome critics felt Fiona's fighting prowess was otherwise undermined by her insecurities and motivations. Despite being impressed with the character's fighting ability, Furniss believes this contradicts with \"her need to seek authentication from a male romantic partner\", arguing that a true martial artist would few have concerns about outward appearance.<ref name=\":17\" /> Although acknowledging that the film demonstrates themes of [[inner beauty]] among \"women of all types\", the author argued that Fiona's understanding relies on male approval, referring to her relationships with both Farquaad and Shrek, and further observing that she struggles to use this same martial arts prowess to fend off Farquaad's guards.<ref name=\":17\" /> Furniss found it disappointing that her arc is \"activated by the kiss of a man\", but admitted the completion of Shrek's character development is similarly determined by him kissing Fiona.<ref name=\":17\" /> Furniss doubts Fiona would not have been able to accept her ogre form had Shrek decided to retreat to his swamp alone after kissing her.<ref name=\":17\" /> Author Margot Mifflin, writing for ''[[Salon magazine|Salon]]'', felt that some of Fiona's actions contradict with the film's morals about looks being less important, citing that she dislikes Farquaad more for his short stature than his cruelty towards others.<ref name=\":32\" /> She also found the princess in Steig's original story to be more [[Women's Liberation|liberated]] and less of a damsel in distress than Fiona.<ref name=\":32\" /> Despite describing the character's ogre form as \"an overfed [[Cabbage patch Doll|Cabbage Patch]] doll with the drowning eyes and apologetic expression of a [[Hummel figurines|Hummel figurine]]\", Mifflin found the fact that Fiona remains an ogre, fights, talks back and has more realistic [[body proportions]] to be ground-breaking, while describing her musical solo as one of the film's \"hilarious\" highlights.<ref name=\":32\" /> ''[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]''<nowiki/>'s Michelle Smith was unimpressed, writing that despite the character's fighting skills, Fiona remains \"desperate to follow the fairy tale script\" and believes marrying her rescuer is \"her ultimate reward\".<ref name=\":70\" />\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nFiona was celebrated as a positive role model by the [[Girl Scouts of the USA]],<ref name=\":92\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cinema.com/news/item/4096/camerons-princess-is-girl-scouts-poster-girl.phtml|title=Cameron's Princess Is Girl Scout's Poster Girl|last=|first=|date=May 22, 2001|website=Cinema.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> who used the character's likeness in several [[tie-in]] media to promote the organization's \"Issues for Girl Scouts\" movement and encourage \"girls to develop self-confidence and embrace diversity.\"<ref name=\":93\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/05/25/shrek-inspires-girl-scouts-girls-are-great-badges/|title=Shrek inspires Girl Scouts' ''Girls are great!'' badges|last=Lee|first=Alice M.|date=May 25, 2001|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The organization also hosted a free screening of the film in 2001, which was attended by an audience of 340.<ref name=\":93\" /> For her performance in ''Shrek'', Diaz won a [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kid's Choice Award]] for Best Burp,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cameron-diaz-actress-vol-57-no-18/feed/|title=Cameron Diaz: Actress|last=|first=|date=May 13, 2002|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> which the actress claims to be one of her greatest achievements.<ref name=\":9\" /> According to Daniel Kurland of [[Screen Rant]], Diaz \"remains a crucial component of what makes the movie work\" despite resembling an \"unsung hero\" throughout the franchise.<ref name=\":12\" /> Summarizing the actress' career, Kendall Fisher of [[E!|''E! Online'']] said Diaz \"voiced one of our favorite animated characters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/876836/cameron-diaz-turns-45-looking-back-at-her-impressive-career-evolution-from-the-mask-to-annie|title=Cameron Diaz Turns 45: Looking Back at Her Impressive Career Evolution From The Mask to Annie|last=Fisher|first=Kendall|date=August 30, 2017|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]'' ranked Shrek Diaz's best film, believing her performance as Fiona aged better than the film's [[Shrek Soundtrack|soundtrack]] and animation.<ref name=\":65\" /> Author Alison Herman elaborated that Fiona embraced her flaws and offered children \"an important lesson in both self-esteem and the comedic value of fart jokes\", while the actress \"holds her own against\" Myers and Murphy; \"as a character, Fiona subverts the pretty-princess trope enough to provide fuel for undergrad media studies papers for decades to come\".<ref name=\":65\" />\n\n''Marie Claire'' ranked Fiona Diaz's third best \"Movie Moments That Made Us Fall In Love With Her\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.co.uk/entertainment/tv-and-film/cameron-s-best-on-screen-moments-35410|title=The Cameron Diaz Movie Moments That Made Us Fall In Love With Her|last=|first=|date=December 5, 2014|website=[[Marie Claire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> In addition to ranking Fiona the fourth best role of Diaz's career following her retirement in 2018, Samarth Goyal of the ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' crowned Fiona \"one of the most loved animated characters of the 21st century\", crediting her with making Diaz \"a big star.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/there-s-something-about-cameron-diaz-here-s-looking-at-five-of-her-best-films/story-WrUssDa4GUo3alu5Gq57AK.html|title=There's something about Cameron Diaz: Here's looking at five of her best films|last=Goyal|first=Samarth|date=April 3, 2018|website=[[Hindustan Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> In 2011, ''[[Gulf News]]'' ranked Diaz among \"Hollywood's A-list of most popular voice actors\",<ref name=\":13\" /> with ''Forbes'' reporting in 2010 that the actress was mentioned in the media approximately 1,809 times while promoting the most recent ''Shrek'' film.<ref name=\":21\" /> ''[[Teen Vogue]]'' considered Fiona among the \"17 Best Princesses in Movies and TV\", praising the character for learning \"to love herself.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/best-princesses-movie-tv|title=17 Best Princesses in Movies and TV|last=McGrath|first=Justine|date=|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> [[NBC New York]]'s Bryan Alexander described Fiona as \"the world's hottest ogre\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Why-Fiona-Taking-Her-Hair-Down-Is-a-Really-Big-Deal-94165809.html|title=Cameron Diaz's Ogre Hair Style Took a Team of 20 for \"Shrek\"|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=May 18, 2010|website=[[NBC New York]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> while [[Stephen Hunter]], film critic for ''The Washington Post'', found hearing Diaz's voice from a computer-animated character \"kind of hot\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/entertainment/movies/reviews/shrekhunter.htm|title='Shrek' Is a Fractured Fairy Tale With Its Heart Firmly in Place|last=Hunter|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Hunter|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> To promote ''Shrek 2'', ice cream restaurant [[Baskin-Robbins]] named a flavor after the character, entitled Fiona's Fairytale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2004-05-19/lifestyle/0405170358_1_princess-fiona-green-ketchup-mms|title=It's Easy Being Green|last=Goldberg|first=Carole|date=May 19, 2004|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Described as \"pink and purple swirled\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.restaurantnewsresource.com/article11004.html|title=Baskin-Robbins Unveils Several Enchanting 'Shrek 2' Ice Cream Creations|last=|first=|date=May 19, 2004|website=Restaurant News Resource|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> the ice cream was [[cotton candy]]-flavored.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2004-05-14-0405150020-story.html|title='Shrek' message, marketing remain the same|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2004|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/despite-what-kermit-says-shrek-is-cool-with-his-color/article_1ee00456-d27d-5dc5-b129-21def658a146.html|title=Despite what Kermit says, Shrek is cool with his color|last=Goldberg|first=Carol|date=May 23, 2004|website=[[NWI Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Shrek}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fiona, Princess}}\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Female characters in film]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Fictional female martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional ogres]]\n[[Category:Fictional princesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Martial artists characters in films]]\n[[Category:Shrek characters]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures cartoons and characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional feminist characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional shapeshifters]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{short description|Fictional character in the Shrek franchise}}\n{{Infobox character\n| colour             = #00663A\n| name               = Princess Fiona\n| series             = [[Shrek (film series)|Shrek]]\n| image              = {{nowrap|[[File:Princess Fiona.png|130px]][[File:PrincessFionaHuman.jpg|160px]]}}\n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = Fiona as an Ogre (left) and as a Human (right)\n| first              = ''[[Shrek]]'' (2001)\n| creator            = [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]]<br>[[Terry Rossio]]<br> [[Joe Stillman]] <br> [[Roger S. H. Schulman]]\n| voice              = [[Cameron Diaz]] (2001\u20132010)<br />[[Holly Fields]] (singing voice and merchandise)\n| species            = [[Ogre]] <br> [[Human]] (formerly)\n| status             = [[Deceased]]\n| gender             = Female\n| title              = [[Princess]]\n| family             = [[King Harold (Shrek)|King Harold]] (deceased father)<br>[[Queen Lillian]] (mother)<br>[[Arthur Pendragon (Shrek)|Arthur Pendragon]] (cousin)\n| spouse             = [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]]\n| children           = [[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|Felicia]] (daughter)<br>[[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|Fergus]] (son)<br>[[List of Shrek characters#Farkle, Fergus and Felicia|Farkle]] (son)\n}}\n'''Princess Fiona'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/shrek/cast/134500/|title=Shrek \u2013 Cast & Crew|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TV Guide]]|id=The character is officially credited as \"Princess Fiona\", as opposed to simply \"Fiona\".|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918230927/https://www.tvguide.com/movies/shrek/cast/134500/|archive-date=September 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8a5b3173|title=Shrek 2 (2004)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[British Film Institute]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> is a fictional character in [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]]' ''[[Shrek (franchise)|Shrek]]'' franchise, first appearing in the [[Animated film|animated]] film ''[[Shrek]]'' (2001). One of the film series' main characters, Fiona is introduced as a beautiful princess placed under a curse that transforms her into an ogre at night. She is initially determined to break the enchantment by kissing a prince, only to meet and fall in love with [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]], an ogre, instead. The character's origins and relationships with other characters are further explored in subsequent films; she introduces her new husband Shrek to her parents in ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004), becomes a mother by ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), and is an empowered warrior in ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010), much of which takes place in an [[Multiverse|alternate reality]] in which Fiona and Shrek never meet.\n\nCreated by screenwriters [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] and [[Terry Rossio]], Fiona is loosely based on the unsightly princess in [[William Steig]]'s children's book ''[[Shrek!]]'' (1990), from which her role and appearance were significantly modified. The screenwriters adapted the character into a princess under a [[shapeshifting]] enchantment, an idea that was initially greatly contested by other filmmakers. Fiona is voiced by actress [[Cameron Diaz]]. Comedian and actress [[Janeane Garofalo]] was originally cast as the character until she was fired from the first film with little explanation. Fiona was one of the first human characters to have a lead role in a [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] film, thus the animators aspired to make her both beautiful and realistic in appearance. However, an early [[test screening]] resulted in children reacting negatively towards the character's [[Uncanny valley|uncanny realism]], prompting the animators to re-design Fiona into a more stylized, cartoonish heroine. Several revolutionary achievements in computer animation were applied to the character to render convincing skin, hair, clothing and lighting.\n\nThe character is considered a [[parody]] of traditional princesses in both fairy tales and [[Disney Princess|animated Disney films]]. Reception towards Fiona has been mostly positive, with critics commending her characterization, [[martial arts]] prowess and Diaz's performance. However, reviewers were divided over the character's human design, some of whom were impressed by her technological innovations, while others found her realism unsettling and too similar to Diaz. Several media publications consider Fiona a feminist icon, crediting her with subverting princess and gender stereotypes by embracing her flaws. Diaz also became one of Hollywood's highest-paid actresses due to her role in the ''Shrek'' franchise, earning $3 million for her performance in the first film and upwards of $10 million for each sequel.\n\n== Development ==\n\n=== Creation and writing ===\n\n''Shrek'' is loosely based on [[William Steig]]'s [[Children\u2019s book|children's book]] ''[[Shrek!]]'' (1990),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.decentfilms.com/reviews/shrek|title=Shrek (2001)|date=2001|website=Decent Films|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116131854/http://www.decentfilms.com/reviews/shrek|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> but significantly deviates from its [[source material]], particularly pertaining to its main characters.<ref name=\":17\" /> In Steig's story, a witch [[Prediction|foretells]] that Shrek will marry an unnamed princess, who she describes as uglier in appearance than Shrek himself, enticing the ogre to seek her.<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tor.com/2010/02/02/introducing-the-original-shrek/|title=Introducing the Original Shrek!|last=Potter|first=Beth|date=February 2, 2010|website=[[Tor.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919171954/https://www.tor.com/2010/02/02/introducing-the-original-shrek/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Described as \"the most stunningly ugly princess on the surface of the planet\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/556154/how-shrek-went-from-worlds-biggest-animated-franchise-internets-creepiest-meme|title=How Shrek went from the world's biggest animated franchise to the internet's creepiest meme|last=Meslow|first=Scott|date=May 21, 2015|website=[[The Week]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414101453/https://theweek.com/articles/556154/how-shrek-went-from-worlds-biggest-animated-franchise-internets-creepiest-meme|archive-date=April 14, 2019|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Steig's princess bears little resemblance to Fiona, but the two characters are immediately attracted to each other and wed with little [[Conflict (narrative)|conflict]].<ref name=\":16\" /><ref name=\":17\" /> Animation historian [[Maureen Furniss]], writing for [[Animation World Network]], identified the fact that Shrek's [[love interest]] is altered from \"a really ugly woman\" into a beautiful princess as the film's most significant modification.<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/shrek-something-old-something-new|title=Shrek: Something Old, Something New|last=Furniss|first=Maureen|authorlink=Maureen Furniss|date=May 31, 2001|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726031123/https://www.awn.com/animationworld/shrek-something-old-something-new|archive-date=July 26, 2019|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> In an effort to expand the plot while making its characters more visually appealing and [[marketable]] \"from a Hollywood\" perspective, the writers decided to adapt ''Shrek!''<nowiki/>'s princess into a beautiful maiden who has been cursed to become ugly only during evenings, which she is forced to conceal from the film's other characters, thus providing \"narrative motivation for not showing her ogre manifestation.\"<ref name=\":17\" /> Furthermore, Furniss observed that [[Lord Farquaad]]'s romantic interest in Fiona is more practical since he is vain and only attracted to her beauty, while his main motivation remains to marry a princess so that he can rule Duloc.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nFeeling that her curse remaining undiscovered until the end was unsuitable for a feature-length film, screenwriters [[Ted Elliott (screenwriter)|Ted Elliott]] and [[Terry Rossio]] introduced the concept of a [[shapeshifting]] princess, which was rejected by the other filmmakers for six months because they found it \"too complex\" for a fairy tale.<ref name=\":60\">{{cite web|url=https://creativescreenwriting.com/shrek/|title=Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio on Shrek|last=Shewman|first=Den|last2=Ryfle|first2=Steve|date=June 9, 2016|website=Creative Screenwriting|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905220452/https://creativescreenwriting.com/shrek/|archive-date=September 5, 2017|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> Elliot and Rossio contested that similar ideas had been used successfully in Disney's ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989) and ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (1991), ultimately convincing the studio by referring to Fiona as an enchanted princess instead.<ref name=\":60\" /> Some writers expressed concerns over whether turning Fiona into an ogre full-time once she professes her love for Shrek suggested \"that ugly people belong with ugly people.\"<ref name=\":60\" /> Rossio explained that since Fiona shape-shifts, the best moral is \"'Even princesses who change their shapes can find love too.' And Shrek would love her in all of her varied forms.\"<ref name=\":60\" /> Elliot elaborated that this prompts audiences to debate if Fiona's \"true form\" is beautiful or unattractive: \"Her true form is beautiful by day, ugly by night.' ... and she was trying to rid herself of part of who she truly was, because society maintained that was wrong.\"<ref name=\":60\" /> The studio ultimately conceded that Fiona remain an ogre, which Elliot considers to be \"a more conventional idea\".<ref name=\":60\" /> \n\nIn early drafts of the script, Fiona is born an ogre to human parents, who lock her in a tower to conceal the true nature of their daughter's appearance,<ref name=\":28\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/19/31.aspx|title=Recycling, \"Shrek\" style|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=May 18, 2004|website=Jim Hill Media|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010164842/http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/19/31.aspx|archive-date=October 10, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> lying to the kingdom that she is a beautiful princess.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/shrek-dreamworks-behind-scenes-hidden-trivia/|title=26 Crazy Revelations Behind The Making Of Shrek|last=Kurland|first=Daniel|date=July 15, 2018|website=[[Screen Rant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191018040320/https://screenrant.com/shrek-dreamworks-behind-scenes-hidden-trivia/|archive-date=October 18, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> One day, Fiona escapes and seeks assistance from a witch named Dama Fortuna, who offers her a choice between two potions: one will turn the princess beautiful, while the other guarantees Fiona's happily ever after.<ref name=\":28\" /> Fiona ignorantly drinks the \"Beauty\" potion for which she does not realize there is a [[Fine print|catch]],<ref name=\":28\" /> as the potion renders her human during the day only to revert her to an ogre every night.<ref name=\":12\" /> The writers originally intended for Fiona's [[backstory]] to be fully animated and used as the film's [[prologue]], but discarded the idea after [[Test audience|test audiences]] deemed it too depressing.<ref name=\":28\" /> Entitled \"Fiona's Prologue\", the sequence was [[Storyboard|storyboarded]] but never animated.<ref name=\":29\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/345217/Shrek/notes.html|title=Shrek (2001) \u2013 Notes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TCM.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191010190649/http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/345217/Shrek/notes.html|archive-date=October 10, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> A second abandoned scene entitled \"Fiona Gets Them Lost\" follows Fiona, Shrek and [[Donkey (Shrek)|Donkey]] after she is and they become trapped in a cave; an action sequence inspired by the film ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' (1984) ensues.<ref name=\":29\" /> In the writers' original draft, Fiona's monstrous form was to have a physical altercation reminiscent of [[Hong Kong action films]] with Shrek once he discovers her, assuming that the monster has harmed Fiona.<ref name=\":60\" /> The idea was abandoned because, according to Elliot, few were familiar [[Hong Kong Cinema|Hong Kong cinema]]'s \"emphasis on action and physicality\" in comparison to more violent American films, explaining, \"no matter how much we described it, [the studio] ... imagined this violent, knock-down, [[Steven Seagal|Steven Segal]]-type, bone-cracking fight\", while some female crew members protested that the concept was [[misogynistic]] towards Fiona.<ref name=\":60\" />\n\nElliott and Rossio had suggested revisiting the discussion about Fiona's true nature is beautiful or an ogre in a potential sequel, but the idea was rejected.<ref name=\":60\" /> The directors spent four months brainstorming several new ideas for the sequel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=3572710|title=Director Andrew Adamson on Shrek 2 and The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe|last=Baillie|first=Russell|date=June 28, 2004|website=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921001608/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/lifestyle/news/article.cfm?c_id=6&objectid=3572710|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref> before ultimately determining that the only logical \"jump off point\" was one of the few areas not explored in the first film: Fiona's parents' reaction to their daughter both marrying and remaining an ogre.<ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-shrek-2-directors|title=INT: Shrek 2 directors|last=JoBlo|date=May 21, 2004|website=[[JoBlo.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920085450/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-shrek-2-directors|archive-date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> ''Shrek 2'' director [[Kelly Asbury]] explained that introducing Fiona's parents presented an entirely \"new story to go on, and a whole new place to go.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/extras/features/4664-the-shrek-2-cast-and-crew-talk|title=The Shrek 2 Cast and Crew Talk|last=|first=|date=May 11, 2004|website=[[ComingSoon.net]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181108144426/http://www.comingsoon.net/extras/features/4664-the-shrek-2-cast-and-crew-talk|archive-date=November 8, 2018|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Additionally, ''Shrek 2'' reveals why Fiona was locked in a tower in the first place,<ref name=\":5\" /> with the filmmakers realizing they could use some of the first film's abandoned concepts to gradually uncover more details about Fiona's story throughout the remainder of the series.<ref name=\":85\">{{cite web|url=https://bluray.highdefdigest.com/4164/shrek_whole_story.html|title=Shrek: The Whole Story|last=Peck|first=Aaron|date=December 8, 2010|website=High Def Digest|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923005900/https://bluray.highdefdigest.com/4164/shrek_whole_story.html|archive-date=September 23, 2018|url-status=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> For ''Shrek 2'', the filmmakers decided to resurrect the idea of Dama Fortuna, re-imagining her as Fiona's conniving [[fairy godmother]] and the sequel's main villain, who uses magic against Fiona and Shrek's marriage.<ref name=\":28\" />\n\n=== Voice ===\n\nFiona is voiced by American actress [[Cameron Diaz]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://parade.com/76403/iraphael/famous-animated-voices/|title=Famous Animated Voices|last=Raphael|first=Isabelle|date=July 26, 2011|website=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005030807/https://parade.com/76403/iraphael/famous-animated-voices/|archive-date=October 5, 2018|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> one of the franchise's three main cast members.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/1462103/Money-talks-for-cast-of-Shrek-2.html|title=Money talks for cast of Shrek 2|last=Davies|first=Hugh|date=May 17, 2004|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620164507/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/1462103/Money-talks-for-cast-of-Shrek-2.html|archive-date=June 20, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Diaz voiced Fiona in all four installments of the film series over the course of ten years.<ref name=\":79\">{{cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/cam-regrets-fionas-californian-tones-458354.html|title=Cam regrets Fiona's Californian tones|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[The Irish Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011013801/https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/cam-regrets-fionas-californian-tones-458354.html|archive-date=October 11, 2018|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":80\">{{cite web|url=https://filmreviewonline.com/2010/05/19/shrek-forever-after-cameron-diaz-on-love-and-happiness/|title=Shrek Forever After \u2013 Cameron Diaz on love and happiness and the ending|last=Sloane|first=Judy|date=May 19, 2010|website=Film Review Online|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011013919/https://filmreviewonline.com/2010/05/19/shrek-forever-after-cameron-diaz-on-love-and-happiness/|archive-date=October 11, 2018|url-status=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> The role was originally intended for comedian and actress [[Janeane Garofalo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2011/08/the-lost-roles-of-janeane-garofalo.html|title=The Lost Roles of Janeane Garofalo|last=Evans|first=Bradford|date=August 11, 2011|website=[[Vulture.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918231049/http://www.vulture.com/2011/08/the-lost-roles-of-janeane-garofalo.html|archive-date=September 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> who was fired from the first film and ultimately replaced with Diaz.<ref name=\":88\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/160924-5-actors-almost-cast-in-shrek-because-mike-myers-wasnt-supposed-to-voice-the-ogre|title=5 Actors Almost Cast In 'Shrek,' Because Mike Myers Wasn't Supposed To Voice The Ogre|last=Denninger|first=Lindsay|date=May 18, 2016|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180718030554/https://www.bustle.com/articles/160924-5-actors-almost-cast-in-shrek-because-mike-myers-wasnt-supposed-to-voice-the-ogre|archive-date=July 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Garofalo maintains that she was fired without an explanation, joking, \"I assume [it is] because I sound like a man sometimes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2756227/janeane-garofalo-talks-ratatouille/#fbid=XY8O2chJ8lO|title=Janeane Garofalo Talks Ratatouille|last=Villalobos|first=Brian|date=June 29, 2007|website=[[MTV]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806190951/http://www.mtv.com/news/2756227/janeane-garofalo-talks-ratatouille/|archive-date=August 6, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> However, it is believed that re-casting Fiona resulted from the death of comedian [[Chris Farley]], who was originally cast as Shrek and had already recorded most of the character's dialogue until he died during production, at which point he was replaced with actor [[Mike Myers]].<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/64343/15-giant-facts-about-shrek|title=15 Giant Facts About Shrek|last=Cormier|first=Roger|date=March 22, 2016|website=[[Mental Floss]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624202213/http://mentalfloss.com/article/64343/15-giant-facts-about-shrek|archive-date=June 24, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> According to film historian Jim Hill, the filmmakers originally cast Garofalo as Fiona because they had felt that the actress' \"abrasive, sarcastic [[comic persona]]\" would serve as an ideal [[Foil (literature)|foil]] to Farley's positive approach to the titular character,<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.verbicidemagazine.com/2015/08/06/chris-farley-shrek-video-watch/|title=Chris Farley's Version of Shrek Has Leaked Online|last=|first=|date=August 6, 2015|website=Verbicide Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919024813/https://www.verbicidemagazine.com/2015/08/06/chris-farley-shrek-video-watch/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> but eventually relented that Garofalo was \"too downbeat\" for the film's lighter tone, offering the role to Diaz.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/17/how-quot-shrek-quot-went-from-being-a-train-wreck-to-one-for-the-record-books.aspx|title=How \"Shrek\" went from being a train wreck to one for the record books|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=May 16, 2004|website=Jim Hill Media|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423190123/http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2004/05/17/how-quot-shrek-quot-went-from-being-a-train-wreck-to-one-for-the-record-books.aspx|archive-date=April 23, 2019|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> With a \"sweeter\" version of Fiona introduced, Shrek was developed into a more pessimistic character.<ref name=\":6\" /> [[File:Cameron diaz 2010.jpg|left|thumb|Actress [[Cameron Diaz]] (2010) has voiced Fiona for the entire series.|249x249px|alt=]]\n\nFiona was Diaz's first animated role.<ref name=\":25\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-05-31-0105310026-story.html|title=A timely morality play|last=Munoz|first=Lorenza|date=May 31, 2001|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920011102/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-05-31-0105310026-story.html|archive-date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]] invited Diaz to star in an animated film about an ogre and a princess who learn to accept both themselves and each other.<ref name=\":25\" /> In addition to the film's positive message, Diaz was drawn to the idea of co-starring alongside Myers, [[Eddie Murphy]] and [[John Lithgow]].<ref name=\":25\" /> Approaching her role as though it were a [[Drama Film|dramatic]] performance, Diaz recorded most of her dialogue before a full script had been written, working closely with director [[Andrew Adamson]] to stage scenes before the film had been storyboarded.<ref name=\":25\" /> Prior to ''Shrek'', Diaz starred in the [[action-comedy]] film ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]'' (2000), a role for which she had undergone [[martial arts]] training.<ref name=\":26\" /> While recording the scene in which her character fights Monsieur Hood and his Merry Men, Diaz became quite animated, gesturing and occasionally uttering [[Cantonese]] phrases; her martial arts background is credited with benefiting the sequence.<ref name=\":26\" /> Diaz once burped during a recording session, which was written into a scene for Fiona.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/leisure/movies/hollywood-s-a-list-of-most-popular-voice-actors-1.825243|title=Hollywood's A-list of most popular voice actors|last=Crane|first=Kelly|date=June 23, 2011|website=[[Gulf News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919132214/https://gulfnews.com/leisure/movies/hollywood-s-a-list-of-most-popular-voice-actors-1.825243|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Without a proper screenplay to aid her, Diaz found the improvisation required for some scenes one of the most challenging aspects of the recording process.<ref name=\":67\" /> The actress did not see the film's completed story until after she had finished working on the project on-and-off for two years, by which point she finally truly understood her \"character and ... what she was going through\".<ref name=\":25\" /> Myers was both impressed with and inspired by Diaz's commitment to her role, to the point that he felt he was acting opposite Fiona herself.<ref name=\":25\" /> Asbury recalled that Diaz immediately \"nailed\" her character, elaborating, \"She had this certain thing about her voice where she could be headstrong and know exactly what she wants and be confident, but also have this touch of sweet naivete and all make it completely believable.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> Despite admiring the performances of her predominately male co-stars, Diaz seldom worked directly with them throughout the ''Shrek'' series.<ref name=\":48\" />\n\nDiaz enjoyed \"the good feeling\" she experienced playing Fiona,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.accessonline.com/articles/justin-cameron-reunite-at-shrek-the-third-premiere-59282/|title=Justin & Cameron Reunite At 'Shrek The Third' Premiere|last=|first=|date=May 7, 2007|website=[[Access Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918231237/https://www.accessonline.com/articles/justin-cameron-reunite-at-shrek-the-third-premiere-59282/|archive-date=September 18, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> and preferred voicing her character as an ogre over a princess, the former of which she finds truly beautiful.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/dec/05/news|title=Cameron Diaz on board for Shrek sequel|last=|first=|date=December 5, 2001|website=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Apart from the ''Charlie's Angels'' sequel ''[[Charlie's Angels: Full Throttle]]'' (2003), ''Shrek'' is the only franchise in which Diaz reprised a role.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-total-film-interview-cameron-diaz/|title=The Total Film Interview - Cameron Diaz|last=|first=|date=July 1, 2007|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> The origins of Fiona's parents had not yet been disclosed in the first film, therefore Diaz voiced Fiona using an [[American Accent|American accent]].<ref name=\":79\" /> After discovering that English actors [[Julie Andrews]] and [[John Cleese]] would voice her parents [[Queen Lillian]] and [[King Harold (Shrek)|King Harold]], respectively, in ''Shrek 2'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hollywood//articleshow/37015964.cms|title=English Fiona|last=|first=|date=May 21, 2010|website=[[Ahmedabad Mirror]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> Diaz regretted voicing her character with her default [[California accent|Californian accent]] as opposed to a [[British accent]].<ref name=\":80\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a221338/diaz-i-wish-fiona-had-a-british-accent/|title=Diaz: 'I wish Fiona had a British accent'|last=Minaya|first=Marcell|date=May 23, 2010|website=[[Digital Spy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011053616/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a221338/diaz-i-wish-fiona-had-a-british-accent/|archive-date=October 11, 2018|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> She identified her accent as one of the few things she would have changed about her performance in retrospect.<ref name=\":80\" /> Bob Thompson of the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' observed that few, if any, critics took issue with Diaz's inconsistency.<ref name=\":81\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20100528/285022620666276|title=Cameron Diaz finds it easy to be green|last=Thompson|first=Bob|date=May 28, 2010|work=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|access-date=October 11, 2018|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> Although admitting that working on the films for only a few hours at a time sporadically sometimes resulted in her feeling as though she is not \"100 per cent involved ... at the same time, that character is so my character. I feel very possessive of Fiona. It's interesting to see something that's not actually tangible so fully embody your essence. It feels like I've lent something to this film that I could never give to any other film, in a weird way.\"<ref name=\":66\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/its-not-easy-being-green-20040529-gdxx8h.html|title=It's not easy being green|last=Horn|first=John|date=May 29, 2004|website=[[The Age]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Diaz would often defend Fiona's appearance from the press asking how she feels about playing an \"ugly\" character, explaining, \"It's shocking to me that that's the perception, just because she's big and round ... Her body is everything that she is inside. I love that she is the princess who isn\u2019t like all the other princesses. She doesn\u2019t look like them, and she's just as beloved and accepted.\"<ref name=\":62\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/getting-it-straight-from-the-women-of-shrek/|title=Getting it straight from the women of \"Shrek\"|last=Germain|first=David|date=May 23, 2007|website=[[Seattle Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> In ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), Diaz co-starred alongside her ex-boyfriend, singer [[Justin Timberlake]], with whom she had broken up the previous year.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.recordonline.com/article/20070507/entertain/70507017|title=Justin Timberlake and Cameron Diaz reunite at 'Shrek the Third' premiere|last=Cidoni|first=Michael|date=May 7, 2007|website=[[Recordonline.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Timberlake plays her character's cousin [[Arthur Pendragon (Shrek)|Arthur Pendragon]], heir to her late father's throne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/justin-timberlake-cameron-diaz-kiss-on-shrek-red-carpet/|title=Justin Timberlake & Cameron Diaz Kiss on Shrek Red Carpet|last=Hammel|first=Sara|date=May 7, 2007|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919024826/https://people.com/celebrity/justin-timberlake-cameron-diaz-kiss-on-shrek-red-carpet/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1501062/justin-timberlake-will-learn-his-lesson-in-shrek-3/|title=Justin Timberlake Will Learn His Lesson In 'Shrek 3'|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=May 2, 2005|website=[[MTV]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> ''Shrek 2'' features a brief reference to Timberlake; a picture of a young knight named \"Sir Justin\" appears in Fiona's childhood bedroom, which is believed to be a reference to their relationship.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/2004/05/17/Shrek-2-features-Timberlake-joke/6281084766400/|title='Shrek 2' features Timberlake joke|last=|first=|date=May 17, 2004|website=[[United Press International]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2007/shrek-the-third-fun-facts/|title=Shrek the Third fun facts|last=Armstrong|first=Josh|date=April 20, 2007|website=Animated Views|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> Diaz was unaware of Timberlake's [[Cameo appearance|cameo]] until watching the film, believing it had been finalized before they were a couple.<ref name=\":66\" /> Although Timberlake was initially cast as Arthur while he was still dating Diaz, producer [[Aron Warner]] maintains that Timberlake's involvement was not influenced by their relationship, insisting that he earned the role based on his own merit and comedic timing.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":49\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/king-shrek-hollywood-s-favourite-ogre-making-regal-return-1.236823|title=King Shrek, Hollywood's favourite ogre, making regal return|last=Germain|first=David|date=April 10, 2007|website=[[CTV News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The film's May 2007 premiere in Los Angeles was the first media event at which the former couple had been photographed since the end of their relationship.<ref name=\":3\" /> Director [[Mike Mitchell (director)|Mike Mitchell]] denied media speculation that Timberlake and his character's omission from ''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010) correlated to Diaz and Timberlake's breakup, explaining that Arthur was written out solely to allow more screen time for more relevant characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Justin-Timberlakes-Omission-from-Shrek-Not-Diaz-Related-94507314.html|title=Justin Timberlake's Omission from \"Shrek\" Not Diaz Related|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[NBC Chicago]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA filmmaker described Diaz as \"the rock\" of the franchise because \"She brings such a great spirit to these movies.\u201d<ref name=\":53\">{{cite web|url=http://mantras.tv/animation/movies/Shrek%20the%20Third.pdf|title=Shrek the Third|last=|first=|date=2007|website=Mantras.TV|page=9|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Following the release of ''Shrek Forever After'', the series' final installment,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/181220/cam-diaz-prefers-ogre-green-to-angels-leather|title=Cam Diaz Prefers Ogre Green to Angels Leather|last=Huntington|first=Heather|date=May 15, 2010|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Diaz reflected that the ''Shrek'' films had remained her \"safety net\" for several years, describing the period as \"a decade of knowing that you finish one and for the next two years we'll be making another one\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/16/movies/16shrek.html|title=He's Big, He's Green, and He's Gone|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave|date=May 14, 2010|work=|access-date=September 18, 2018|author-link=Dave Itzkoff|website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> She remains hopeful for future sequels,<ref name=\":0\" /> joking, \"I'm ready for 'Shrek 18,' if they haven't killed Fiona off by then.\"<ref name=\":49\" /> Diaz was saddened to bid farewell to her character,<ref name=\":42\">{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/cameron-diaz-on-her-shrek-role/93734154/|title=Cameron Diaz on her \"Shrek\" role|last=Covert|first=Colin|date=May 15, 2010|website=[[Star Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103183535/http://www.startribune.com/cameron-diaz-on-her-shrek-role/93734154/|archive-date=January 3, 2018|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/celebrity-news/swamp-monster-cameron-diaz-983747|title='Swamp monster' Cameron Diaz|last=|first=|date=June 28, 2010|website=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Independent Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> admitting that she took the films and Fiona for granted until the end because she always assumed she would be invited back within a few months for another installment.<ref name=\":48\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/saturday-star/20100717/282226597000502|title=Cameron Diaz on becoming Princess Fiona|date=July 17, 2010|work=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|Saturday Star]]|access-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922135733/https://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/saturday-star/20100717/282226597000502|archive-date=September 22, 2018|via=[[PressReader]]}}</ref> Considering the role \"a privilege and honor\",<ref name=\":48\" /> Diaz maintains that Fiona is the role for which she is most recognized by children,<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/the-interview-cameron-diaz-185337.html|title=The Interview: Cameron Diaz|last=Lyons|first=Saffron|date=July 21, 2002|work=|access-date=September 18, 2018|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> but she prefers when parents allow them to pretend that her character truly exists without revealing her voice actress,<ref name=\":0\" /> often attempting to prevent parents from exposing the truth.<ref name=\":81\" /> Diaz elaborated that Fiona has become \"part of my screen persona. Rather than me putting myself through her I think she comes through me in a weird way. When people think of me they think of Fiona, it's not the other way around.\"<ref name=\":67\" /> Diaz believes that her popularity has greatly increased since voicing the character.<ref name=\":9\" /> Despite being currently in development, Diaz has yet to confirm whether or not she will reprise her role in a fifth film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/3/31/15141312/shrek-5-reinvent-franchise-dreamworks|title=Shrek 5 will completely reinvent the series|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=March 31, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> although she had previously said that she would return for a fifth installment if asked.<ref name=\":81\" />\n\nDiaz's role in the ''Shrek'' series is believed to have contributed to her becoming one of Hollywood's wealthiest actresses by 2008.<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/top-10-highest-paid-actresses/8/|title=Top 10 Highest-Paid Actresses \u2013 3. Cameron Diaz ($15+ Million/Movie)|last=|first=|date=2007|website=[[CBS News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.urbandaddy.com/articles/41889/a-farewell-to-cameron-diazs-acting-career|title=A Farewell to Cameron Diaz's Acting Career|last=Ashcraft|first=Kady Ruth|date=March 12, 2018|website=[[UrbanDaddy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921231746/https://www.urbandaddy.com/articles/41889/a-farewell-to-cameron-diazs-acting-career|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018|quote=She went on to voice the ogress Fiona in the Shrek franchise, a career move that in 2008 ranked her as Forbes\u2019 richest female celebrity.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/celebrity/a3069/cameron-diaz-interview-environment/|title=Cameron Diaz's Excellent Adventure|last=Kaylin|first=Lucy|date=June 2, 2009|website=[[Marie Claire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2018|quote=the highest-earning actress in Hollywood, thanks largely to some nimble voice work as the ogress Fiona in the Shrek franchise.}}</ref> After being paid $3 million for the first film,<ref name=\":77\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2008-12-04/news/0812030245_1_shrek-jean-vander-pyl-princess-fiona|title=Is a voice worth that much?|last=Lewis|first=Herschell Gordon|authorlink=Herschell Gordon Lewis|date=December 4, 2008|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181006000742/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2008-12-04/news/0812030245_1_shrek-jean-vander-pyl-princess-fiona|archive-date=October 6, 2018|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Diaz originally re-negotiated to receive $5 million for ''Shrek 2'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/film/news/inside-move-shrek-2-s-expensive-voices-1117802559/|title=Inside Move: 'Shrek 2's' expensive voices|last=Brodesser|first=Claude|date=July 10, 2001|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> estimated to be an hourly salary of $35,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=103716|title=Shrek Stars' Salaries Jump for Sequel|last=|first=|date=July 11, 2002|website=[[ABC News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919024830/https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=103716|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.ign.com/articles/2001/07/12/shrek-2-cast-sees-green|title=Shrek 2 Cast Sees Green|last=Linder|first=Brian|date=June 21, 2012|website=[[IGN]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> She ultimately earned between $10 to $15 million for reprising her role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/12/28/voiceover-industry-attracts-big-celebs-gets-more-competitive.html|title=Big-name stars flooding market for voice-over work, experts say|last=McKay|first=Hollie|date=December 28, 2012|website=[[Fox News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404091951/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/12/28/voiceover-industry-attracts-big-celebs-gets-more-competitive.html|archive-date=April 4, 2018|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/45762/diaz-sandler-really-rich|title=Diaz, Sandler Really Rich|last=Byrne|first=Bridget|date=August 29, 2003|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/shrek-2-189216/|title=Shrek 2|last=Travers|first=Peter|date=2004|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/aug/29/entertainment/et-quick29.2|title=Diaz's pay is said to be a record|last=Dutka|first=Elaine|date=August 29, 2003|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> For ''Shrek the Third'', Diaz was paid $30 million, her highest salary at that point,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/top-actress-salaries-are-quote-156261|title=Top actress salaries are quote-worthy|last=Grabicki|first=Michelle|date=December 4, 2007|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> due to securing a significant portion of the installment's profits.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/reese-angelina-lead-list-of-highest-paid-actresses/|title=Reese, Angelina Lead List of Highest-Paid Actresses|last=Silverman|first=Steven M.|date=November 30, 2007|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920011221/https://people.com/movies/reese-angelina-lead-list-of-highest-paid-actresses/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|access-date=September 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/30/AR2007113000445.html?noredirect=on|title=Reese Witherspoon Highest-Paid Actress|last=|first=|date=December 1, 2007|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> She earned $10 million for ''Shrek Forever After''.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/03/24/hollywood-movies-animation-business-entertainment-animation-stars_slide.html|title=Slide Show: Hollywood's Animation A-List|last=Pomerantz|first=Dorothy|date=Mar 24, 2010|website=[[Forbes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/03/24/hollywood-movies-animation-business-entertainment-animation-stars.html#59ecf76a2ffc|title=Hollywood's Animation A-List|last=Pomerantz|first=Dorothy|date=March 24, 2010|website=[[Forbes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=July 19, 2018}}</ref> In 2010, ''Forbes'' ranked Diaz Hollywood's second highest-earning voice actor, behind only Myers.<ref name=\":21\" /> On the actress' lucrative earnings, filmmaker [[Herschell Gordon Lewis]] wrote in an article for the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' \"Sure, she captured the character well. Yes, the 'Shrek' movies invariably are box office successes. But can anyone say that if the voice of Princess Fiona were that of a competent actress other than Cameron Diaz, the movie would have flopped?\"<ref name=\":77\" /> Actress [[Holly Fields]] has provided the character's singing voice in the film, in addition to voicing the character in several video games, toys, commercials and amusement park rides. Fields is often hired to imitate Diaz, describing the experience as one of her \"coolest jobs\".<ref name=\":91\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.diabolikdvd.com/holly-fields-interview/|title=Holly Fields Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=DiabolikDVD|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Design and animation ===\n\nFiona is the franchise's [[Leading lady|female lead]] and Shrek's [[romantic interest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=pt&u=https://super.abril.com.br/mundo-estranho/que-personagens-famosos-sao-vitimas-das-parodias-de-shrek/&prev=search|title=What famous characters are \"victims\" of Shrek's parodies?|last=da Silva|first=C\u00edntia Cristina|date=April 18, 2011|website=[[Superinteressante]]|language=Portuguese|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\":48\" /> ''Shrek'' was the first computer-animated film to feature human characters in lead roles,<ref name=\":32\">{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2001/05/24/anti_shrek/|title=\"Shrek\" is not Shrek!|last=Mifflin|first=Margot|date=May 24, 2001|website=[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/co-directing-shrek-victoria-jenson|title=On Co-Directing Shrek: Victoria Jenson|last=Koseluk|first=Chris|date=May 10, 2001|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018|quote=This is the first time you really see humans appear in principal roles in a CG film}}</ref> thus director [[Vicky Jenson|Vicki Jenson]] believed its heroine should be beautiful yet convincing.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/06/18/shrek_2001_directors_interview.shtml|title=Andrew Adamson and Vicky Jenson|last=Falk|first=Ben|date=2001|website=[[BBC]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181030023829/http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/06/18/shrek_2001_directors_interview.shtml|archive-date=October 30, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Elliott and Rossio had originally envisioned Fiona's monstrous form as furry in appearance, wanting her to resemble an entirely unique character as opposed to simply a female version of Shrek, but the filmmakers struggled to agree upon her final design.<ref name=\":60\" /> Aiming to achieve stylized realism,<ref name=\":69\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/844510/Shrek-animators-add-style-to-reality.html|title='Shrek' animators add style to reality|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Breznican|date=May 25, 2001|website=[[Deseret News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> the animators found that they could emphasize Fiona's face most efficiently by focusing \"on the subtleties of the human form\" and compiling [[Transparency and translucency|translucent]] layers of skin to prevent the character from resembling plastic, a task they found particularly daunting due to people's familiarity with human skin.<ref name=\":50\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemareview.com/production.asp?prodid=1357|title=Shrek|last=|first=|date=|website=CinemaReview.com|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> To make Fiona's skin more believable, the animators studied [[dermatology]] books to learn how various light sources interact with human skin,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailylocal.com/arts_and_entertainment/shrek-animators-give-reality-style/article_8e70c702-1c7b-5596-845f-956e5e6d684a.html|title='Shrek' animators give reality style|last=|first=|date=May 17, 2001|website=[[Daily Local News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref> which visual effects supervisor Ken Bielenberg approached as though they were lighting Diaz herself.<ref name=\":69\" /> Bielenberg joked, \"You want the sunset to reflect off her face in a way that's flattering ... Fiona may be a computerized princess, but she has her bad side.\"<ref name=\":69\" /> The animators painted a combination of freckles and warmer tones onto some of her skin's deeper layers, through which they then filtered light.<ref name=\":20\" /> A [[shader]] was used to penetrate, refract and re-emerge layers of light, the [[Saturation (color theory)|concentration]] of which was adjusted to achieve Fiona's desired radiance; they learned that too much [[Exposure (photography)|exposure]] resulted in a [[mannequin]]-like appearance.<ref name=\":50\" /> The lighting department consulted with makeup artist Patty York to learn different approaches to creating realistic effects on Fiona's face,<ref name=\":26\">{{cite web|url=http://culture.com/articles/463/shrek-production-information.phtml|title=Shrek : Production Information|last=|first=|date=|website=Cinema.com|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> while the computer graphics software [[Autodesk Maya|Maya]] was used to animate her hair,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalmediafx.com/Shrek/shrekfaq.html|title=Shrek FAQ|last=Tracy|first=Joe|date=|website=Digital Media FX|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> which consists of more than 1 million polygons.<ref name=\":59\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/shrek-summer-152865|title=A Shrek of Summer|last=Ansen|first=David|authorlink=Ansen, David|date=May 6, 2001|website=[[Newsweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> The animators felt that Fiona's design was \"too real\" at times.<ref name=\":7\" /> When the film was previewed to test audiences, some children cried because they found Fiona's [[Hyperreality|hyperrealism]] disturbing;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sessions.edu/notes-on-design/by-hand-or-on-the-computer-the-threat-of-the-uncanny-valley/|title=By hand or on the computer? The threat of the Uncanny Valley|last=|first=|date=February 13, 2012|website=[[Sessions College for Professional Design]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919132232/https://www.sessions.edu/notes-on-design/by-hand-or-on-the-computer-the-threat-of-the-uncanny-valley/|archive-date=September 19, 2018|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":89\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/science/sdut-ucsd-exploring-why-some-robots-creep-people-out-2011aug04-story.html|title=UCSD exploring why robots creep people out|last=Robbins|first=Gary|date=August 4, 2011|website=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/idealog/20170724/282385514564811|title=The Creep Factor|last=|first=|date=July 24, 2017|work=Idealog|access-date=September 19, 2018|via=PressReader}}</ref> the character was suffering from a phenomenon known as the [[uncanny valley]].<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=124371580|title=Hollywood Eyes Uncanny Valley In Animation|last=York|first=Jamie|date=March 5, 2010|website=[[National Public Radio]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Consequently, DreamWorks ordered that the character be re-animated to appear more like a cartoon and less like a human simulation.<ref name=\":15\" /> Animator Lucia Modesto recalled that her team was instructed to \"pull back\" on the character's design because her realism was growing unpleasant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irssh.com/yahoo_site_admin/assets/docs/17_IRSSH-436-V4N2.44204045.pdf|title=Hyper-Realistic Characters and the Existence of the Uncanny Valley in Animation Films|last=Kaba|first=Fethi|date=2012|website=International Review of Social Sciences and Humanities|page=190|issn=2248-9010|access-date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829040130/http://irssh.com/yahoo_site_admin/assets/docs/17_IRSSH-436-V4N2.44204045.pdf|archive-date=August 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2002/06/face/|title=Why Is This Man Smiling?|last=Weschler|first=Lawrence|date=June 1, 2002|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=Animation Studies \u2013 Animated Dialogues, 2007|last=Butler|first=Matthew|last2=Joschko|first2=Lucie|date=2007|page=61|citeseerx = 10.1.1.664.7656}}</ref> Subsequently, Fiona was modified to fit in among the film's more fantastical characters, which supervising animator [[Raman Hui]] credits with improving the believability of Fiona and Shrek's relationship.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalmediafx.com/Interviews/ramanhui.html|title=dFX Interview: Raman Hui|last=|first=|date=|website=Digital Media FX|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> To make Fiona a more \"cartoony-looking love interest,\"<ref name=\":14\" /> the animators enlarged her eyes and smoothed her skin.<ref name=\":7\" /> Hui acknowledged that Fiona was much more difficult to animate as a human because any errors were quite apparent.<ref name=\":59\" /> In total, Fiona's face required a year of constant experimentation before the animators were satisfied with her final design: a realistic yet softer interpretation of the princess.<ref name=\":54\">{{cite web|url=https://www.asc.ohio-state.edu/palazzi.1/AC753W05/Computer%20Graphics%20World%20-%20Medieval%20Magic.pdf|title=Medieval Magic|last=Robertson|first=Barbara|date=October 2004|website=[[The Ohio State University]]|page=3|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDirector Andrew Adamson admitted that making Fiona beautiful yet viscerally familiar posed several unique challenges for the filmmakers.<ref name=\":54\" /> For example, her eyebrows sometimes cast shadows over her eyes, while her upturned lip and large eyes resulted in a \"spooky\" appearance.<ref name=\":54\" /> They wanted Fiona's appearance to be relatable without \"stick[ing] out among Shrek and the other fantastic characters and distract from the fairy-tale mood.\"<ref name=\":71\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2001/05/13/accent-on-the-details-shrek-takes-quantum-leap-in-animation/|title=Accent on the details: 'shrek' takes quantum leap in animation|last=Lumenick|first=Lou|authorlink=Lou Lumenick|date=May 13, 2001|website=[[New York Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Adamson identified Fiona as the film's most difficult character to animate due to people's familiarity with human mannerisms and expressions, whereas audiences are not nearly as accustomed to talking animals, such as Donkey.<ref name=\":71\" /> Hui maintains that Fiona's appearance was not based on that of any specific individual.<ref name=\":7\" /> Although the animators wanted to avoid making the character resemble Diaz too closely, elements of the actress's movements and mannerisms, which were videotaped during recording sessions,<ref name=\":71\" /> were incorporated into Fiona nonetheless, which they drew onto a different face to create a unique new character.<ref name=\":7\" /> Studying Diaz's mannerisms inspired the animators to exaggerate Fiona's expressions and reactions, instead of striving for realism.<ref name=\":71\" /> For example, Adamson believes Fiona squinting her eyes and compressing her lips while listening to someone else offers \"a richness you\u2019ve never seen before\u201d, despite their difficulty to animate.<ref name=\":71\" /> Diaz was shocked and ran out of the studio screaming joyfully when she saw her character animated to her voice for the first time.<ref name=\":11\" /> Although Diaz did not think the character resembles her, she recognized that Fiona had many of her mannerisms in addition to her own voice, appearing \"more real than she had imagined\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2004-05-19/lifestyle/0405170385_1_shrek-green-ogre-animation|title=Shrek 2 Has Ingredients Of Another Monster Hit|last=Koltnow|first=Barry|date=May 19, 2004|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> The actress explained that \"the experience was so weird she felt like she was watching some kind of strange sister.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Now-animation-is-king-Shrek-and-Atlantis-2921792.php|title=Now animation is king / 'Shrek' and 'Atlantis' will duke it out this summer|last=Stack|first=Peter|date=May 13, 2001|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Fiona's body consists of 90 muscles,<ref name=\":26\" /><ref name=\":54\" /> but her entire model is made up of more than 900 movable muscles.<ref name=\":59\" /> Even in her ogre form, Fiona is significantly smaller than Shrek, with layout supervisor Nick Walker confirming that Shrek is capable of swallowing Fiona's head whole.<ref name=\":52\">{{cite web|url=https://www.linuxjournal.com/article/9653|title=DreamWorks Animation \"Shrek the Third\": Linux Feeds an Ogre|last=Rowe|first=Robin|date=June 5, 2007|website=[[Linux Journal]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nActor [[Antonio Banderas|Antonia Banderas]], who voices [[Puss in Boots (Shrek)|Puss in Boots]], originally found it challenging to accept Fiona's unconventional appearance.<ref name=\":31\" /> Banderas explained that he experienced \"a certain resistance as a spectator for her to be an ogre\", initially wishing for her and Shrek to end the film as humans before finally accepting the character's appearance and sequel's ending.<ref name=\":31\" /> The actor believes several audience members \"went through this process when they were observing this movie\" because \"We are used to rejecting ugliness without reason.\u201d<ref name=\":31\" /> Costume designer [[Isis Mussenden]] designed the character's costumes for the first two ''Shrek'' films, for which she helped develop new technology to animate clothing in the then-new computer animation medium.<ref name=\":40\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BOMcDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT606&lpg=PT606&dq=Andrew+Adamson+fiona+interview#v=onepage&q=Andrew%20Adamson%20fiona%20interview&f=false|title=The Art and Practice of Costume Design|last=Mertz|first=Melissa|publisher=CRC Press|year=2016|isbn=9781317573678|location=United States|pages=|via=Google Books}}</ref> The filmmakers wanted a more realistic approach to costumes than previous computer animated films, in which clothing was typically depicted as a tight layer over the figure, adorned with a few wrinkles.<ref name=\":40\" /> The filmmakers had envisioned Fiona's velvet gown as one that moves independently from her body, therefore one of the film's producers recruited Mussenden, with whom they had worked prior, to assist them with the process.<ref name=\":40\" /> Mussenden began by creating a one-quarter scale replica of the skirt. To determine the gown's volume, fullness and where certain areas would rest on the character's form, the costume designer worked with both a pattern maker and designer.<ref name=\":40\" /> The patterns and seams were labeled and forwarded to the animators, who would replicate the images on the computer.<ref name=\":40\" /> Mussenden decided to give Fiona's dresses tight sleeves as opposed to the long, flowing sleeves associated with traditional [[Medieval fashion|medieval clothing]] due to the difficulty the latter would have been for the animators.<ref name=\":41\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2004/05/18/clothes-make-the-ogre/a04bd3bd-2597-4e9d-9ee4-7a6c5c244319/|title=Clothes Make the Ogre|last=|first=|date=2004|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Unlike ''Shrek'', Fiona has several costume changes in ''Shrek 2''. In the sequel, both Fiona's ogre and human forms are shown wearing the same green dress. To ensure that both forms looked equally flattering in the same outfit, Mussenden lowered the dress' waistline to make it more medieval in appearance than the costume she wears in the first film.<ref name=\":41\" /> Fiona's first costume is a lilac dress, which Mussenden designed to appear \"organic and textured, because she's been living in the swamp\". Towards the end of the film, she changes into a white ballgown with rhinestones inspired by an image of a 1958 dress the costume designer had found.<ref name=\":41\" /> \n\nThe scene in which Fiona single-handedly defeats Monsieur Hood and his Merry Men references the [[slow motion]] special effects popularized by ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999),<ref name=\":29\" /><ref name=\":59\" /><ref name=\":43\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pluggedin.ca/movie-reviews/shrek/|title=Shrek|last=Waliszewski|first=Bob|last2=Smithouser|first2=Bob|date=|website=[[Plugged In]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921230232/https://www.pluggedin.ca/movie-reviews/shrek/|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> as well as Diaz's own ''Charlie's Angels'' films.<ref name=\":58\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/shrek-review/|title=Shrek Review|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2001|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.film4.com/reviews/2001/shrek|title=Shrek (2001)|last=|first=|date=2001|website=[[Film4]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406054408/http://www.film4.com/reviews/2001/shrek|archive-date=April 6, 2010|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":61\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2001-05-18-0105180372-story.html#|title=An ogre in love|last=Caro|first=Mark|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> In a DVD bonus feature, Fiona explains that she performed her own stunts in the film, claiming that she based her kung fu on ''Charlie's Angels''.<ref name=\":83\">{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2002/02/23/shrek-laat-scheten-in-een-sprookje-7578827-a143954&prev=search|title=Shrek lets fart in a fairy tale|last=Linssen|first=Dana|date=February 23, 2002|website=[[NRC Handelsblad]]|language=Dutch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Despite concerns that references to ''The Matrix'' would eventually date the film, Rossio believes the gag will remain funny because it is a parody instead of merely an imitation.<ref name=\":60\" /> A similar reference is made when Fiona defeats a mob at the beginning of ''Shrek 2'', a complex sequence for which animators used powerful data processors to store and manipulate millions of computer generated images.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.ca/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=http://www.elmundo.es/magazine/2004/246/1086789278.html&prev=search|title=Know what Shrek laughs about|last=Calleja|first=Pedro|date=June 13, 2004|website=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Modesto created new character models for Fiona and Shrek in ''Shrek the Third'',<ref name=\":51\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/guest_writers1/b/leo_n_holzer/archive/2007/05/01/toon-tuesday-dreamworks-artists-technicians-tried-hard-not-to-ogre-compensate-while-working-on-shrek-the-third.aspx?PageIndex=2|title=Toon Tuesday : \"Shrek the Third\" artists & technicians tried hard not to ogre-compensate|last=Holzer|first=Leo N.|date=April 30, 2007|website=Jim Hill Media|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> while new software and servers were implemented to animate individual strands of the princess's hair much faster than had been possible during production of the first film.<ref name=\":53\" /> In ''Shrek Forever After''<nowiki/>'s alternate reality, the character wears her hair unbraided for the first time,<ref name=\":37\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allure.com/story/princess-fionas-expensive-new-do|title=Princess Fiona's Expensive New 'Do|last=Wexler|first=Sarah|date=May 19, 2010|website=[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> which was inspired by singer [[Janis Joplin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/movies/10-things-didnt-know-shrek-forever|title=10 Things You Didn't Know about Shrek Forever After|last=|first=|date=December 9, 2017|website=[[TVOvermind]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Due to its costliness, Fiona's new hairstyle first needed to be approved by DreamWorks, with Mitchell likening the process to \"prepar[ing] like a lawyer\".<ref name=\":38\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Why-Fiona-Taking-Her-Hair-Down-Is-a-Really-Big-Deal-94165809.html|title=Cameron Diaz's Ogre Hair Style Took a Team of 20 for \"Shrek\"|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=May 18, 2010|website=[[NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> The re-design was a difficult, expensive process that required 20 animators to animate each strand individually,<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":38\" /> as Mitchell was particularly determined to render it correctly due to audiences' familiarity with long hair.<ref name=\":38\" /> One group was specifically tasked with setting up Fiona's hair, which head of production technology Darin Grant believes \"allowed the process to be optimized and work across many, many shots\" as it \"flows and cascades throughout\" the entire film,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/vfxworld/decade-shrek-tech|title=A Decade of 'Shrek' Tech|last=Desowitz|first=Bill|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[Animation World Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> reinforcing Fiona's liberated personality.<ref name=\":37\" />\n\n=== Personality ===\n\nAccording to Rossio, the first film's four main characters are written \"around the concept of self-esteem, and appropriate and/or inappropriate reactions to appropriate or inappropriate self-assessment\", explaining that Fiona seeks validation from others because she believes \"there's something not correct about herself\".<ref name=\":60\" /> Adamson elaborated that the character's main issue revolves around living up to stereotypes and ideas \"represented in fairy tales that if ... you look a certain way and act a certain way and put the right dress and slippers on a handsome man is going to come\", dismissing this as an unrealistic and unhealthy approach to finding romance.<ref name=\":19\" /> Diaz confirmed that Fiona only becomes her true self once she is freed from the tower and realizes her Prince Charming differs from who she had been taught to expect.<ref name=\":66\" />\n\nA scene during which Fiona duets with a bird who explodes once the princess sings a high note,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Animated-fairy-tale-perfectly-fractured-Shrek-2862091.php|title=Animated fairy tale perfectly fractured / 'Shrek' delights viewers of all ages|last=LaSalle|first=Mick|date=November 2, 2001|website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> subsequently frying its eggs for breakfast,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/shrek1/|title=Shrek (2001)|last=Parker|first=Sabadino|date=2001|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160728073931/http://www.popmatters.com/review/shrek1/|archive-date=July 28, 2016|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> is considered to be a parody of Disney fairy tales such as ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'' (1950), about which Adamson explained \"pok[es] fun at people's expectations\" of princesses.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/05/29/shrek-anti-disney-fairy-tale/|title=Is ''Shrek'' the anti- Disney fairy tale?|last=Reese|first=Lori|date=May 29, 2001|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Diaz believes her character's personality \"shattered\" children's perception of princess characters from the moment she was freed from the tower, explaining that Fiona had always been capable of freeing herself but chose to remain in the tower solely because she was \"following the rules of a fairy tale book\".<ref name=\":48\" /> In the sequel, Diaz explained that Fiona \"has a lot of pressure from all the people who told her about Prince Charming to take everything materialistically and monetarily. And she literally is just kind of baffled by it and says, 'Sorry, but I don't need any of those things.' All she needs is this man who she loves and loves her and accepts her.\"<ref name=\":66\" /> Diaz considers her character to be an empowered, positive role model for young girls,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldextra.com/entertainment/people/celebrity-news/it-s-ogre-diaz-says-bye-to-fiona/article_75fc04c8-0201-5028-929e-ccd7cd7aff40.html|title=It's ogre: Diaz says bye to Fiona|last=Covert|first=Colin|date=May 21, 2010|website=Daily Herald|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> explaining, \"She's never depended on anyone to rescue her, which is a different message from Snow White and Rapunzel ... She was capable of getting out of the tower herself\" and \"took on Shrek as her partner rather than as her rescuer.\"<ref name=\":42\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhregister.com/news/article/Hollywood-s-highest-paid-actress-says-good-bye-to-11592108.php|title=Hollywood's highest-paid actress says good-bye to her 'Shrek' character|last=Covert|first=Colin|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[New Haven Register]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref> She believes that the moment she accepts herself as an ogre is her most empowered moment, as well as \"the biggest stride in her evolution as a person\".<ref name=\":67\" />\n\nDiaz considers Fiona to be \"the anchor that holds all these kooky characters\", identifying her as the comedy's [[straight man]].<ref name=\":67\">{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/fashion-news/happy-days-for-cameron-diaz-997160|title=Happy days for Cameron Diaz|last=|first=|date=April 20, 2010|website=[[Manchester Evening News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925104231/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/fashion-news/happy-days-for-cameron-diaz-997160|archive-date=September 25, 2018|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Revealing that she \"hate[s] naggy women\", Diaz sometimes found herself wishing that Fiona would be \"less naggy\" and more compassionate and understanding towards the difficult changes Shrek is undergoing since marrying her.<ref name=\":1\" /> During production of ''Shrek the Third'', Diaz observed that the filmmakers had made Fiona into more of a nag and asked that they tone this down, explaining, \"just because she got married it doesn't mean she has to become a nag'.\"<ref name=\":67\" /> This was one of only a few things Diaz asked that they adjust about Fiona.<ref name=\":67\" /> In ''Shrek Forever After''<nowiki/>'s [[Multiverse|alternate reality]], Fiona frees herself from the tower on her own and subsequently becomes a warrior and leader of an army of ogres,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canmag.com/nw/15767-shrek-forever-after-cameron-diaz|title=Cameron Diaz on Shrek Forever After|last=Topel|first=Fred|date=May 19, 2010|website=CanMag|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> which some commentators found to be a more empowering approach to the princess; Diaz contested that her character has \"always been a warrior ... of love through all these films. What she\u2019s worked for, what she\u2019s fought for is the love that she has for herself and the love that she has for Shrek and her family and her friends.\"<ref name=\":36\">{{cite web|url=https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/features/21634-qaa-the-stars-of-shrek|title=Q&A: The Stars of Shrek|last=|first=|date=May 21, 2010|website=[[Relevant (magazine)|Relevant]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921074453/https://relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/features/21634-qaa-the-stars-of-shrek|archive-date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Diaz concluded that, due to the fourth film's tone, Fiona's responsibilities are simply more apparent,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/sun/intermission/index.ssf/2010/05/shrek.html|title=Voices speak fondly to 'Shrek,' forever after|last=Urbancich|first=John M.|date=May 21, 2010|website=Cleveland.com|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> believing that in this film she is \"fighting for what she believes in.\"<ref name=\":48\" />\n\n== Characterization and themes ==\n\nTodd Anthony of the ''Sun-Sentinel'' cited Fiona among several elements that make ''Shrek'' resemble an archetypal fairy tale initially.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-05-18/entertainment/0105160756_1_lord-farquaad-shrek-princess-fiona|title=Ogre's Odyssey Fractures A Few Fairy Tales Shrek|last=Anthony|first=Todd|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Furniss identified Fiona's [[character arc]] as struggling with insecurities about her identity and appearance before finally \"accept[ing] herself in a so-called 'ugly' physical manifestation\", which she described as merely \"cute\" as opposed to \"push[ing] the boundaries of true ugliness.\"<ref name=\":17\" /> Demonstrated by her \"very definite ideas about how she wants to be rescued,\"<ref name=\":74\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2001/05/16/shrek-it-out-an-unlikely-lovable-ogre-cavorts-in-an-instant-fairy-tale-classic/|title='Shrek' it out: an unlikely lovable ogre cavorts in an instant fairy-tale classic|last=Lumenic|first=Lou|authorlink=Lou Lumenick|date=May 16, 2001|website=[[New York Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Bob Waliszewski of ''[[Plugged In]]'' believes Fiona \"has bought into the conventions of fairy tale [[romanticism]] hook, line and sinker\", writing, \"Her skewed perspective on love and marriage undermines [[agape love]] and spiritual discernment in relationships.\"<ref name=\":43\" /> Similarly, ''[[TV Guide]]'' film critic [[Frank Lovece]] described Fiona as a \"beautiful and headstrong princess\" who has spent too much time thinking about true love.<ref name=\":76\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/shrek/review/134500/|title=Shrek \u2013 Review|last=Lovece|first=Frank|authorlink=Frank Lovece|date=2001|website=[[TV Guide]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> [[Michael Sragow]], film critic for ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', agreed that the character is \"fixated on being treated like a fairy-tale princess\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2001-05-18/features/0105180081_1_donkey-eddie-murphy-fairy|title=A beauty of a beast|last=Sragow|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Sragow|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> resulting in a precarious outlook on reality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/shrek|title=Shrek|last=B|first=N|date=2001|website=[[Total Film]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Although Fiona is originally disappointed upon discovering her rescuer is not a Prince Charming, her expectations are more-so grounded in \"rituals of self-loathing\".<ref name=\":33\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/shrek|title=Shrek|last=Gonzalez|first=Ed|date=May 13, 2001|website=[[Slant Magazine]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Furniss believes Fiona's story is targeted towards Disney films in which princesses are constantly rescued from \"horrible fates by knights\".<ref name=\":17\" /> However, despite her efforts to look, speak and behave like a traditional princess,<ref name=\":46\">{{cite web|url=https://geekgirlcon.com/princessfiction/|title=This is what a Princess Looks Like: Fictional Edition|last=Krismer|first=Shiboo|date=February 27, 2012|website=GeekGirlCon|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Fiona is soon proven to be an nontraditional princess, exemplified by her traits as a skilled fighter, unusual diet occasionally consisting of wild animals and tendency to belch spontaneously.<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":46\" />\n\nJames Clarke, author of ''Animated Films - Virgin Film'', described Fiona as \"both an old-school and new-school heroine, in love with the notion of a charming prince who will rescue her but also tough talking and tough acting\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B090Ndx1o6cC&pg=PT124&lpg=PT124&dq=best+animated+heroines+princess+fiona#v=onepage&q=best%20animated%20heroines%20princess%20fiona&f=false|title=Animated Films - Virgin Film|last=Clarke|first=James|publisher=Random House|year=2012|isbn=9781448132812|location=United States|pages=|via=Google Books}}</ref> Although she originally possesses traits associated with a traditional princess, being tall and slender, both Shrek and audiences soon agree that Fiona is different,<ref name=\":17\" /> and the princess is merely \"following a script from a storybook\" herself.<ref name=\":46\" /> Paul Byrnes of ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' wrote that Fiona's depiction in the first film offers \"a sense of how gender roles had shifted\" by resembling \"a bottom-kicking heroine\".<ref name=\":90\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/shrek-forever-after-20100609-xwjw.html|title=Shrek Forever After|last=Byrnes|first=Paul|date=June 10, 2010|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref> Among her unusual characteristics, John Anderson of ''[[Newsday]]'' observed that Fiona is \"perfectly capable of taking care of herself. She's just been waiting for some classic romance.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/content/movies/nd4756.htm|title=The Neatest Story Ever Told 'Shrek' stands tall among fairy tales|last=Anderson|first=John|date=2001|website=Newsday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010526174307/http://www.newsday.com/content/movies/nd4756.htm|archive-date=May 26, 2001|url-status=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Although in the context of the film Shrek initially observes Fiona's differences once she belches, \"it rapidly also becomes apparent that she is indeed not a prototypical fairy-tale princess\", according to author Johnny Unger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/2553641|title=Gendered discourses in a contemporary animated film: subversion and confirmation of gender stereotypes in Shrek|last=Unger|first=Johnny|last2=Sunderland|first2=Jane|date=|website=Academia.edu|page=6|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> The ''New York Press'' observed that ''Shrek'' emphasizes \"that the ogre falls in love with the heroine not because of her conventional good looks, but in spite of them ... looking past Fiona's skinny, blond human surface and seeing the belching, bug-eating ogre beneath.\"<ref name=\":34\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?avis=NP&date=20040525&category=NEWS&lopenr=305259985&Ref=AR&template=printart|title=Green Meanies|last=|first=|date=|website=New York Press|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Journalist [[Steve Sailer]], writing for [[United Press International|UPI]], similarly wrote that \"Fiona wins Shrek's heart by belching, beating up Robin Hood's Merry Men (who act like Broadway chorus boys) with cool \"Matrix\"-style kung fu, and cooking the Blue Bird of Happiness' eggs for breakfast.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/2001/05/17/Film-of-the-week-Shrek-is-kids-revenge/9297990072000/|title=Film of the week: 'Shrek' is kids' revenge|last=Sailer|first=Steve|date=May 17, 2001|website=UPI|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Elliot believes that Fiona's storyline explores \"the actual prevalence of attitudes about appearance in society\", identifying a theme of lacking self-esteem as particularly prevalent with Fiona.<ref name=\":60\" /> Film critic [[Emanuel Levy]] shared that \"Fiona suffers/benefits from duality\", transitioning from a \"sexy, opinionated, and feisty\" character into an outcast once \"her secret is revealed\", after which she becomes closer to Shrek.<ref name=\":72\">{{cite web|url=http://emanuellevy.com/article.php?articleID=3053|title=Shrek|last=Levy|first=Emanuel|authorlink=Emmanuel Levy|date=2001|website=[[Emanuel Levy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061118223241/http://emanuellevy.com/article.php?articleID=3053|archive-date=November 18, 2006|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]], film critic for the ''[[New York Press]]'', wrote that Fiona takes the film's [[metaphor]] pertaining the people \"passing for something they're not\" to \"a whole different level\", explaining, \"At first you think she's a standard-issue princess who's willing to let her hair down and hang with the riffraff\", describing her as \"a modern-day Disney heroine.\"<ref name=\":75\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/shrek-the-best-american-movie-of-the-year/|title=Shrek: The Best American Movie of the Year|last=Seitz|first=Matt Zoller|date=May 22, 2001|website=New York Press|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Seitz also observed \"interracial overtones\" in Fiona and Shrek's relationship.<ref name=\":75\" />\n\n''PopMatters'' contributor Evan Sawdey wrote that the ''Shrek'' films use Fiona to promote acceptance, particularity the moment she \"discovers that her true form is that of an ogre\", by which she is not saddened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/134878-shrek-the-whole-story-2496098809.html?rebelltitem=1#rebelltitem1|title='Shrek: The Whole Story': Imagine What We Would Have Missed If We Just Left Him Alone|last=Sawdey|first=Evan|date=December 15, 2010|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Believing that Fiona would happily battle and defend whatever she loves or believes in, Diaz identified the character as \"the anchor everyone has attached themselves to\", to whom Shrek looks to for guidance, which she would not have been able to provide unless she possessed the strength herself.<ref name=\":48\" /> In terms of character development and evolvement, Diaz recalled that, despite having been raised in a \"storybook life\", Fiona eventually comes to terms with the fact that \"her Prince Charming didn\u2019t come in the package she thought he would. She\u2019s learned to have patience with Shrek, accept him for who he his\", particularly going against being taught that her Prince Charming must look and act a certain way.<ref name=\":1\" /> Thus, Adamson considers Fiona to be \"an [[Women's empowerment|empowering]] character\" for young girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/Profiles/Articles/AndrewAdamson/AndrewAdamson.html|title=Creating Imaginary Worlds from Shrek to Narnia|last=Fischer|first=Paul|date=November 21, 2005|website=FilmMonthly|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Unlike Farquaad, Shrek respects Fiona for speaking up for and defending herself.<ref name=\":30\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyedge.ie/shrek-appreciate-4041874-May2018/|title=9 reasons we need to appreciate Shrek more than we already do|last=O'Neill|first=Rachel|date=May 29, 2018|website=[[The Daily Edge]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Fiona's final transformation sequence in which she transforms into an ogre permanently is considered to be a parody and critique of the Beast's transformation into a human in Disney's ''Beauty and the Beast'' (1991),<ref name=\":75\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cVHhj-GIk0wC&pg=PA860&lpg=PA860&dq=princess+fiona+transformation+beauty+and+the+beast#v=onepage&q=princess%20fiona%20transformation%20beauty%20and%20the%20beast&f=false|title=The Greenwood Encyclopedia of Folktales and Fairy Tales: Q-Z|last=Haase|first=Donald|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2008|isbn=9780313334443|location=United States|page=860|via=Google Books}}</ref> with Fiona coming to realize that her \"true love's true form\" is in fact an ogre.<ref name=\":34\" /> Novelist and film critic [[Jeffrey Overstreet]] considered it to be \"part of society\u2019s downfall that we embrace the Princess Fionas when they\u2019re glamorous rather than real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lookingcloser.org/2008/05/shrek-2001/|title=Shrek (2001)|last=Overstreet|first=Jeffrey|date=2001|website=Looking Closer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229005001/http://lookingcloser.org/2008/05/shrek-2001/|archive-date=December 29, 2008|url-status=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] observed that Fiona is the only princess competing to be Farquaad's bride (opposite Cinderella and Snow White) who \"who has not had the title role in a Disney animated feature\", which he considered to be \"inspired by feelings DreamWorks partner Jeffrey Katzenberg has nourished since his painful departure from Disney\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shrek-2001#disqus_thread|title=Shrek|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=May 18, 2001|website=Roger Ebert|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a review for ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', film critic [[Stephanie Zacharek]] observed that Fiona \"has two little [[freckle]]like beauty spots, one on her cheek and one on her upper chest\", which she interpreted as \"symbols of her human authenticity, but they also serve as a sort of factory trademark left by her creators: 'You see, we've thought of every last detail.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2001/05/18/shrek/|title=Shrek|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|date=May 18, 2001|website=Salon|access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Rick Groen of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' observed that Fiona \"appears to replicate the body of Cameron Diaz\", describing her as \"a cute brunette with a retrouss\u00e9 nose, ample curves, and cleavage that broadens whenever she bends low in her scoop-neck frock.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/movie/MOVIEREVIEWS/20010518/RVSHRE|title=If only it were kid's stuff|last=Groen|first=Rick|date=May 18, 2001|website=The Globe and Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040221114849/http://www.globeandmail.com/servlet/ArticleNews/movie/MOVIEREVIEWS/20010518/RVSHRE|archive-date=February 21, 2004|url-status=|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Fiona is skilled in [[hand-to-hand combat]] and martial arts.<ref name=\":46\" /> ''[[The New York Times]]'' journalist A. J. Jacobs wrote that Fiona's [[Chinese martial arts|kung fu]] skills rival those of actor [[Bruce Lee]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/19/books/review/frogkisser-garth-nix-the-land-of-stories-chris-colfer.html|title=Fairy Tales, Gently Fractured|last=Jacobs|first=A. J.|date=May 19, 2017|website=The New York Times|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> abilities she is explained to have inherited from her mother Queen Lillian.<ref name=\":85\" /> Describing Fiona as tough and clever, museum curator Sarah Tutton observed that, despite being a love interest, the character \"doesn\u2019t play the typical supporting role ... Just because Princess Fiona subverts the idea of beauty, it doesn\u2019t mean that beauty is not important. It means that the film isn\u2019t taking it as a cliche.\"<ref name=\":44\">{{cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/forget-waiting-for-prince-charming-modern-princesses-are-breaking-gender-stereotypes/news-story/f6ce5199600ab44953f384197b64fda7|title=Forget waiting for Prince Charming, modern Princesses are breaking gender stereotypes|last=Weekend|first=Anna Brain|date=April 4, 2014|website=[[Herald Sun]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> In the third film, Fiona teaches the classic princesses, who are naturally inclined to \"to assume passive positions\", not to wait for their princes to rescue them,<ref name=\":31\">{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/shrek-creators-embrace-fractured-fairy-tales-wbna18661568|title='Shrek' creators embrace fractured fairy tales|last=|first=|date=August 4, 2010|website=[[Today.com|Today]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> making them over into [[action hero]]ines themselves when Prince Charming takes over the kingdom while teaching them to stand up for themselves.<ref name=\":62\" /><ref name=\":52\" /> Several critics considered this moment to be about [[girl power]] and female empowerment,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sociotimes.com/archives/2007/05/girl_power_hits.aspx|title=Girl Power Hits Shrek III|last=Kendall|first=Pete|date=May 21, 2007|website=Socio Times|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":64\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2007/05/16/shrek-third-2/|title=Shrek the Third|last=Schwarzbaum|first=Lisa|authorlink=Lisa Schwarzbaum|date=May 16, 2007|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://login.live.com/login.srf?wa=wsignin1.0&rpsnv=13&ct=1537245256&rver=6.7.6640.0&wp=MBI_SSL&wreply=https://outlook.live.com/owa/?RpsCsrfState=9ede1515-3e01-3d5d-a4c4-49dde02ac750&id=292841&whr=hotmail.com&CBCXT=out&lw=1&fl=dob,flname,wld&cobrandid=90015|title=Shrek The Third: review|last=Mclaughlin|first=Robert|date=July 2, 2007|website=Den of Geek|access-date=September 24, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/17/review.shrek/index.html|title=Review: 'Shrek' continues genial hit-or-miss ways|last=Charity|first=Tom|date=May 17, 2007|website=CNN|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/a-nervous-shrek-loses-the-old-spark-20070523-gdq7ef.html|title=A nervous Shrek loses the old spark|last=Maddox|first=Garry|date=May 23, 2007|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> as well as a ''Charlie's Angels'' reference.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mustangnews.net/shrekiiiafairytalegoneboring/|title=Shrek III a fairytale gone boring|last=Narciso|first=Isaiah|date=May 22, 2007|website=Mustang News|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Diaz believes that the films and her character \"retain the best qualities of\" classic fairy tale characters, \"infusing them with contemporary wit, style and relevance\" for a more contemporary generation.<ref name=\":31\" /> Diaz elaborated, \"We do love those girls ... But now they have a whole new life. They can exist in our current culture, our pop culture again ... Where before, they were forgotten. It\u2019s a celebration of them. It\u2019s a rebirth.\u201d<ref name=\":31\" /> Furthermore, Diaz believes that the princesses' independence is a positive message for both women and men, interpreting it as \"a message for everyone \u2026 You have to be proactive in your own life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.today.com/popculture/diaz-shrek-pals-share-fairy-tale-talk-1C9423012|title=Diaz and 'Shrek' pals share fairy-tale talk|last=|first=|date=May 9, 2007|website=Today|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Miller believes that Fiona's skills as a martial artist prove naturally beneficial to her adjustment to motherhood because \"she can use her whole body. She\u2019s very adaptable.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/exclusive-shreks-babies-revealed/#mom-knows-best|title=Exclusive: Shrek's Babies Revealed!|last=Lynch|first=Jason|date=May 1, 2007|website=People|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Appearances ==\n\n===Film series===\nFiona first appears in ''[[Shrek]]'' (2001) as a bride chosen by Lord Farquaad, who intends to marry the princess solely so that he can become King of Duloc.<ref name=\":55\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4724343/A-monster-triumph.html|title=A monster triumph|last=O'Hagan|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew O'Hagan|date=June 29, 2001|website=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> In order to regain ownership of his swamp, Shrek and Donkey agree to retrieve Fiona from her dragon-guarded tower and deliver her to Farquaad.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":56\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/shrek-u-9153444.html|title=Shrek (U)|last=Quinn|first=Anthony|date=June 28, 2001|website=[[The Independent]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Fiona is rescued successfully but disappointed upon discovering that Shrek is an ogre instead of a knight, proceeding to act coldly towards him at the beginning of their journey back to Duloc. However, her attitude softens once she overhears Shrek explain that he is constantly misjudged by his appearance, and the two gradually develop a camaraderie as Fiona falls in love with [[Shrek]].<ref name=\":76\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ericdsnider.com/movies/shrek/|title=Shrek|last=Snider|first=Eric D.|date=2001|website=Eric D. Snider|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Late one evening, Donkey discovers that Fiona is under an enchantment that transforms her into an ogre every night, and she wishes to break the spell by kissing Farquaad before the next sunset.<ref name=\":84\">{{cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/2016/04/108730/disney-princess-fiona-shrek|title=The One Princess No One Talks About & Why She Matters|last=Cohen|first=Anne|date=April 22, 2016|website=[[Refinery 29]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref> When she finally decides to tell Shrek the truth the following morning, she learns that Shrek has already summoned Farquaad to take her back to Duloc himself, having overheard and misinterpreted some of her conversation with Donkey.<ref name=\":76\" /> The princess and ogre part ways, Fiona returning to Duloc with Farquaad and Shrek returning to his swamp alone. Shrek and Donkey soon [[Wedding Crasher|interrupt]] Fiona and Farquaad's wedding ceremony, where Shrek professes his love for her. With the sun setting, Fiona allows herself to transform into an ogre in front of Shrek for the first time, prompting Farquaad to threaten to lock her back in her tower for eternity. However, the [[Dragon (Shrek)|dragon]] that had once imprisoned Fiona eats Farquaad, killing him. Fiona finally confesses her feelings for Shrek and, upon kissing him, turns into an ogre full-time; the two ogres marry.\n\nIn ''[[Shrek 2]]'' (2004), Fiona and Shrek return home from their [[honeymoon]] to find that Fiona's parents are inviting them to the kingdom of Far, Far Away to celebrate and bless their marriage. Shrek is apprehensive about meeting his parents-in-law, but Fiona insists.<ref name=\":24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/animation/shrek-2/4018693.article|title=Shrek 2|last=Oppenheimer|first=Jean|date=May 16, 2004|website=[[Screen Daily]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Fiona's parents, King Harold and Queen Lillian, are surprised to find that their daughter married an ogre,<ref name=\":47\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shrek-2-2004|title=Shrek 2|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|date=May 18, 2004|website=[[RogerEbert.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> with Harold acting particularly coldly towards his new son-in-law, which in turn strains Fiona and Shrek's relationship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/film/review/shrek2|title=Shrek 2|last=Thomas|first=David|date=2004|website=[[Contactmusic.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> When a tearful Fiona unintentionally summons her [[Fairy Godmother (Shrek)|Fairy Godmother]], who discovers that the princess married someone other than Prince Charming \u2013 her own son \u2013 she conspires with Harold to kill Shrek and trick Fiona into falling in love with Charming, as per their original agreement.<ref name=\":47\" /> Fiona is briefly returned to her human form when Shrek consumes a potion that turns both him and his true love beautiful,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/shrek-2-v286672|title=Shrek 2 (2004) \u2013 Synopsis by Mark Deming|last=Deming|first=Mark|date=May 19, 2004|website=[[AllMovie]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> but Shrek must obtain a kiss from Fiona before midnight, otherwise the spell will revert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/n_10395/|title=Con Anima|last=Rainer|first=Peter|date=2004|website=New York|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> However, Fairy Godmother, from whom Shrek steals the potion, tricks Fiona into believing Charming is Shrek's human form. Despite their efforts, Fiona continues to resent Charming's impression of her husband to the point where Fairy Godmother imprisons Shrek and insists that Harold feed Fiona a potion that will force her to fall in love with whomever she kisses first, intending for this to be Charming. However, the king refuses upon seeing how unhappy Fiona has become, thwarting Fairy Godmother's plan. Fairy Godmother and Charming are defeated by Fiona, Shrek and their friends. Although Shrek offers to kiss Fiona so that they can remain human forever, Fiona refuses, insisting that she would rather spend forever with the ogre she fell in love with and married, and they turn back into ogres.\n\nIn ''[[Shrek the Third]]'' (2007), Fiona and Shrek take on the roles of acting Queen and King of Far, Far Away while Harold is ill.<ref name=\":51\" /> When Harold passes away, Shrek is reluctantly named next-in-line to Harold's throne, a position he declines because becoming king would prevent him and Fiona from returning to their swamp.<ref name=\":82\">{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/shrek-third-cast-finalized|title=Shrek the Third Cast Finalized|last=DeMott|first=Rick|date=July 13, 2006|website=Animation World Network|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Determined to locate a suitable heir, Shrek sets out to recruit Fiona's cousin Arthur Pendragon to convince him to assume the throne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2007/05/14/shrek-sustains-creative-dynasty/|title=\"Shrek\" sustains creative dynasty|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2007|website=The Denver Post|access-date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Before Shrek departs, Fiona finally reveals that she is pregnant, forcing Shrek to come to terms with the idea of fatherhood.<ref name=\":4\" /> While Shrek, Donkey and Puss venture to Camelot to recruit Arthur, Fiona remains at Far, Far Away, where her princess friends [[Rapunzel (Shrek)|Rapunzel]], [[Snow White (Shrek)|Snow White]], [[Sleeping Beauty]], [[Cinderella (Shrek)|Cinderella]] and her stepsister Doris host a [[baby shower]] for her.<ref name=\":49\" /> The shower is interrupted by Prince Charming, still bitter over losing both the kingdom and Fiona to Shrek. Charming stages an invasion so that he can proclaim himself king of Far Far Away. Instead of waiting to be rescued, an idea that Fiona finds appalling, she encourages the princesses to free themselves and fight back.<ref name=\":63\" /> After escaping the dungeon, Fiona, Lillian and the princesses (albeit Rapunzel, who has betrayed them to marry Charming) organize a resistance to defend themselves and the kingdom.<ref name=\":82\" /> Artie makes a speech to convince the villains to go straight. In the end, Fiona and Shrek return to the swamp, where Fiona gives birth to [[Ogre Triplets (Shrek)|ogre triplets]] named Felicia, Fergus and Farkle.<ref name=\":90\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lancasteronline.com/features/entertainment/shrek-forever-after-an-ending-fit-for-a-king/article_fb1f6aa3-17fe-5cbd-a835-58a8cb2e8a09.html|title='Shrek Forever After:' An ending fit for a king|last=Glass|first=Erica|date=May 28, 2010|website=[[LNP (newspaper)|LNP]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''[[Shrek Forever After]]'' (2010) reveals that, during the events of the first film, Fiona's parents had nearly lost the kingdom to Rumpelstiltskin, nearly signing it over in return for their daughter's freedom, but his plans are thwarted when Fiona is rescued by and falls in love with [[Shrek]].<ref name=\":35\">{{cite news|last=Giese|first=Rachel|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/review-shrek-forever-after-1.900866|title=Review: Shrek Forever After|date=May 20, 2010|work=[[CBC.ca]]|access-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live|author-link=Rachel Giese}}</ref> Fiona confronts Shrek, who has grown frustrated with his mundane repetitive life since becoming a father, about losing his temper during their children's birthday; a heated argument between the two prompts Shrek to wish he had never rescued Fiona from the tower, a comment by which Fiona is hurt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/cbbcnews/hi/newsid_8720000/newsid_8725900/8725939.stm|title=Film Review: Shrek Forever After|last=|first=|date=August 3, 2010|website=BBC|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> When Shrek makes his deal with Rumpelstiltskin, for a single day he is taken to an alternate reality where he was never born. Here, Rumpelstiltskin  has seized power by tricking Fiona's parents out of ruling the kingdom of Far Far Away. Since Shrek never frees Fiona from the tower, she remains under the witch's spell \u2013 human by day and ogre by night \u2013 and has subsequently become the leader of a group of Ogre resistance fighters.<ref name=\":35\" /><ref name=\":68\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/125942-shrek-forever-after-2496190280.html|title='Shrek Forever After': It's Getting Pretty Stale|last=Fuchs|first=Cynthia|date=May 20, 2010|website=[[PopMatters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 25, 2018}}</ref> Shrek initially believes his relationship with Fiona still exists there but when she doesn't even recognize him, he finally accepts completely that the reality he is in is not his own and that Rumpelstiltskin  has truly altered reality to be as if he never existed until now. Fiona is shown to still be kindhearted and caring but bitterly cynical and disillusioned about the power of true love, because she was never rescued from her tower, having grown traumatized from her years of solitary imprisonment.<ref name=\":68\" /> She begins to fall in love with him again when he starts training with her, but still does not kiss him (having only started to find him likable). But Fiona's attitude towards Shrek changes as she and the other ogres head off to take down Rumpelstiltskin once and for all. During the day, Shrek realizes that a loophole will negate the deal if he can receive a True Love's kiss from Fiona. After a failed attempt, they realize that he has succeeded when Fiona's curse has been broken. The timeline returns to normal, and Shrek returns to his children's birthday party before he lashed out at everybody and warmly greets Fiona.\n\n=== Television specials and shorts ===\nFiona has appeared in two holiday-themed [[Television special|television specials]]: ''[[Shrek the Halls]]'' (2007) and ''[[Scared Shrekless]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Shrek/Princess-Fiona/|title=Princess Fiona|website=Behind the Voice Actors|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> The animated short ''[[Shrek in the Swamp Karaoke Dance Party|Shrek in the Swamp Karaoke Dance Party!]]'' (2001) is included on [[home video]] releases of ''Shrek'', featuring several of the film's characters performing covers of well-known songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/13-best-movie-karaoke-scenes-lost-in-translation-500-days-of-summer-more|title=13 Best Movie Karaoke Scenes: 'Lost In Translation,' '(500) Days of Summer,' More|last=Stern|first=Marlow|date=July 21, 2013|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=August 25, 2018}}</ref> In the short, Fiona sings an excerpt from [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s song \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\" (1984).<ref name=\":83\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/nov/01/entertainment/ca-64102|title='Shrek' Delivers DVD-ROM Goodies|last=King|first=Susan|date=November 1, 2001|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Fiona appears in the short ''[[Shrek 4-D]]'', a 4-D film originally shown at various amusement and theme parks. The short was renamed ''Shrek 3-D'' and ''The Ghost of Lord Farquaad'' for home video and [[streaming service]] releases. In it, Fiona and Shrek's honeymooning plans are interrupted by Farquaad's ghost,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04n99xk|title=Shrek: The Ghost of Lord Farquaad|last=|first=|date=|website=[[BBC Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> who kidnaps Fiona and intends to kill the princess so that he can marry her ghost in the [[afterlife]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/The-Ghost-of-Lord-Farquaad/552494/|title=The Ghost of Lord Farquaad 2003|last=|first=|date=|website=Blu-ray.com|access-date=October 16, 2018}}{{dead link|date=December 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Shrek and Donkey pursue Farquaad determined to rescue her,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/c7fppf/shrek-the-ghost-of-lord-farquaad/|title=Shrek: The Ghost of Lord Farquaad|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Radio Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> assisted by Dragon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shrek_4d_shrek_3d?|title=Shrek 4-D (Shrek 3-D) (2003)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> Fiona appears in the short film ''[[Far far away idol|Far, Far Away Idol]]'', a parody of the [[reality television]] singing competition ''[[American Idol]]'', which is included as a bonus feature on home video releases of ''Shrek 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/shrek-2-the-record-shattering-439-million-box-office-smash-premieres-on-dvd-and-vhs-friday-november-5-74152902.html|title=Shrek 2, the Record Shattering $439 Million Box Office Smash Premieres on DVD and VHS Friday, November 5|last=|first=|date=2004|website=[[PR Newswire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603170304/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/shrek-2-the-record-shattering-439-million-box-office-smash-premieres-on-dvd-and-vhs-friday-november-5-74152902.html|archive-date=June 3, 2013|access-date=October 17, 2018}}</ref> First serving as a judge alongside Shrek and an animated version of ''American Idol'' judge [[Simon Cowell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2004/digital/features/idol-times-for-shrek-2-1117911626/|title='Idol' times for 'Shrek 2'|last=Hettrick|first=Scott|date=October 7, 2004|website=Variety|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> offering feedback about the other characters performances,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://animatedviews.com/2004/shrek-2/|title=Shrek 2|last=Simon|first=Ben|date=November 3, 2004|website=Animated Views|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> Fiona eventually duets [[The Romantics]]' \"[[What I Like About You (song)|What I Like About You]]\" with Shrek.\n\n===Stage===\n\nFiona appeared in the [[Shrek The Musical|stage musical adaptation of the film]], which ran on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] from 2008 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/shrek-the-musical-477427/#opennightcredit|title=Shrek The Musical|website=Internet Broadway Database|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> The role was originated by actress [[Sutton Foster]], who had been involved in the project three years before its premiere, having learned about it from composer [[Jeanine Tesori]] and director [[Jason Moore (director)|Jason Moore]].<ref name=\":87\">{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/diva-talk-chatting-with-shreks-sutton-foster-plus-news-of-buckley-lupone-and-minnelli-com-155590|title=Diva Talk: Chatting with Shrek's Sutton Foster Plus News of Buckley, LuPone and Minnelli|last=Gans|first=Andrew|date=November 28, 2008|website=[[Playbill]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> She was drawn towards the idea of playing a princess for the first time, the prospect of which she found \"fun\", as well as the opportunity to collaborate with lyricist and librettist [[David Lindsay-Abaire]].<ref name=\":87\" /> Actresses Keaton Whittaker and Marissa O'Donnell portrayed younger versions of the character.<ref name=\":87\" /> Before production, Foster described Fiona as an atypical princess who is \"a little bipolar, but rightfully so\" having \"grown up, like we all have, with ideas of how the world works\" while trying to surround herself with, and emulate, fairy tales.<ref name=\":87\" /> Foster believes Fiona constantly struggles with her \"inner ogre\" despite trying to be perfect. \"Everything she's been told is that she's supposed to look a certain way and act a certain way, but everything on the inside is telling her something different.\"<ref name=\":87\" /> Although Fiona longs to be a \"proper princess\", Foster identifies herself as \"more of a tomboy\", while Fiona's body contradicts with her desires: \"as soon as she starts farting and burping, she has a really great time! And I just love that, that she finds herself in just having fun with an ogre, with Shrek. And I love that she falls in love with him through something crude.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2008/12/shrek_the_musicals_sutton_foster.html|title=Shrek the Musical's Sutton Foster on the Grave Seriousness of Onstage Farting|last=Fradkin|first=Lori|date=December 12, 2008|website=Vulture.com|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref> Foster found it \"fun to play a truly conflicted character and to be a princess who burps and farts and gets to do silly things.\"<ref name=\":87\" /> Foster earned a Tony Award nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Musical|Best Actress in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/05/theater/theaterspecial/05tonyslist.html|title=2009 Tony Award Winners|date=May 29, 2009|website=The New York Times|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Despite being a fan of the musical adaption, Diaz has stated that she has no intention of reprising her role on stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/cameron-diaz-says-1000881/|title=Cameron Diaz Says \"Shrek No!\" to Broadway|last=Eng|first=Joyce|date=December 15, 2008|website=TV Guide|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\nDuring early press screenings, critics were amused by Fiona's bluebird scene to the point where they laughed hysterically.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nitrateonline.com/2001/rshrek.html|title=Shrek|last=Savada|first=Elias|date=May 18, 2001|website=Nitrate Online|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> [[David Ansen]] of ''Newsweek'' reported that the sequence consistently \"sends audiences into fits of delight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/shrek-effect-153723|title=The Shrek Effect|last=Ansen|first=David|authorlink=David Ansen|date=June 17, 2001|website=[[Newsweek]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' film critic [[Richard Schickel]] called Fiona \"an excellent character,\" highlighting her confrontation with Monsieur Hood.<ref name=\"shrektime\">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,999937-1,00.html|title=Cinema: Monstrously Good|last=Schickel|first=Richard|date=May 21, 2001|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=May 15, 2013|author-link=Richard Schickel|url-access=registration}}</ref> Similarly, the ''[[New York Post]]'' film critic [[Lou Lumenick]] identified Fiona's encounters with Monsieur Hood and the bluebird as clever, delightful \"sendups of a long line of Disney classics\".<ref name=\":74\" /> Kelly Vance of the ''[[East Bay Express]]'' wrote, \"Armed with Diaz' vocal portrayal ... Fiona is more charming, more vulnerable, perkier, and even more sensitive than if she were played by a human actress.\"<ref name=\"eastbayexpressshrek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/graphically-ever-after/Content?oid=1065466|title=Graphically Ever After|last=Vance|first=Kelly|date=May 18, 2001|work=[[East Bay Express]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> Film critic Emanuel Levy believes ''Shrek'' benefits from Fiona, writing that \"Diaz applies well skills she had acquired for ''Charlie's Angels''\".<ref name=\":72\" /> [[Hollywood.com]]'s Robert Sims joked that \"Fiona could teach Charlie's Angels a lesson or two in romance and survival skills.\"<ref name=\"shrekhollywood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/movies/review/455380/shrek-review|title=Shrek Review|last=Sims|first=Robert|date=June 3, 2001|website=[[Hollywood.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> [[Malcolm Johnson (journalist)|Malcolm Johnson]] of the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' lauded Fiona as \"a marvel, as beautiful and shapely as a real star but capable of moves that go beyond the wirework in ''The Matrix''.\"<ref name=\":45\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2001-05-18/features/0105181351_1_princess-fiona-snow-white-animation|title=The Green Party 'Shrek' Rules|last=Johnson|first=Malcolm|authorlink=Malcolm Johnson (journalist)|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Hartford Courant]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Johnson continued, \"Every turn of Fiona's head, every glance, every shift of mouth lift character animation to new heights.\"<ref name=\":45\" /> Similarly, the ''[[London Evening Standard]]'' wrote that \"every bright ringlet on Princess Fiona ... the liquefaction flow of her velvet robe, even her skin tones have the feel of organic root, thread or cell.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/film/green-ogre-rips-disney-to-shreds-7433246.html|title=Green ogre rips Disney to shreds|last=|first=|date=June 28, 2001|website=[[London Evening Standard]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Slant Magazine]]''<nowiki/>'s Ed Gonzalez identified Fiona's struggles with [[Self-hatred|self-loathing]] as the film's strongest asset.<ref name=\":33\" /> Reviewing ''Shrek the Third'', ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' film critic [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] described Fiona as \"fabulously resourceful\", identifying the moment she reinvents her princess friends into independent women as the film's sole \"Cool Thing.\"<ref name=\":64\" /> \n\nDiaz has also received positive attention for her voice acting.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":92\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/film-and-television-biographies/cameron-diaz|title=Cameron Diaz: 1972\u2014: Model, actress|last=|first=|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[Encyclopedia.com]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|quote=Besides garnering many rave reviews from critics, Diaz was honored ... for her portrayal of Princess Fiona.}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' film critic [[Desson Howe]] wrote that Diaz's performance offers \"a funny, earthy princess.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/entertainment/movies/reviews/shrekhowe.htm|title='Shrek': A Funny, Fractured Fairy Tale|last=Howe|first=Desson|authorlink=Desson Howe|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> ''GamesRadar+'' wrote Fiona \"nestle[s] comfortably between the movie's storybook style and [[Photorealism|photo-realistic]] convincingness,\" continuing that Diaz's performance \"reinforces her game-for-a-laugh reputation\".<ref name=\":58\" /> Kim Morgan of [[OregonLive.com]] said, \"Diaz's sweet yet tough demeanor shines through all her computer-generated-imagery beauty,\" citing her vulnerability as an asset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/movies/oregonian/index.ssf?/movies/oregonian/al_61fshrk18.frame|title=A romantic leading ogre|last=Morgan|first=Kim|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[OregonLive.com]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010708154405/http://www.oregonlive.com/movies/oregonian/index.ssf?%2Fmovies%2Foregonian%2Fal_61fshrk18.frame|archive-date=July 8, 2001|access-date=September 28, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''<nowiki/>'s film critic [[Andrew O'Hagan]] believes Diaz imbues Fiona with \"easygoing shrillness that modern eight-year-olds may find likeable\",<ref name=\":55\" /> while the ''Deseret News''<nowiki/>' Jeff Vice wrote that Diaz proves more than merely \"a pretty face.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/700002713/Shrek.html|title=Film review: Shrek|last=Vice|first=Jeff|date=August 24, 2004|website=[[Deseret News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Bruce Westbrook of the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'' reviewed Diaz as an improvement upon \"the spunkiness of today's heroines\" by \"packing surprise punches that would have suited her role in ''Charlie's Angels''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/movies/article/Shrek-1527382.php|title=Shrek|last=Westbook|first=Bruce|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[Houston Chronicle]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 4, 2010}}</ref> [[Turner Classic Movies]] believes Diaz's performance earned the actress \"a legion of younger fans\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/50053%7C173505/Cameron-Diaz/biography.html|title=Cameron Diaz \u2013 Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref> a sentiment with which ''[[TV Guide]]'' agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/cameron-diaz/bio/143212/|title=Cameron Diaz \u2013 Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TV Guide]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020|quote=Younger viewers fell for the California beauty ... when she voiced Princess Fiona in the beloved animated fairy tale Shrek and its sequels.}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]''<nowiki/>' Cynthia Fuchs, reviewing the fourth film, described the princess as \"always at least a little wonderful, patient, and smart (and now awesomely Amazonian),\" and found herself wishing Fiona would discover a [[Parallel universes in fiction|parallel universe]] in which she is truly appreciated.<ref name=\":68\" /> \n\nNot all reviews were positive. Finding Fiona's fight scene unnecessary, Derek Armstrong of [[AllMovie]] wrote that it \"leaves things feeling scattershot\" despite its appealing visuals.<ref name=\":78\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/shrek-v242627/review|title=Shrek (2001) \u2013 Review by Derek Armstrong|last=Armstrong|first=Derek|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[AllMovie]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> In a negative review, [[CNN]]'s Paul Tatara dismissed Fiona as \"bland\" and the film's \"only miscue among the characters\".<ref name=\":8\" /> Criticizing her design, Tatara felt the princess \"gives off the creepy air of a possessed [[Barbie doll|Barbie Doll]]\" while \"Diaz's [[Valley girl|California-girl]] line readings simply don't fit the character.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news|last=Tatara|first=Paul|url=http://www.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/05/17/review.shrek/index.html|title=Review: 'Shrek' a wild, enchanted, hilarious tale|date=May 18, 2001|work=|access-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live|website=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Similarly, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''<nowiki/>'s Mark Caro found Fiona's design generic and Barbie-like, but admitted these characteristics benefit the film's plot and themes.<ref name=\":61\" /> Anthony Quinn of ''[[The Independent]]'' found Fiona's realism particularly troubling, suggesting that the animators should have simply \"invite[d] Cameron Diaz to play her as well as voice her.\"<ref name=\":56\" /> Similarly, ''[[The New Yorker]]'' film critic [[Anthony Lane]] felt the character was too realistic, writing, \"What I don't want is to gaze at Princess Fiona ... and wonder if she is supposed to resemble Cameron Diaz\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2001/05/21/fantasy-land|title=Fantasy Land|last=Lane|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Lane|date=May 21, 2001|website=[[The New Yorker]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]], film critic for ''[[The Guardian]]'', dismissed Fiona and the film's human characters as \"disappointingly ordinary looking and unexpressive,\" comparing them to [[Clay animation|claymation]],<ref name=\":57\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2001/jun/29/1|title=Shrek|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Bradshaw|date=June 29, 2001|website=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> while ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]''<nowiki/>'s Peter Rainer agreed that human characters such as Fiona \"are less interesting\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/reviews/4698/|title=Troll on a Roll|last=Rainer|first=Peter|date=2001|website=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> Paul Malcolm of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' described Diaz's performance as \"insuperably flat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/film/trouble-in-fairyland-2133359|title=Trouble in Fairyland|last=Malcolm|first=Paul|date=May 16, 2001|website=[[LA Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> Philippa Hawker of ''[[The Age]]'' felt the third film could benefited from Fiona being named Harold's heir, opposing the idea of relegating her to \"a cursory girl-power scenario\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/shrek-the-third-20070607-ge52kr.html|title=Shrek the Third|last=Hawker|first=Philippa|date=June 7, 2007|website=[[The Age]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Feminist analysis ===\n\nSome media publications have regarded Fiona as a feminist icon.<ref name=\":63\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2007/05/23/shrek-princess-goes-feminist-402110/|title=Shrek princess goes feminist|last=|first=|date=May 23, 2007|website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alloy.com/entertainment/cartoon-feminist-icons/13/|title=18 Cartoon Characters Who Are Actual Feminist Icons|last=Miles|first=Ellie|date=December 1, 2017|website=[[Clevver news|Alloy]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206170529/http://www.alloy.com/entertainment/cartoon-feminist-icons/13/|archive-date=December 6, 2017|access-date=October 3, 2018|quote=If you need reminding why Princess Fiona is a god damn feminist legend, just cast your mind back to the first Shrek film.}}</ref><ref name=\":39\" /><ref name=\":86\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/7776018.stm|title=The sexual revolution... in cartoon form|last=|first=|date=December 11, 2008|work=|access-date=December 23, 2018|website=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> Upon her debut, Fiona was celebrated by most critics \"as a radical new take on the princess myth\".<ref name=\":70\">{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/the-royal-wedding-and-the-lure-of-the-princess-myth-939|title=The royal wedding and the lure of the princess myth|last=Smith|first=Michelle|date=April 28, 2011|website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018|quote=Shrek\u2019s Princess Fiona ... was celebrated as a radical new take on the princess myth}}</ref> Fiona's subversion of common princess tropes continues to be widely discussed in the media.<ref name=\":65\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/movies/2018/3/13/17116436/cameron-diaz-best-performances-shrek-any-given-sunday|title=What Is Cameron Diaz's Best Performance?|last=Herman|first=Alison|date=March 13, 2018|website=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 24, 2018|quote=Fiona subverts the pretty-princess trope enough to provide fuel for undergrad media studies papers for decades to come}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' contributor Claudia Puig felt the first film boasts \"a wonderfully affirming message for girls courtesy of Fiona\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/dreamworks-animation-movies-ranked-best-worst-shrek-panda-dragon/|title=All 34 DreamWorks Animation Movies Ranked From Worst to Best (Photos)|last=Puig|first=Claudia|date=March 30, 2017|website=[[Wired.com|Wired]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Jack Rear, writing for Pretty 52, described Fiona as \"feminism goals\" due to her martial arts proficiency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pretty52.com/stylish/celebrity-adele-clapped-back-at-people-who-compared-her-to-princess-fiona-20170304|title=Adele Clapped Back At People Who Compared Her To Princess Fiona In The Best Way|last=Rear|first=Jack|date=March 4, 2017|website=Pretty 52|access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> ''Affinity Magazine'' contributor Isabel Tovar identified the moment Fiona defeats Monsieur Hood as \"female empowering\", believing \"Fiona has been feminist queen since day one.\"<ref name=\":63\">{{cite web|url=http://culture.affinitymagazine.us/5-moments-that-prove-that-the-shrek-movies-are-the-best/|title=5 Moments That Prove That The Shrek Movies Are The Best|last=Tovar|first=Isabel|date=July 28, 2017|website=Affinity Magazine|access-date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> Teresa Brickey of ''[[The Odyssey Online|The Odyssey]]'' said Fiona contested the [[patriarchy]] by \"accept[ing] her body ... who she loved, and fought for right to do her thing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theodysseyonline.com/dear-kim-kardashian-shrek-is-more-feminist-than-you|title=Shrek Is More Feminist Than Kim Kardashian|last=Brickey|first=Teresa|date=May 30, 2016|website=[[The Odyssey Online|The Odyssey]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Reviewing ''Shrek Forever After'', [[Rachel Giese]] of [[CBC.ca|CBC]] found the character's \"[[Girl power|girl-power]] turn as a warrior princess\" to be one of the installment's most endearing changes.<ref name=\":35\" /> Crowning the character \"the best feminist action hero around\", Emily Shire of ''[[The Week]]'' deemed Fiona \"the kind of feminist action hero movies need more of\", describing her as a strong heroine who \"saves herself and loved ones\" while accepting the \"'ugly' and 'gross' aspects of herself\".<ref name=\":39\">{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/454355/sorry-katniss-princess-fiona-still-best-feminist-action-hero-around#!|title=Sorry Katniss, Princess Fiona is still the best feminist action hero around|last=Shire|first=Emily|date=December 16, 2013|website=[[The Week]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Shire also voiced her preference for Fiona over ''[[The Hunger Games franchise|The Hunger Games]]''<nowiki/>' [[Katniss Everdeen]] and the superheroine [[Wonder Woman]].<ref name=\":39\" /> Allison Maloney of [[The Shriver Report]] shared Shire's sentiments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shriverreport.org/the-best-time-in-history-to-lean-in-princess-fiona-the-role-model-and-the-brand-that-sold-strength-best/|title=The Best Time in History to Lean In, Princess Fiona the Role Model and the Brand That Sold Strength Best|last=Maloney|first=Allison|date=December 20, 2013|website=[[The Shriver Report]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Felicity Sleeman, a writer for ''[[Farrago (magazine)|Farrago]]'', believes \"Fiona completely dispels any misconceptions of the passive princess trope\", citing her as a [[strong female character]] \"able to stand up for herself and fight in ways that would typically be considered masculine.\"<ref name=\":73\">{{cite web|url=http://farragomagazine.com/2016/08/08/in-defense-of-shrek/|title=In Defense Of Shrek|last=Sleeman|first=Felicity|date=August 6, 2016|website=[[Farrago (magazine)|Farrago]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> Sleeman continued that one of the most important components of Fiona's personality \"is that the films don\u2019t ignore or degrade any of her qualities that are considered typically feminine\", elaborating that her struggles over her appearance are \"significant in that it presents the ways in which so many girls are pressured by society to uphold a certain standard of beauty.\" Sleeman concluded, \"In an industry where female characters have so often portrayed as [[Secondary character|secondary characters]] defined by their beauty ... Fiona is a well-rounded character who represents an eclectic mix of traits that are representative of real women\", remaining feminine yet strong.<ref name=\":73\" /> Rachel O'Neill, a writer for ''[[TheJournal.ie|The Daily Edge]]'', identified Fiona as \"the first badass princess ... able to speak for herself\", joking, \"nobody can fling a mermaid quite like Fiona.\"<ref name=\":30\" />\n\nIn 2008, [[BBC News Online|BBC News]] named Fiona \"the next feminist icon\", believing the character retains \"a certain sex appeal which continues even after she changes into an ogre - perfectly underlining how attitudes have changed towards women in the 21st Century.\"<ref name=\":86\" /> ''[[HuffPost]]'' contributor Hayley Krischer cited Fiona as a rare example of a princess who \"br[oke] the mold\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/hayley-krischer/im-a-feminist-momand-my-d_b_998130.html|title=I'm a Feminist Mom \u2014 And My Daughter Loves Princesses|last=Krischer|first=Hayley|date=December 20, 2011|website=[[HuffPost]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Iona Tytler of [[Babe.net]] recognized Fiona among childhood feminist characters \"who got you where you are today\".<ref name=\":94\" /> Praising her independence, Tytler said Fiona \"overc[ame] the societal prejudice in her world that came with being an ogre\" while becoming \"more comfortable in her own skin.\"<ref name=\":94\">{{cite web|url=https://babe.net/2016/10/22/every-feminist-character-childhood-got-today-898|title=The feminist characters from your childhood who got you where you are today|last=Tytler|first=Iona|date=October 22, 2016|website=[[Babe.net]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> Sarah Tutton, curator of the [[Australian Centre for the Moving Image]]'s DreamWorks exhibit, credits Fiona with \"br[eaking] the mould of the helpless princess,\" citing her as a modern-day feminist.<ref name=\":44\" /> Tutton also said the character \"completely subverts what it means to be a beautiful princess.\"<ref name=\":44\" /> ''Forbes'' contributor Dani Di Placido believes Fiona embodied characteristics associated with the unconventional, rebellious warrior princess several years before such traits became standard in film and television.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danidiplacido/2018/08/24/nobody-knows-what-to-do-with-fairytale-princesses/#3870b6507277|title=Fairytale Princesses Are In A Strange Place Right Now|last=Di Placido|first=Dani|date=August 24, 2018|website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> Similarly, the [[British Film Institute]]'s So Mayer wrote that heroines such as [[Merida (Disney)|Merida]] and [[Elsa (Frozen)|Elsa]] from Disney's ''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]'' (2012) and ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' (2013), respectively, were both \"late to the party compared to\" Fiona, reflecting, \"over the course of the trilogy she wanders the wilderness, turns down Lord Farquaad, survives imprisonment, decides she prefers being ogre to being human, and organises a resistance composed of fairytale princesses.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/news-bfi/list/feminist-guide-love-screen-list|title=The feminist's guide to love on screen: a list|last=Mayer|first=So|date=January 11, 2018|website=[[British Film Institute]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 27, 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, ''Female Action Heroes: A Guide to Women in Comics, Video Games, Film, and Television'' author Gladys L. Knight wrote that Fiona challenged the manner in which medieval women are portrayed on screen.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Knight|first=Gladys L.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0PKSFHwhTGYC&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=action+hero+princess+fiona#v=onepage&q=action%20hero%20princess%20fiona&f=false|title=Female Action Heroes: A Guide to Women in Comics, Video Games, Film, and Television|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|year=2010|isbn=9780313376122|location=United States|page=176|pages=|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Mary Zeiss Stange, author of ''Encyclopedia of Women in Today's World, Volume 1'', cited Fiona as an example of an \"outstanding female action hero\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bOkPjFQoBj8C&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=action+hero+princess+fiona#v=onepage&q=action%20hero%20princess%20fiona&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Women in Today's World, Volume 1|last=Stange|first=Mary Zeiss|last2=Sloan|first2=Jane E.|last3=Oyster|first3=Carol K.|publisher=SAGE|year=2011|isbn=9781412976855|volume=1|location=United States|page=19|via=Google Books}}</ref>''[[Refinery29|Refinery 29]]''<nowiki/>'s Anne Cohen felt Fiona remains a strong heroine despite ''Shrek''<nowiki/>'s \"un-feminist plot\" featuring several men making decisions about her future without her involvement.<ref name=\":84\" /> Cohen praised Fiona for defending herself, defying stereotypes, speaking her mind and accepting her own flaws.<ref name=\":84\" /> Crowing Fiona an \"important cultural milestone\", the author concluded that she is \"fierce, honest [and] wonderful\" despite her unconventional appearance.<ref name=\":84\" /> \n\nSome critics felt Fiona's fighting prowess was otherwise undermined by her insecurities and motivations. Despite being impressed with the character's fighting ability, Furniss believes this contradicts with \"her need to seek authentication from a male romantic partner\", arguing that a true martial artist would few have concerns about outward appearance.<ref name=\":17\" /> Although acknowledging that the film demonstrates themes of [[inner beauty]] among \"women of all types\", the author argued that Fiona's understanding relies on male approval, referring to her relationships with both Farquaad and Shrek, and further observing that she struggles to use this same martial arts prowess to fend off Farquaad's guards.<ref name=\":17\" /> Furniss found it disappointing that her arc is \"activated by the kiss of a man\", but admitted the completion of Shrek's character development is similarly determined by him kissing Fiona.<ref name=\":17\" /> Furniss doubts Fiona would not have been able to accept her ogre form had Shrek decided to retreat to his swamp alone after kissing her.<ref name=\":17\" /> Author Margot Mifflin, writing for ''[[Salon magazine|Salon]]'', felt that some of Fiona's actions contradict with the film's morals about looks being less important, citing that she dislikes Farquaad more for his short stature than his cruelty towards others.<ref name=\":32\" /> She also found the princess in Steig's original story to be more [[Women's Liberation|liberated]] and less of a damsel in distress than Fiona.<ref name=\":32\" /> Despite describing the character's ogre form as \"an overfed [[Cabbage patch Doll|Cabbage Patch]] doll with the drowning eyes and apologetic expression of a [[Hummel figurines|Hummel figurine]]\", Mifflin found the fact that Fiona remains an ogre, fights, talks back and has more realistic [[body proportions]] to be ground-breaking, while describing her musical solo as one of the film's \"hilarious\" highlights.<ref name=\":32\" /> ''[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]''<nowiki/>'s Michelle Smith was unimpressed, writing that despite the character's fighting skills, Fiona remains \"desperate to follow the fairy tale script\" and believes marrying her rescuer is \"her ultimate reward\".<ref name=\":70\" />\n\n=== Recognition ===\n\nFiona was celebrated as a positive role model by the [[Girl Scouts of the USA]],<ref name=\":92\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cinema.com/news/item/4096/camerons-princess-is-girl-scouts-poster-girl.phtml|title=Cameron's Princess Is Girl Scout's Poster Girl|last=|first=|date=May 22, 2001|website=Cinema.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> who used the character's likeness in several [[tie-in]] media to promote the organization's \"Issues for Girl Scouts\" movement and encourage \"girls to develop self-confidence and embrace diversity.\"<ref name=\":93\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2001/05/25/shrek-inspires-girl-scouts-girls-are-great-badges/|title=Shrek inspires Girl Scouts' ''Girls are great!'' badges|last=Lee|first=Alice M.|date=May 25, 2001|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The organization also hosted a free screening of the film in 2001, which was attended by an audience of 340.<ref name=\":93\" /> For her performance in ''Shrek'', Diaz won a [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kid's Choice Award]] for Best Burp,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/cameron-diaz-actress-vol-57-no-18/feed/|title=Cameron Diaz: Actress|last=|first=|date=May 13, 2002|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> which the actress claims to be one of her greatest achievements.<ref name=\":9\" /> According to Daniel Kurland of [[Screen Rant]], Diaz \"remains a crucial component of what makes the movie work\" despite resembling an \"unsung hero\" throughout the franchise.<ref name=\":12\" /> Summarizing the actress' career, Kendall Fisher of [[E!|''E! Online'']] said Diaz \"voiced one of our favorite animated characters\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/ca/news/876836/cameron-diaz-turns-45-looking-back-at-her-impressive-career-evolution-from-the-mask-to-annie|title=Cameron Diaz Turns 45: Looking Back at Her Impressive Career Evolution From The Mask to Annie|last=Fisher|first=Kendall|date=August 30, 2017|website=[[E! Online]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]]'' ranked Shrek Diaz's best film, believing her performance as Fiona aged better than the film's [[Shrek Soundtrack|soundtrack]] and animation.<ref name=\":65\" /> Author Alison Herman elaborated that Fiona embraced her flaws and offered children \"an important lesson in both self-esteem and the comedic value of fart jokes\", while the actress \"holds her own against\" Myers and Murphy; \"as a character, Fiona subverts the pretty-princess trope enough to provide fuel for undergrad media studies papers for decades to come\".<ref name=\":65\" />\n\n''Marie Claire'' ranked Fiona Diaz's third best \"Movie Moments That Made Us Fall In Love With Her\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marieclaire.co.uk/entertainment/tv-and-film/cameron-s-best-on-screen-moments-35410|title=The Cameron Diaz Movie Moments That Made Us Fall In Love With Her|last=|first=|date=December 5, 2014|website=[[Marie Claire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 3, 2018}}</ref> In addition to ranking Fiona the fourth best role of Diaz's career following her retirement in 2018, Samarth Goyal of the ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' crowned Fiona \"one of the most loved animated characters of the 21st century\", crediting her with making Diaz \"a big star.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/there-s-something-about-cameron-diaz-here-s-looking-at-five-of-her-best-films/story-WrUssDa4GUo3alu5Gq57AK.html|title=There's something about Cameron Diaz: Here's looking at five of her best films|last=Goyal|first=Samarth|date=April 3, 2018|website=[[Hindustan Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> In 2011, ''[[Gulf News]]'' ranked Diaz among \"Hollywood's A-list of most popular voice actors\",<ref name=\":13\" /> with ''Forbes'' reporting in 2010 that the actress was mentioned in the media approximately 1,809 times while promoting the most recent ''Shrek'' film.<ref name=\":21\" /> ''[[Teen Vogue]]'' considered Fiona among the \"17 Best Princesses in Movies and TV\", praising the character for learning \"to love herself.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/best-princesses-movie-tv|title=17 Best Princesses in Movies and TV|last=McGrath|first=Justine|date=|website=[[Teen Vogue]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 20, 2018}}</ref> [[NBC New York]]'s Bryan Alexander described Fiona as \"the world's hottest ogre\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Why-Fiona-Taking-Her-Hair-Down-Is-a-Really-Big-Deal-94165809.html|title=Cameron Diaz's Ogre Hair Style Took a Team of 20 for \"Shrek\"|last=Alexander|first=Bryan|date=May 18, 2010|website=[[NBC New York]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref> while [[Stephen Hunter]], film critic for ''The Washington Post'', found hearing Diaz's voice from a computer-animated character \"kind of hot\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/entertainment/movies/reviews/shrekhunter.htm|title='Shrek' Is a Fractured Fairy Tale With Its Heart Firmly in Place|last=Hunter|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Hunter|date=May 18, 2001|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 1, 2018}}</ref> To promote ''Shrek 2'', ice cream restaurant [[Baskin-Robbins]] named a flavor after the character, entitled Fiona's Fairytale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2004-05-19/lifestyle/0405170358_1_princess-fiona-green-ketchup-mms|title=It's Easy Being Green|last=Goldberg|first=Carole|date=May 19, 2004|website=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> Described as \"pink and purple swirled\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.restaurantnewsresource.com/article11004.html|title=Baskin-Robbins Unveils Several Enchanting 'Shrek 2' Ice Cream Creations|last=|first=|date=May 19, 2004|website=Restaurant News Resource|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> the ice cream was [[cotton candy]]-flavored.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2004-05-14-0405150020-story.html|title='Shrek' message, marketing remain the same|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2004|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwitimes.com/entertainment/despite-what-kermit-says-shrek-is-cool-with-his-color/article_1ee00456-d27d-5dc5-b129-21def658a146.html|title=Despite what Kermit says, Shrek is cool with his color|last=Goldberg|first=Carol|date=May 23, 2004|website=[[NWI Times]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Shrek}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fiona, Princess}}\n[[Category:Animated human characters]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Ted Elliott and Terry Rossio]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Female characters in film]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Fictional female martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional ogres]]\n[[Category:Fictional princesses]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Martial artists characters in films]]\n[[Category:Shrek characters]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures cartoons and characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional feminist characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional shapeshifters]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:c4c:bd00:15a7:ad47:fd7:992e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(It\u2019s very good)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princess_Fiona"}
